<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Russian deputies to lay claim to Crimea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Russian parliament is expected today to revoke the 1954 gift of Crimea
to Ukraine.
Mr Vladimir Podoprigora, deputy chairman of the parliament's committee for
relations with former Soviet republics, said most parliamentary factions
were prepared to vote 'yes' on the proposal.
The much-postponed resolution decrees that Khrushchev's decision to transfer
Crimea from Russia to Ukraine was unconstitutional.
Mr Leonid Kravchuk, the Ukrainian president, condemned the proposal and said
it would further undermine relations with Russia.
'Ukraine has not passed a single political resolution which interferes in
the domestic affairs of Russia,' he said.
Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, chairman of the Russian parliament, sought to
reassure Ukraine that Russia's review of the 1954 transfer was a matter of
historic justice not a territorial claim, but Mr Kravchuk dismissed this
justification. 'This is a question of justice from the Russian point of view
but if we are to follow this logic then all unjust acts must be reversed
beginning with 1917 or even earlier.'
Mr Kravchuk accused the Russian parliament of violating international law
and ignoring political reality.
Mr Podoprigora denied the vote would mean Russia reclaiming Crimea, since
both countries remained bound by an agreement not to seek border changes as
long as they remained part of the Commonwealth.
But whatever the rhetoric of some deputies and Russian nationalists, the
Russian leadership has good reason to preserve the status quo. By reclaiming
Crimea, Russia would create a precedent for territorial claims by others on
its land.
In Simferopol, the Crimean parliament backed away from confrontation with
Ukraine yesterday by repealing an act of independence passed last month.
</TEXT>
