<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Danes split evenly over Maastricht treaty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LESS THAN a fortnight before Denmark holds a binding referendum to approve
or reject the Maastricht treaty on European union, the most recent opinion
poll has indicated that 41 per cent of voters are against the treaty.
According to a Gallup Poll published yesterday, only 39 per cent of Danes
are firmly in favour of the treaty while the remainder are not likely to
vote or are still undecided.
The Gallup Institute points out that the gap between those against the
treaty and those in favour is so narrow that statistically the difference is
not significant.
This is the third Gallup Poll this month and all three have shown a small
majority in favour of rejecting the treaty.
Denmark will be the first of the EC countries to approve or reject
Maastricht, and only one other country, Ireland, will be holding a
referendum.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
