<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / London Stock Exchange: Stocks boosted by KIO stake talk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANY FEELING that the sunshine might draw dealers away from their trading
screens was dispelled yesterday, as London stocks received a boost from what
many in the market discounted as no more than rumour, and remained
surprisingly firm all day.
The FT-SE 100 Index was marked up at the opening and rose sharply in the
morning to show a gain of 24.4 points, before slipping to a close of
2,711.9, up a net 11.3, but with no sign that it will stumble in the next
few days.
It was helped by a strong close on Wall Street overnight and a clutch of
well-received company results. However, its first kick-start of the day came
from rumours that the Kuwait Investment Office (KIO) was about to sell its
9.8 per cent stake in BP to Lord Hanson.
The idea that Hanson might bid for BP has been talked up and knocked down
for some time, but the possibility that the KIO might sell its stake,
amounting to more than 500m shares, gave a new twist to an old story. BP
rose 10p initially but analysts pointed out that the shares had
underperformed the market significantly since the general election.
Some pinpointed the derivatives markets as the source of the talk and,
certainly, the Footsie future for June delivery traded at a significant
premium to its estimated fair value throughout the day.
As the BP impetus faded, the market began to look at the UK retail sales for
April, which were higher than the weak March figure but slightly off the 1.1
per cent rise expected.
Traders also looked towards the opening on Wall Street. Although the Dow had
reached a record peak at the previous close, some felt it could move higher
on hopes that the Federal Reserve would cut the discount rate. Others argued
that a huge issue of new General Motors shares would hold back the Dow.
The Footsie ticked back from its mid-morning high of 2,725, affected partly
by an overhang of stock in Argyll, a profits warning from Ranks Hovis
McDougall, and fears that Sun Alliance would offload its stake in Commercial
Union.
When it opened, New York gave no clear direction but the Footsie was strong
enough to hold on to a gain of around 10 points. Buying by overseas
institutions was still evident even though London had to compete with strong
demand in most of the other European markets. Traders added that the buyers
were matched by a wall of reluctant sellers.
Individual stocks providing support included Bass, with good results, and
well-received figures from Land Securities. Elsewhere, the pound was steady
and gilts were firm.
Turnover of shares, which many had expected to drift, was a solid 598.7m,
compared with Tuesday's 565.4m. The volume was helped by two medium-sized
programme trades, but it still indicated that the value of genuine customer
retail business would be higher than Tuesday's Pounds 992m.
Hopes that the Federal Reserve would reduce the discount rate remained
unfulfilled and the Footsie June future slipped back slightly in
after-hours' trading. However, dealers were convinced that the London market
had not reached a ceiling.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
