<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow eases in absence of Fed
move on rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARES turned slightly lower following signs from the Federal Reserve
that monetary policy would remain on hold, at least for another day, writes
Karen Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average crossed the 3,400 level at 11.30am, by
adding a mere 2.93 points, but it failed to hang on to its slim gain and
ended 4.15 down on balance at 3,393.84.
New York SE turnover, which has been thin in recent weeks, was moderate with
198.7m shares changing hands. Declining issues narrowly exceeded advances by
861 to 820. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 slipped 0.98 to 415.39, but the Nasdaq
composite of over-the-counter stocks added 2.24 at 580.29.
On Tuesday, the Dow climbed 21.96 to a record close of 3,397.99, assisted by
widespread speculation that a surprisingly sharp drop in April's US housing
starts would prompt the Fed to ease monetary policy.
Share prices turned lower shortly after the Fed failed to intervene in the
open market, which was taken as a sign that it did not intend to reduce
interest rates. The Fed often signals a change in monetary policy through
its open market operations.
A large offering by General Motors on Tuesday also put pressure on prices.
The company's global public offering of 55m shares were priced at Dollars 39
apiece through underwriters led by Morgan Stanley. The company, which has
said it would use the proceeds to improve liquidity and its balance sheet,
had increased the size of the offering from 50m. GM eased Dollars  1/4 to
Dollars 39.
Of the other big US auto makers, Chrysler softened Dollars  1/8 to Dollars
18 1/2 and Ford lost Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 44 1/4 .
Humana tumbled Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 23 in active trading after the
company warned that a decline in hospital admissions and heavy discounting
might cut into its third-quarter profits. It has projected earnings of less
than 50 cents a share in the quarter, compared with 64 cents a year earlier.
In the department store sector, Dayton Hudson advanced Dollars 2 3/8 to
Dollars 64 5/8 , adding to its Dollars 3 5/8 gain on Tuesday which followed
news of first-quarter net income of 40 cents a share, against 39 cents a
year earlier. Dean Witter Reynolds has added the issue to its recommended
list and increased its rating on the stock to 'buy'.
A number of blue chip stocks were prominent among the most active issues on
the NYSE, including Walt Disney, down Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 39 1/4 ,
McDonalds, up Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 46 1/8 , and Coca-Cola, off Dollars
3/4 to Dollars 44 3/8 .
On the Nasdaq market, Intel led trading, rising Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 47
7/8 . QVC Network jumped Dollars 2 1/8 to a 52-week high of Dollars 20 5/8
on news of first-quarter net earnings from operations of 29 cents a share,
compared with 5 cents a share on fewer shares outstanding a year earlier.
An initial public offering of 2.2m shares in Holson Burnes was priced at
Dollars 14, and the stock traded at Dollars 14 3/8, up Dollars 3/8.
Canada
TORONTO shadowed Wall Street to end slightly down as many investors remained
on the sidelines awaiting further news on possible cuts in US and Canadian
interest rates.
The market is still hoping for a reduction in the US discount rate and a
lowering of Canadian prime rates. Some traders said an expected 13
basis-point fall in today's Bank of Canada key lending rate could lead to a
round of  1/4 percentage point prime lending rate cuts by leading Canadian
banks.
The composite index finished 4.1 lower at 3,381.2 and declines outscored
rises by 314 to 246, with 251 issues unchanged. Volume came to 26.7m shares.
</TEXT>
