<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Money Markets: Cash trading quiet
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE-MONTH money ended slightly softer in the sterling cash markets
yesterday, as traders anticipated smaller shortages in forthcoming weeks.
But the market was quiet, and closing figures in the cash and futures
markets ended mostly unchanged.
Yet more hints that a cut in base rates is unlikely over the summer led to a
quiet market. In a speech to the annual dinner of the CBI on Tuesday night,
the chancellor of the exchequer said that Britain should aim to match
Japan's inflation performance if it wants to be 'a first-rank commercial
power'.
That was compounded by the Bank of England's statement in its quarterly
bulletin that the Maastricht criteria relating to inflation and interest
rates will be met by 'a continuation of the present counter-inflationary
stance of policy'.
As a result, period rates were mostly unchanged. One-month money ended the
day at 10 per cent, down  1/16 on the previous day's close. But three-month
money, an important indicator of where the market thinks rates are moving,
remained unchanged at 10 per cent.
On the sterling futures market, there was also little change. The June short
sterling contract closed at 89.98, up one tick on the day after very low
volume. That closing price suggests that three-month LIBOR in a month's time
will be at 10.02 per cent.
In its money market operations, the Bank of England found that players were
again unwilling to offer paper. With a bank holiday weekend approaching, the
market is probably waiting until tomorrow to take up the shortage in the
hope of pushing the overnight rate down over a three-day weekend.
The Bank purchased Pounds 30m of Band-1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent and
Pounds 11m of Band-2 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent. In the afternoon, the
Bank purchased Pounds 100m of Band-1 Treasury bills at 9 7/8 per cent,
Pounds 267m of Band-1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent and Pounds 35m of Band-2
bills at 9 7/8 per cent. It offered late assistance of Pounds 610m.
In Germany, the Bundesbank drained DM4.2bn from the banking system with
yesterday's repurchase agreements. It allocated DM29.7bn of 27-day funds,
mostly at 9.65 per cent, and DM9.6bn of 56-day money, mostly at 9.65 per
cent.
</TEXT>
