<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Saudi oil minister fails to
turn up at Opec summit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR HISHAM NAZER, the Saudi Arabian oil minister, yesterday failed to turn up
at the ministerial summit of the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting
Countries in Vienna. Other delegations were surprised and disconcerted, but
the Saudis said it signalled no change in the kingdom's oil policy.
A Saudi delegate said Mr Nazer was simply 'a little bit exhausted' after an
intensive series of overseas meetings.
Some oil analysts suggested that Mr Nazer's absence, his first from an Opec
meeting since he replaced Sheikh Yamani as the kingdom's oil minister in
1987, could be interpreted as a 'slight' towards delegations favouring a
higher-price Opec policy.
However, diplomats in Riyadh who met Mr Nazer yesterday said they believed
he was genuinely overtired. The diplomats said that there was no indication
that Mr Nazer's post as oil minister was threatened, or that his absence
indicated a shift in oil policy by Riyadh.
Mr Nazer's place at the summit was taken by Mr Fayez Badr, a minister of
state with responsibility for the Saudi Ports Authority and a man with no
obvious oil expertise.
Saudi Arabia has widely flagged before the Opec summit, which begins in
earnest today, that it would be seeking a 1m barrels a day rise in the
cartel's production ceiling for the third quarter from the 22.98m b/d agreed
for the second quarter in February.
Iran, among several other delegations, opposes such a move and would prefer
to see Opec restrain output to force prices towards the cartel's formal
reference price of Dollars 21 a barrel. Mr Gholamreza Agazadeh, Iran's oil
minister, told reporters curtly yesterday: 'I want a cut in the ceiling.'
Saudi Arabia estimates the call on Opec crude to reach 24.2m b/d for the
third quarter, but actual production for the second has neared 23.5m b/d
rather than the nominal February figure, largely because of Kuwait's
accelerated output and a Saudi refusal to cut production below 8m b/d - as
it was notionally allocated.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
