<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Construction Contracts: Managing health care in
Czechoslovakia
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
HEWLETT-PACKARD has been selected as the prime vendor by Universal Health
Insurance Company (VZP) to set up computer systems to handle health care for
the Czech republic. The value of the contract is estimated at USDollars
10.5m (Pounds 5.83m).
VZP, which was established late last year by the Czech National Council, is
to replace the previous 'no-cost' centralized health care model of the Czech
republic. Sister republic Slovakia is expected to set up its own health care
system in the near future.
The planned HP open systems-based computers will be installed at VZP
headquarters in Prague and at 75 branch offices within the Czech republic.
Beginning in the second half of 1992, the system will handle all payments to
doctors, hospitals and pharmacies. Record keeping for the 10m eligible
insured persons and the collection of insurance premium payments will begin
officially at the start of 1993.
The HP computing systems, which are adjustable to meet the computing needs
of the individual branch offices, will include a client/server configuration
using HP's Precision Architecture RISC-based HP 9000 Series 800 business
servers, HP-UX Unix-based operating system, personal computers, data
terminals and printers.
The system will offer the ORACLE relational database management system as
well as applications software developed by APP Systems, a Czech software
developer.
The first HP computers are already being installed for applications testing,
with the bulk of the systems scheduled to be installed in the second half of
this year.
