<TEXT>
ROYAL BANK of Canada and National Bank of Canada are having their credit
ratings reviewed for possible downgrading in the wake of the bankruptcy
filings by Olympia &amp; York, the Canadian-based property company, writes Simon
London.
However, Standard &amp; Poor's, the US credit rating agency, said it had
affirmed the credit ratings of Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, Bank of
Montreal, Bank of Nova Scotia and Toronto-Dominion Bank.
S&amp;P said the problems of O&amp;Y 'underscored the likelihood that property
markets worldwide will continue to experience high office vacancy rates and
diminishing underlying property values.' That set of circumstances would
have a negative impact on the banks' assets quality, S&amp;P added.
The ratings under review are RBC's AA long term senior debt rating, and the
NBC's A1 commercial paper rating.
</TEXT>
