<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAF4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / International Capital Markets: Westpac puts brave face on
losses - The impact of a bank's pessimistic view of the Australian economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS precious little sign of Australia's long-awaited economic recovery
in the massive losses announced yesterday by Westpac Banking Corporation,
the country's largest bank in terms of assets.
The level of Westpac's write-offs and problem loan disclosure reflects an
extremely pessimistic view of the Australian economy, precisely at a time
when some encouraging recovery signs are beginning to emerge.
The bank has not only written down the bulk of its property portfolio by
more than a third, but has also virtually doubled its problem loan
provisioning.
Westpac's brutal accounting treatment also throws down the gauntlet to its
competitors in an Australian banking industry still wracked by a 1980's
lending spree to the country's remarkable crop of failed entrepreneurs;
notably Mr Alan Bond, Mr Christopher Skase and Mr John Spalvins.
National Australia Bank is due to report interim results today, followed by
ANZ next week. However, widely varying write-off and provisioning approaches
have long been a feature of the Australian banking industry.
Westpac's action suggests that anything less dramatic by rival banks may
mean that they will meet stock market disapproval. In its latest full year,
National wrote off Dollars A955m (USDollars 729) in bad loans and raised
problem loan provisions to Dollars A3.9bn while corresponding figures for
the ANZ were Dollars A1.04bn and Dollars A3.6bn.
The stock market is likely to demand much more 'blood on the floor,' mindful
that on an international scale, the Australian banks can afford bigger
write-offs. They enjoy comfortable capital adequacy ratios, especially the
all important Tier 1 measure.
Even after yesterday's deck-clearing, Westpac is claiming a Tier 1 ratio of
5 per cent against the 4 per cent minimum demanded under central bank
regulations. National boasted a Tier 1 ratio of 7.6 at the end of last year,
with ANZ on 6 per cent.
Even so, Westpac's decision not to have it's ADollars 1.2bn rights issue
underwritten was surprising; especially in the light of some worrying
information buried in the fine print of yesterday's announcement.
The fine print showed that the big write-downs have reduced the company's
net asset backing from Dollars A5.66 to Dollars A3.75 a share, but 74 cents
of that valuation is in future income tax benefits which are not allowable
for capital adequacy purposes.
As a consequence, on a strict interpretation, Westpac's asset backing is
perilously close to the Dollars A3 price of the rights issue. The shares
closed at Dollars A3.89 in Sydney yesterday.
Westpac's managing director Mr Frank Conroy put a brave face on the results
yesterday, pointing to an improvement in core profitably. He noted that
operating earnings before tax totalled Dollars A687m in the latest half.
Although that was a decline on the Dollars A892m recorded for the
corresponding six months of last year, it was higher than the Dollars A655m
earned for the second half of 1990-91.
Mr Conroy said that the bank did not expect any negative response from the
ratings agencies, and shortly afterwards Moody's confirmed all Westpac's
ratings. 'We do anticipate a positive reaction as we proceed with the
capital raising and the bank's performance continues to improve'.
'I want the market and the media to have no misunderstanding on the
following points: I can assure proprietors, staff and customers that our
reviews have been thorough and conservative. The bank is sound, and what we
are reporting today will increase our financial strength. We expect a sound
profit in the second half and we can look forward to the future with
confidence,' Mr Conroy said.
Analysts, however, were less than happy last night as they digested the
enormous breadth and impact of the Westpac statement. Some were puzzled that
the property exposure involved properties with a book value of Dollars
A6.3bn. Some analysts' estimates put Westpac's total property exposure in
excess of ADollars 12bn.
Much of Westpac's property exposure is held through the Australian Guarantee
Corporation (AGC) subsidiary which made a loss of Dollars A719m and has
necessitated an Dollars A850m capital injection from the parent.
Mr Conroy said that AGC's affect on the group was actually more serious than
it appeared on paper because a number of the finance arm's problems had been
transferred to the bank.
'If you include Bill Acceptance Corporation, Westpac General Finance in the
UK, and the cost of the support arrangements from the bank, AGC and its
related activities accounted for Dollars A1.1bn of the Dollars A1.67bn group
half-year loss,' he said.
He added that the bank would reduce AGC's exposure to major property
developments and would turn its attention to specialist activities. Mr
Conroy's final comments on AGC underlined, if they did not understate, the
plight of the entire group. 'Of course mistakes have been made,' he said.
'Hopefully we have learnt from them.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
