<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / International Company News: Sega lifts profits and increases
dividend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SEGA Enterprises, the video game and toy maker, doubled profits to Y33.5bn
(Dollars 251.87m) for the year to end-March. Unlike most Japanese companies,
it sharply increased its dividend.
Comparisons are made difficult by a change in the company's accounting year,
but sales rose from Y106.6bn to Y213.3bn on strong demand for Sega games in
the US.
After-tax profit was dragged down to Y14bn by the settlement of a US patent
dispute over image-display technology, which resulted in the company writing
off Dollars 28.67m of the agreed Dollars 43m payout to a US inventor.
The only other disappointment was the impact of the Tokyo share price
collapse on short-term holdings of stocks, which are showing unrealised
losses of Y235.8m, up from Y25.5m at the end of March last year. The
increase came in spite of the company almost halving its short-term holdings
to Y1.35bn.
Even though Sega apparently paid the Dollars 28.67m out of its cash
reserves, these rose, from Y29bn to Y72.5bn, following a surge in US sales
during the Christmas period, when it took market share from the industry
leader, Nintendo.
Yesterday's results came as Sega of America, the US subsidiary of the parent
company, and Sony Electronic Publishing announced a marketing agreement.
Under the deal, Sony will produce and market Sega video games and
interactive entertainment, Reuters reports. Sony Electronic will develop
games for all Sega cartridge-based platforms. The deal also provides
opportunities for the development of Sega titles through Sony Pictures
Entertainment and Sony Music Entertainment.
</TEXT>
