<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR CONRAD BLACK, chairman of the Daily Telegraph group, yesterday informed
trade union leaders at the New York Daily News that he would want to cut 700
jobs if he acquired the newspaper.
Mr George McDonald, president of the Allied Printing Trades Council, a
coalition of nine unions, said representatives of Mr Black mentioned the
prospective job cuts at a 'get-to-know-you meeting.'
Mr John Campi, spokesman for the Daily News, said that Mr Black on Tuesday
submitted a bid for the famous New York tabloid acquired last year by the
late Mr Robert Maxwell. The bid was believed to be for Dollars 75m (Pounds
42m).
Mr McDonald seemed untroubled by the job cuts mentioned by Mr Black's
representatives. 'It's just a proposal. They'll say it's negotiable,
otherwise we can't do business. Black wants the paper and we want our jobs,'
he said.
The unions gave up about 800 jobs last year when Mr Maxwell acquired the
paper.
Mr Mortimer Zuckerman, publisher of US News and World Report, is another
prospective buyer of the Daily News.
