<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / International Company News: Toray slides despite improved
fibre sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TORAY Industries, Japan's leading synthetic fibre maker, yesterday posted
falls in consolidated earnings for the full year to March. It blamed
sluggish demand for its synthetic fibres, and lower profits at its
construction affiliate, writes Emiko Terazono in Tokyo.
Pre-tax profits fell 11.4 per cent to Y64bn (Dollars 481.20m) on a 6.5 per
cent rise in total sales, to Y976.7bn. After-tax profits fell 26.2 per cent
to Y27.7bn.
The company's fibre sales grew 10.1 per cent to Y489.9bn. However, the
company said demand for nylon used in tyre cords and fishing nets declined.
Sales of chemicals and new businesses declined 0.5 per cent and 2.4 per cent
respectively.
Nylon resin sales slowed because of sluggish demand from the automotive and
electronic industries. Polyester film sales also decreased because of low
demand and increasing price competition from film for magnetic tapes and
industrial materials.
Sales of the housing and engineering division rose 7.8 per cent to Y219bn,
but operating profits fell 3.2 per cent to Y7.6bn.
