<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / International Company News: O&amp;Y in talks on tax payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; York has funnelled so much cash out of its profitable US buildings
in recent months that it has asked authorities in New York for temporary
relief on municipal tax payments which fall due on July 1.
O&amp;Y said yesterday it was exploring 'options' with the New York City
administration, and was likely to reach an agreement in the next week.
About USDollars 75m in property tax payments fall due on July 1. Although
only four of O&amp;Y's 12 New York buildings have cash flow problems, the
company has diverted every spare dollar from its US operations to the
cash-starved Canadian parent and the Canary Wharf project in London.
O&amp;Y hopes that last week's Ontario court order, which freezes its Canadian
debt obligations under the Companies' Creditors Arrangements Act (CCAA),
will give it sufficient breathing space to replenish the coffers of its US
operations. Its ability to do so partly depends on petitions to be brought
by bondholders in the Ontario Court of Justice today to exclude some of the
developer's most prized Canadian buildings from the CCAA order.
The bondholders' move to reverse the order has wide implications for all
forms of non-recourse finance. The bonds were issued by single-purpose
companies with no recourse to O&amp;Y Developments, the parent. The bondholders
had previously assumed that they would be insulated from the parent's
liquidity crisis.
The bondholders will argue that their claims should be separated from those
of O&amp;Y's other creditors and that they should be at liberty, if necessary,
to seize rents from the buildings to cover overdue debt-service payments.
The CCAA order issued last week covers a total of 28 entities besides the
parent company. They include First Canadian Place, O&amp;Y's 72-storey flagship
in Toronto, as well as other buildings in Toronto, Calgary and Ottawa.
The application is likely to be opposed by O&amp;Y's bank lenders, whose claims
on the projects in question generally rank behind the bondholders.
However, some of the banks which provided a Dollars 2.5bn jumbo loan to O&amp;Y
are expected to raise concerns of their own about the CCAA order. The banks
contend that the order in its present form permits O&amp;Y to channel surplus
cash from its Canadian assets to the US and UK operations, which have not
been brought under court protection.
The banks will also mount a separate court challenge today against the
amount of collateral provided by the developer to its Canadian lenders. The
international group is seeking to assert its rights to the security pledged
on a Dollars 100m loan advanced earlier this year by four Canadian banks.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
</PAGE>
