<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE OPERATING profits for Berliner Handels-und Frankfurter Bank, the
Frankfurt-based merchant bank, advanced 30 per cent in the first four months
of the current year compared with the previous corresponding period.
Partial operating profits - excluding the contribution from trading -
increased by 21.5 per cent, Mr Klaus Subjetzki, outgoing senior partner,
told the bank's annual meeting.
Total assets climbed by 5.2 per cent to DM28.1bn (Dollars 17.6bn), while
interest income was up 5.5 per cent and commission income up 20 per cent.
The results are in line with strong results from other German banks which
have also reported good figures for the early part of the current year.
The results follow a record year for the German banking sector and suggest
that there has been only a moderate slowdown in loan demand in spite of a
sharp downturn in German economic activity.
The sector is also benefiting from a recent improvement in conditions in the
domestic stock market.
