FT  21 MAY 92 / UK Company News: US buyer for ASH's surveillance division
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUTOMATED Security (Holdings), which supplies burglar alarms and other
security products, is selling its electronic and television surveillance
wing to a US company for Pounds 150m.
The loss prevention business, which includes till monitoring to prevent
theft by shop staff and the new TVX system using a tiny video camera, is
being sold to Sensormatic, a supplier of electronic security systems listed
on the New York stock exchange.
It is acquiring a business that made Pounds 11.1m trading profit last year
on sales of Pounds 60.2m. Net assets before the deduction of borrowings were
Pounds 68.5m in November. It is being sold debt-free.
ASH previously tried to float off this wing. More recently, it tried to sell
part of the leasing portfolio to reduce debt. The cash consumptive nature of
the business had raised concern among analysts.
Mr Tom Buffett, chairman, said the sale would wipe out the group's debt and
'take away balance sheet concerns'.
At the end of November, ASH's net borrowings were Pounds 95m. The group
still has about Pounds 60m of convertible capital bonds.
ASH made Pounds 23.2m pre-tax profit last year and the first fall in 19
years came as a shock to the market, further undermining the share price.
This had fallen from more than 300p two years ago to 81p in March. The
recovery continued yesterday with an 11p rise, though the announcement did
not come until after the market closed.
ASH's remaining security systems business made a trading profit of Pounds
35.1m on sales of Pounds 119m last year. The deal should lift the interest
burden on the remaining business.
Mr Buffett said the deal marked an alliance between the two groups. He would
become non-executive vice-chairman of Sensormatic.
The initial payment of Pounds 50m cash is expected to be followed by another
Pounds 100m from the proceeds of a public offering of securities by
Sensormatic.
