<DOCNO>FT922-6825</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAFBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Economic Viewpoint: Two per cent inflation and slow recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SAMUEL BRITTAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In last Monday's Economic Viewpoint, I argued that the only way to discover
whether, and how far, British interest rates could move below German
interest rates within the constraints of the ERM was to 'suck it and see'.
That is, the Bank of England should move them down gradually and be prepared
to go into reverse if sterling came under pressure within its ERM band.
Why has not the Bank of England so far attempted this? One answer is that
these are early days. It is only since the April 9 election that there has
been this room to experiment; and there has already been a half point cut in
base rate to 10 per cent. A further reduction of half a point - or two
further cuts of a quarter point - would take the UK rates a shade below
German rates and into the experimental zone.
There are also, however, domestic arguments for caution about cutting basic
rates, which need to be discussed, but not necessarily endorsed. In line
with my usual practice of leaving the heavier economics to the second half
of my articles, I shall start off with the partisan political case.
The chart shows UK output in relation to the trend of productive capacity.
The numbers just give an order of magnitude. The trend line is meant to give
an idea of where output might be if inflation is not accelerating, and
production is growing in line with capacity.
During the period in the late 1980s, when the thick line, indicating actual
output, was above the dotted trend line, there was pressure on productive
capacity, with inflation rising and the balance of payments gap widening.
Somewhere towards the end of 1990, output reached a sustainable level, as
overheating was giving way to recession. Since then, output has been well
below the sustainable level, recession has been prolonged, but inflation has
fallen.
The Bank of England expects a slow recovery. This means not merely that
output will stay below the trend line, but that the gap shown by the shaded
area between output and productive potential will continue to widen. Indeed,
according to some definitions it would not be a real recovery.
The prospect is nevertheless quite pleasing to some in government. The logic
of the case is this. The upturn in the late 1980s came too early and went
too far. Therefore, the 1992 election had to be fought under the handicap of
a corrective recession. If output can be kept comfortably below capacity for
a couple of years, there can be a growth spurt in the pre-election period
without any inflationary overheating. The GDP line would then start to move
up smartly towards, but still not reach, the trend line.
Thus there could be a pre-election boom without too much inflationary
danger; and after the next election the government will try to stay nearer
the trend line. I am perhaps over-rationalising a desire to do in this
parliament the opposite of what was done in the last; but the proposition
should be discussed.
There are two objections to this approach. First, it is immoral to have
recessionary conditions unnecessarily prolonged and unemployment
unnecessarily high to arrange a pre-election boost. Second, it will not work
politically. The errors of the late 1980s were honest lapses and arose from
policies such as credit deregulation, which were worthwhile for their own
sake, and were corrected when they were diagnosed, despite the political
risks. The electorate sensed this and still preferred the Conservatives to
the alternative. If, however, they sense that they have gone through
unnecessary years of stagnation and are then being bribed by a deliberate
and unsustainably rapid expansion, the government will be out on its ear,
however weak the opposition.
Now let me turn to the economic case for preferring a slow recovery. I had
described the subject of this article to colleagues needing to know in a
rush as 'the Bank of England's case for continuing the recession'. This
served as shorthand, but may be unfair in view of the May Bulletin's
statement that 'high interest rates in Germany have obliged other countries
in the ERM, especially those in the narrow band, to maintain higher interest
rates than domestic considerations would, for the most part, have dictated'.
I defy anyone to tell me whether or not the Bank of England is saying that
UK interest rates are higher than it would like.
What then is the domestic economic case for maintaining a substantial and
widening 'gap' between output and productive capacity? It is to achieve an
inflation rate which the chancellor, Norman Lamont, has described as 'not
only below the European average, but as low as the best in Europe, measured
on a comparable basis'. He quantified this objective as '2 per cent'.
When UK output fell below the trend line near the end of 1990, the
underlying inflation rate was still much too high, even allowing for lags.
If this is to be reduced, output must fall below the trend line and stay
there until a sufficient improvement in inflation is in the pipeline. And if
the amount of slack is not merely high, but increasing, inflation will come
down that much faster.
The case for continuing to pile on the agony is that UK inflation is still a
good deal higher than it appears in the headline rate, which is distorted by
the timing of mortgage interest reductions. The underlying rate is still
about 5 1/2 per cent, a good deal higher than Germany's, for all the
Schadenfreude. UK producer price inflation, which is now running at 2 per
cent to 3 per cent a year, is doing much better; but in leading competitor
countries it is below 1 per cent.
How strong are the arguments for suspending this aim until something like
'stable prices' has been entrenched? Common-sense observation suggests that
it is much more difficult to squeeze out the last few percentage points of
inflation than to get down to 4 or 5 per cent. An inflation rate of 2 per
cent is less than the creeping inflation that prevailed in the Bretton Woods
period and less than anything known in the lifetime of most of the
population. To achieve it would involve a clampdown on the costs of the half
of the economy that is sheltered from international competition such as
construction, property rents and other services.
We have moved a long way from the traditional economic objective, which
would have been to stabilise the movement of output as near to the trend
line as possible. As this is well beyond the half-way point of my article, I
can add that some might have described this objective as 'minimising a
quadratic loss function' - or flattening out booms and slumps.
Even if the Treasury wants to forget about stable growth rates, it may
simply not be able to maintain the margin of slack required for inflation to
fall as low as it would like. For if demand remains slack for too long,
capacity can be retired and workers become so discouraged that they leave
the labour force. Such people have little disinflationary influence.
It is reasonable for the chancellor to seek to publicise a lower rate of
inflation than he expects to get. If he becomes a 'Stormin' Norman' for 2
per cent, he may be able to lock in 4 per cent. But serious disinflation
objectives are best stated in terms of internationally traded goods and
services; and the reluctance of the sheltered sectors to follow suit is best
treated by competition and other supply-side activities.
</TEXT>
