<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Observer: Tale of woe
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Having spent the last two years graphically depicting the impact of
recession on its membership, the Confederation of British Industry yesterday
poured out its own, sorry tale of financial hardship.
The organisation's expanded accounts for 1991 show that an operating surplus
of Pounds 756,000 in 1990 turned into a deficit of Pounds 188,000 last year
 -a performance the CBI tries to pass off as an achievement in these tough
times.
But having preached the need for moderation on pay throughout the darks days
of 1991, the CBI also disclosed that its own salary roll - despite a
standstill in the numbers employed - rose by a healthy (some might say well
above average) 12 per cent during the year.
At least Sir John Banham, the retiring CBI director general, did not
personally add to the organisation's swelling pay costs. Yesterday, he was
again reminding people how he has consistently refused any pay rise during
the slump - which puts Bank of England governor Robin Leigh-Pemberton's much
trumpeted self-denial firmly in its place.
</TEXT>
