<DOCNO>FT922-6833</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAE3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Arts: The Family Reunion - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In 1951, TS Eliot reflected on the 'intentions, failures, and partial
successes' of his plays. He rightly said of The Family Reunion: 'After what
must seem to the audience an interminable time of preparation, the
conclusion comes so abruptly that we are, after all, unready for it.' This
throws down the gauntlet to both audience and director, and his challenge
has been met in a bold, exciting production at the Leicester Haymarket.
Putting a difficult verse drama on the Haymarket main stage calls for nerve
and invention: Reunion gets both from director Julia Bardsley and designer
Aldona Cunningham. The out-of-kilter country-house set works with the
discordant soundtrack (Andrew Poppy) to conjure feelings which, according to
Eliot, 'which we can only detect' from the corner of the eye. Frequent
changes of state indicate the shiftings of consciousness implicit in Eliot's
text.
Reunion, based on Aeschylus and cut for Leicester, traces the return of
Harry to his ancestral home. There, a chorus of aunts and uncles, a harridan
of a mother and a jilted sweetheart await him. He has been haunted by
'furies' ever since his wife fell to her death from an ocean liner; he
searches for peace with himself and his dying mother.
Eliot wrote Reunion in 1939, midway between Murder in The Cathedral and Four
Quartets. It shares technical similarities with both, and was subject to his
rigorous verse-drama aesthetic. While he felt that he overvalued the verse,
neglecting plot and character, Eliot managed to write speech rhythms which
make one cease to be conscious of the play's verse form. This production
strives to stay in touch with those rhythms: 'In an old house there is
always listening . . . We do not like to walk out of a door and find
ourselves back in the same room.'
Eliot was later to rue the chorus and the furies. But here, two coups of
stagecraft involving both make the evening. The furies are terrifying
children dressed as Harry's relatives, and appear in a wonderfully
frightening sequence; they reappear in a psychodrama of Harry's past. The
exorcised furies become 'the friendly ones'.
The fine acting of Rory Edwards (Harry) and Paola Dionisotti (his sage aunt
Agatha) sends tap-roots into the subconscious. Even her dangerous lines 'May
the weasel and the otter be about their proper business' find a place amidst
the evil in the dark. The chorus is an apt melange of insight and stupidity,
conveying their uncertainty and their knowledge; the reflective passages
should be quieter.
This is intelligent directing which tackles Eliot head on. If the production
overreaches itself, it does so to compass Eliot's scope; for he knew that
art was the imposition of credible order upon ordinary reality which
elicited a perception of order in reality.
Leicester Haymarket Theatre (0533 539797) until June 6
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6834</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAE2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Arts: Such stuff as dreams are made on - Cinema
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS and STEPHEN AMIDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LONG DAY CLOSES (12) Curzon West End
WAYNE'S WORLD (PG) Empire Leicester Sq
DON'T TELL MOM THE BABY SITTER'S DEAD (PG) MGMs West End, Odeon
Kensington
DEF BY TEMPTATION (18) Prince Charles
Terence Davies's The Long Day Closes, like his Distant Voices, Still Lives,
is a dream of what film-making could be like. Davies is telling us another
story from his past: his boyhood memories of life with Mum (Marjorie Yates)
in mid-1950s Liverpool, when the bliss of family life and of discovering the
movies (The Robe, Private's Progress, The Lady-killers) was poisoned only by
an eleven year old's first taste of life at a new Catholic school.
It is not what Davies tells, it is how he tells it. He must never have
listened to sensible cinematic advice in his life. The film has no coherent
story; there are long silences interspersed with cryptic dialogue or
impromptu singalongs; and the images mix the real with the surreal. In one
scene a fantasised sailing ship splashes real spray at hero Bud (Leigh
McCormack as the young Davies) as he daydreams in a classroom. In another,
he sees his own face in a school window: but it is not a reflection, it is a
new image of himself about to flash us forward into a new scene.
The Long Day Closes is a miracle of rebel imagination over movie manners.
Since Davies's first film Trilogy, a three-part suicide note shot in black
and white with BFI money, he has put colour and humour into his work. And a
dazzling sensuality. He turns his recreated postwar Liverpool, painstakingly
mocked up at London's Rotherhithe Studios, into a dreamscape part beautiful,
part brutalist.
Changing daylight weaves shifting traceries on worn carpets. Rain lends a
silver pointillism to a street outside a cinema. (As abruptly and
dramatically as it comes, it is cut off.) And lyrical tracking-shots travel
not just between streets but between years, lubricated by Davies's
invocation of hallowed movie dialogue lines. 'In those years they had time
for everything' (The Magnificent Ambersons); 'Mrs Wilberforce, I understand
you have rooms to let' (The Ladykillers).
Some filmgoers resist or even resent film-making so determinedly
impressionistic. Even though their own minds operate in this
free-associative way almost every minute of their lives, they think films
should tell neat linear stories. But just look at one scene that turned this
filmgoer incandescent with joy. The boy sits on a staircase silently musing.
All that 'happens' is that the lighting on his face changes three times. The
scene has no takeaway message, the boy's thoughts and feelings are not
spelled out in over-voice. But the profundity and serendipity of changing
human mood has never been more simply, vividly caught.
Davies only falters, briefly, when he harks back to the messianic
miserablism of Trilogy. It is a good black joke to follow Mum's wistful 'I
wonder what 1956 will bring' with a shot of nailed feet on a cross. (Cue
Bud's entry into his new school.) But the round of lice inspections and
bleak cruelty, with more helpings of religious symbolism, is too overtly
querulous.
We feel hectored. Worse, we feel we have been smuggled into Davies's mind by
the non-denominational beguilements of the film's early scenes in order to
be his anti-Catholic storm troopers when he needs us.
Far more haunting is a single, inexplicable nightmare image at home. A pair
of hands reach out from behind Bud's bed and clasp his head. Nothing leads
to the scene, nothing leads away: it is for the audience to join the
emotional dots. Here and in the film's use of music to challenge or ironise
the visuals, and in the ingenuity of the visuals themselves like the
halo-ing back-light on Bud's head in class that suddenly wobbles to become a
movie projector beam, Terence Davies proves that he is not just a good
film-maker, he has the makings of a great film-maker.
Wayne's World provides the most convincing argument since Network for
throwing your television out of the window. It follows the antics of two
young American couch potatoes, Wayne and Garth (Mike Myers and Dana Carvey),
as they present their public access TV chat show, an anarchic combination of
mindless babble of the 'party on, dude' variety, woebegone special guests
and lots of heavy metal music. When not on air, Wayne and Garth stumble
through the world in a permanent electronic thrall - quoting TV adverts, lip
synching to the radio, dreaming of the girl in the rock video. Their idea of
witty dialogue is for one to exclaim 'No Way]', whereupon the other counters
by saying 'Way]'.
The film was born as a regular skit on America's Saturday Night Live comedy
show, where it provided an often hilarious depiction of a generation of
youth unable to conceive of anything that is not bounced off a satellite or
channelled through loudspeakers. It is a shame that Myers, the show's
creator, felt it had to be stretched out to a movie format - the plot,
involving a venal network producer trying to take over the show, is
nonsense, while the satire quickly achieves saturation point in a series of
gags which will try the patience of most viewers. To make matters worse,
there are continual references to television commercials and programmes
unavailable over here. This is not to say that there are not some funny
moments, though the overall impression the film leaves you with is that the
telecommunications revolution is over, and the machines have won.
A far less distressing view of American youth is on display in Don't Tell
Mom The Babysitter's Dead. The film's plot is more or less deducible from
its title: a harried single mother of five decides to take a few months off
in Australia, leaving her children in the care of a tough old sitter, who
promptly dies, whereupon the eldest child (Christina Applegate) must take
charge of the family. The carefree 17-year-old soon shows her worth by
bluffing her way into a high-paying position in the fashion industry,
managing to hold the family together while at the same time winning the
heart of the boy in the hot dog delivery van. What starts out as a
potentially chaotic teen comedy soon turns into a gormlessly charming
coming-of-age story that comes down firmly in favor of honesty, hard work
and traditional family values.
The distributors of Def by Temptation claim that it is 'the best black
vampire movie since Blacula', an assessment I am not prepared to argue with,
having missed all the other black vampire movies. Unfortunately, first time
writer/director James Bond III has made a film which is hard to praise in
many other ways. It tells the story of a young divinity student who travels
to New York City for a vacation, only to find himself doing battle with a
female vampire barfly who tries to tempt him away from his faith. Despite
some spirited acting by Bill Nunn and Kadeem Hardison, the film's pace too
uneven and its goriness too unconvincing to make it very scary.
It is not that Bond is without talent - he just has failed to stretch his
low budget to adequately cover the horror genre.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6835</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAE1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Arts: Patagonia/The Fastest Clock in the Universe - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR MACAULAY and DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Telling your own history is an important way of showing that you have some
pride in yourself. Patagonia, presented by the Welsh group Brith Gof, is
less about that distant land than about the 153 Welsh settlers who sailed
there in 1865 and whose descendants remain there, still speaking Welsh -
mixed with Spanish and a little English - holding eisteddfodau, singing
festivals and Welsh newspapers. Part documentary, part performance art,
Patagonia does honour to both Wales and to pioneers.
Its first parts remind me a lot of Martha Graham's greatest work, the 1944
Appalachian Spring. Like that, this shows the bare frame of a new homestead
against an open sky, the two women and two men of the new community, their
relationships and the religious practices they have brought with them. But
Patagonia is not a dance work, and it celebrates to a considerable degree
the way these Welsh Patagonians have kept the Welsh language alive. I have
no Welsh, but hearing the musicality of this Welsh, whether in speech or in
song, was one of the evening's pleasures.
This work is about history, the development of a community through the
generations and its commemoration of its past. We not only see and hear the
rites and customs of these emigres, we hear detached commentary too. A
narrator figure - who sits, with his back to us, at the front of the
auditorium, using the front of the stage as his desk - and the four onstage
performers tell isolated stories of specific families and their houses. We
hear how 'She is the museum. Women always carry the history,' how even these
Welsh became 'true conquistadors,' how 'In a land where nothing rots,
history spreads itself,' and how one of these stories was told to (among
others) Bruce Chatwin and became chapter 17 of his In Patagonia.
All of this is affecting and stimulating, and the simple elegance of the
staging is often marvellous. The four-part singing is excellent, the
speaking has dignity, the main gestures have breadth and power. The use of
sand on the floor provides a source of beautifully ambiguous symbolism -
sand as locale, sand as time, sand as omnipresent intrusion.
Best is the way that the staging frequently shows us two or more acts at the
same time or in quick succession. There are, however, a few longueurs, even
though the work lasts only 70 minutes. Certain inventories of local life
become ponderous, and the slow-motion treatment of one dramatic episode
manages to be both dull and obscure.
But Patagonia, a frequently poetic work, won my immediate respect and
interest. Brith Gof is a group new to me; I hope to encounter more of its
work before long. It is the first offering in the excellent three-week
Barclays New Stages season at the Royal Court, which presents some of
Britain's leading work in performance art, new dance and/or music theatre.
Philip Ridley's new play at the Hampstead Theatre until June 13 is short and
sour, variably funny and intermittently gripping. In outline the scenario
might suggest Joe Orton, but neither the writing nor the sentiments echo
that cheerful subversive at all. Structurally, the play is much nearer to
Pinter's Birthday Party - and not only because Ridley's centrepiece too is a
sinister party.
Here, the birthday is Cougar Glass's 'nineteenth': we gather he has had
several of those already. He lives with his sugar-daddy 'Captain Tock', a
cultivated, tragically balding antique dealer who likes clocks (Cougar hates
them, and cultivates nothing but his quiff and his artifical tan). The
parties are a device for luring beddable youths home; in due course the
Captain will make an excuse and leave.
The latest unknowing prey is Foxtrot Darling (Ridley's way with names is all
his own), for whom Cougar has become a a big-brother substitute. Foxtrot
arrives with not only a deeply unwelcome birthday gift, but his pregnant
fiancee Sherbet Gravel too; they call each other 'Babe' indiscriminately.
The Captain decides to remain, while Cougar leaves off his languid macho
preening and goes into a long, silent seethe. Sherbet soon sizes up the
situation all too well, and her bright chat turns again and again to
reflections upon mortality. Eventually there is a ghastly eruption, staged
for maximum theatrical impact by the director Matthew Lloyd.
Jonathan Coy (I think that is his real name) plays the Captain with some
delicacy, if slightly too much hair, and Con O'Neill (ditto) seethes well.
The kids are expertly cartooned by Jude Law, the lamb to the slaughter, and
clever Emma Amos. As tough old Cheetah Bee, the landlady of this
semi-converted factory (picturesquely devised by Moggie Douglas), Elizabeth
Bradley makes the most of her two appearances with Zimmer frame.
They all give the play a grounding in a plausible East End reality which
Ridley's text barely suggests, dreamily abstract as it often is. Curious
exercise] If it bears a moral, it seems too obvious to mention; but perhaps
there is a real-life Cougar out there somewhere, who is meant to be
pilloried here.
</TEXT>
