<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Technology: Cutting through the red tape - How fragmented
sectors, such as machine tools, can realistically carry out joint R&amp;D
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Over the past few months, Europe's machine tool builders have been engaged
in characteristically low-pro-file talks with the European Community about a
possible industrial policy. In the depths of a recession that has damaged
competitiveness, the industry hopes for some stimulus to investment by its
customers in manufacturing, but also wants the EC to help create the
conditions that might address some of its longer-term problems.
At the top of the list is a very different approach to research and
development - aimed at stimulating better co-operation between companies in
the most strategically important areas of R&amp;D, and improving the unhappy
relationship between the industry and EC-funded research programmes.
The outcome of the talks is far from clear, but the industry's approach
raises questions about the nature of R&amp;D in a fragmented, intensely
competitive industry of some 1,500 independent producers.
How does such an industry achieve a balance between 'R' and 'D' when most
companies concentrate exclusively on the D? Where does the R get done, and
how does the industry benefit? How much R is necessary anyway?
For many machine tool builders, development work that is not linked to a
specific product or technology is rare, and 'blue-sky research' taboo. But
new materials, relatively new processes such as laser-cutting and the trend
towards standardisation of control systems, motors and drives all argue for
a significant research element in R&amp;D.
Inevitably, though, the recession has reduced the ability of machine tool
builders to do much more than plough their own development furrows.
Consequently, increased co-operation on higher levels of research -
broad-based and 'pre-competitive' but not 'blue-sky' - has become an even
higher priority for producers, users, institutions and universities.
But the industry and the EC industrial research infrastructure is poorly
matched. Most machine tool builders, for example, believe the structure and
content of the EC's Brite/Euram industrial research projects make it
difficult for them to participate.
'The research is too far removed from the market place to allow the
formulation of projects that can be useful in the medium- or short- term,'
says Mike Bright, chairman of Brighton-based FMT Holdings. 'It's the
Plesseys, Siemens &amp; Philips who are obtaining the funds. The SMEs (small and
medium-sized enterprises) are not getting a look in, and it's causing quite
a concern.'
Tony Balding, managing director of Norwich-based Beaver Engineering Group,
cites the intimidating amounts of paperwork involved in applying to join an
EC project. He warns too that small companies which do participate may find
their pace is inhibited by larger, slower-moving partners.
Continental machine tool companies have similar complaints. Sandvik of
Sweden has participated in Brite/Euram via EC subsidiaries, but Clas Ake
Hedstrom, president of the Sandvik Coromant metal-cutting tools division,
says that results have been limited so far, and some programmes are taking
longer than was originally anticipated.
The problem for the machine tool industry is that such EC projects were set
up to focus on what Nigel Eldred, chief executive of Amtri, the UK machine
tool research organisation, calls 'macro-technology'.
Consequently, small companies which have traditionally carried out strictly
targeted development work find it difficult to leap into these broader-based
projects.
However, the industry has reason to hope that EC-funded research may soon
become more user-friendly. Jean Heymans, secretary general of Cecimo, the
European machine tool trade association umbrella body, says the EC's current
Framework programme for Brite/Euram projects will be much more geared to
industry than to blue-sky research.
Cecimo, whose talks with the EC are backed by its 12 member countries, is
pushing for a policy designed to improve the SMEs' access to R&amp;D programmes
through measures such as increased funding for their projects, simplified
administrative procedures and enlarged Craft-type programmes.
Craft, an offshoot of Brite/Euram and currently at the pilot stage, is
likely to be more market-oriented than Brite/Euram itself, and could appeal
to SMEs. Administrative procedures should be simpler but, according to one
UK machine tool official, 'there will still be a whittling down process, and
unless you know the ropes, you haven't got a hope in hell'.
As long as the machine tool industry retains its current structure, though,
there will always be companies which will find it hard to benefit from the
EC's largesse - some Ecu 500m (Pounds 350m) spent on Brite/Euram in 1989-92
and Ecu 670m budgeted for the overlapping 1990-94 programme.
But the industry can, and is, participating in the pan-European Eureka R&amp;D
initiative, launched in 1985. This is intended to be more market-related
than Brite/Euram, but projects are narrower in scope and rely on funding by
national governments.
Speed is probably the biggest factor prompting some companies to consider
bilateral agreements on development rather than become involved in a
long-term project which offers little opportunity to cover administrative
costs and could be tantamount to 'buying a headache,' says Eldred.
But at least one larger UK machine tool company is happy to be taking part
in a Brite/Euram project, even if it did take months to get off the ground.
Jones &amp; Shipman, the Leicester-based grinding machine manufacturer, is
investigating the potential of cubic boron nitride for precision cylindrical
grinding at high wheel speeds via a four-year Brite/Euram project based at
Aachen.
The diversity of the project's participants is a new trend for machine tool
research and one which many observers believe should be encouraged. Apart
from Aachen University's machine tool research department, the other
partners are Brussels-based Diamond Boart, manufacturers of super-abrasive
wheels, and a user - the vehicle-parts and electricals group Robert Bosch.
In the UK, which has traditionally lagged behind continental Europe in
harnessing R&amp;D carried out by companies, universities and government-funded
research institutions, Amtri has been the catalyst behind a unique project
that follows a similar approach.
The Pounds 15m Machine Tool Technology and Materials Processing Programme,
supported by the Department of Trade and Industry, brings machine tool
customers, producers and part suppliers together in a series of separate
projects such as high-speed spindle research. The aim is for all the
technologies being developed in the programme to be combined in a
'multi-function machine tool'.
Eldred sees a key role for Amtri as a 'networker' to link companies with
universities and other bodies, and to keep its ear close to the ground in
relation to other European centres. As companies and institutions begin to
take a more international approach to research partnerships, the next step
is to help develop a more effective 'network of networks' in Europe,
according to Derek Palethorpe, Amtri's director of operations.
The overall aim should be to produce a more co-ordinated, broad-based
approach to R&amp;D in the European machine tool industry. In the background is
competition from Japan, which has always outshone rivals on product
development and exploitation but is also becoming more interested in
multidisciplinary international research.
Japan's proposed research project into intelligent manufacturing systems,
for example, is intended to have international participation. Some European
observers worry, therefore, that it may be no more than a Trojan horse
feeding on Europe's remaining areas of superiority in machine tool
innovation.
At the same time, industry critics say, more mergers and cross-border
co-operation among European machine tool builders would develop a mentality
that is better suited to participate in the higher reaches of EC research.
At least they would have more resources to handle the red tape.
</TEXT>
