<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Technology: Self-help on open systems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An initiative to promote 'open' computer systems among UK small- and
medium-sized businesses is being orchestrated by the Department of Trade and
Industry as its Pounds 12m open systems technology transfer programme ends
this month.
The DTI has already held meetings with a number of large computer suppliers
who have pledged their support for a broad programme of measures to
disseminate information about open systems and their benefits.
The list includes ICL, IBM, Digital Equipment, Hewlett Packard, AT&amp;T,
Easylink, Unisys and Uniplex. While details of the initiative remain to be
settled, it seems likely it will include a 'hotline' number which companies
will be able to call for independent advice.
It is also likely to develop guidelines which will define a set of
attributes for openness which could be compared with suppliers' offerings.
Open systems are based on commonly accepted industry standards and usually
imply computers that can easily be connected together and run software from
any supplier following open systems rules.
Open systems offer significant possibilities for cutting costs once the move
from proprietary designs has been made, but DTI studies show that while the
message is well understood among very large companies - BP, Marks &amp; Spencer
and Lucas are enthusiastic supporters of the initiative  - medium-sized and
small companies are frequently confused by differing messages from suppliers
and have difficulty obtaining independent information on which to base
decisions. They are often too small to be able to afford to join one of the
big league self-help organisations such as the Butler Cox Foundation.
The DTI intends to inject some Pounds 2m in pump priming funds over the next
two years but otherwise will confine itself to acting as 'honest broker'
among the various factions and suppliers which make up the open systems
movement.
The idea is for the industry to take the lead in speaking to customers with
a single, unambiguous voice about open systems. The DTI initiative is backed
by lobby groups including X/Open, Uniforum UK, Unix International and the
National Computing Centre.
</TEXT>
