<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Kinnock calls for re-think on
'opt-outs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROMOTION of 'co-ordinated expansion' during the UK presidency of the
Community was urged on the government yesterday, by Mr Neil Kinnock, the
Labour leader.
Opening the debate for the opposition, Mr Kinnock argued that such an
approach was the only way 'to ensure vitality and confidence in western
Europe and to promote stability, hope and strengthened democracy in Eastern
Europe'.
The certainty of growing interdependence between EC countries made it
essential, he said, for the government to work towards promoting balanced
development and social cohesion.
He called on the prime minister to abandon his 'opt-out mentality' and
re-emphasised Labour's broad support for the treaty, He also emphsasised its
opposition to opting out of the social chapter and economic and monetary
union.
These 'opt-outs' are at the heart of the party's 'reasoned amendment' to the
bill. But if that amendment fails, Labour policy is to abstain on whether
the bill should proceed. That policy came under fire during the debate from
some Labour backbenchers.
Mr Kinnock called the terms in which minsters had attacked the social
chapter 'absolute fantasies' and warned that the government had indulged in
such fictions because it needed the false threat of disruption to cover up
its desertion of duty in failing to secure better rights for British
workers.
He said Britain was the example that poor labour conditions did not mean
necessarily superior economic performance, and called on ministers to end
efforts to make Britain 'the labour market bargain basement of Europe'.
Turning to economic and monetary union, he warned the government that as
early as 1994 it would have to make specific proposals so that preparatory
decisions could be taken. 'They won't be able to opt out of that', he said.
While Mr Kinnock was heard in a crowded Commons with little interruption,
there was discomfort for the Labour front bench from Mr Peter Shore.
The former Labour cabinet minister called the party's apparent readiness to
let the EC decide the future size of public borrowing under a Labour
government 'a total disgrace', and warned that opposition MPs had a duty to
vote against the bill itself.
He ridiculed the briefing from the party's Treasury frontbench team that the
mention of goals of sustainable growth and high employment early in the
treaty put those aims on a par with the aims of economic and monetary union,
and price stability in particular.
Mr Shore said the government had evaded the central issue of where Britain
should go when a majority of other EC member states wanted a different -
federal - destiny.
Mr Tony Benn (Lab Chesterfield) said it would be absolutely wrong for a step
of such magnitude to be taken without consulting the people who - because of
the transfer of more decision-making to Brussels - would lose democratic
rights.
Mr Austin Mitchell (Lab Great Grimsby) said the Bill would get a second
reading tonight not because the argument had been won but because the Labour
leadership had 'allowed it to go through'.
</TEXT>
