<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Smith and Gould clash in debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RIVAL candidates for the Labour leadership clashed last night in the
first and, possibly, the only head-to-head confrontation before the
electoral college ballots on July 18.
Their performances in a Fabian Society debate eschewed acrimony and were
held by many to have amounted to a draw. However, several rounds of applause
for Mr John Smith's staunch avowals of Labour's first principles may just
have given him a points victory over his rival, Mr Bryan Gould.
The loudest accolade came for the shadow chancellor's dismissal of a
suggestion that the party should appeal baldly to electors' self-interests.
'The philosophy of democratic socialism is about a moral view of life . . .
if there is no morality in it it is not worth having,' he said.
Mr Gould won acclaim too when he made clear that altruism was not enough and
that Labour needed to find new ways to appeal to a new and wider electorate.
Arguing that one path to victory was to defuse the concentration of power
among vested interests, he cited the aphorism: 'The great advantage of
socialism is it removes the need to be altruistic.'
In the event, the clearest exposition of the differences between the two men
came in their opening statements. Mr Smith spoke of building an opposition
from the anti-Conservative majority.
Promoting his plan for a Commission on Social Justice to examine tax and
benefits, he argued: 'We face a new challenge of designing a strategy for
social justice and economic opportunity that will benefit the minority,
while gaining the votes of the majority that will have to pay for it.'
Mr Gould offered a lightly veiled critique of his rival as a 'one last
heave' candidate.
The leadership needed someone with the experience to fight beyond Labour's
heartlands who could offer 'distinctive and positive reasons why people
should vote Labour.' That would involve a commitment to run the economy
differently and challenge monetarist orthodoxy, he said.
The differences between the two men in much of the question session that
followed was mostly mood music.
On Europe, Mr Gould rejected a purely 'monetarist' approach in the
convergence towards economic and monetary union. Mr Smith, instead, stressed
the need to discuss that question while progressing to the EMU goal.
On party reforms, Mr Smith argued that there should be a role for MPs in a
future leadership electoral college, whereas his opponent said a one-member,
one-vote system would lessen union unease.
Both agreed on the need for constitutional reform, especially devolution and
a consideration of electoral reform.
Mr Gould put greater emphasis on the need to promote full employment before
a redistributive tax policy, whereas Mr Smith suggested that such a goal,
although desirable, was no substitute for a clearly argued case for
redistribution.
</TEXT>
