<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / The Finance Bill: Ex-rebel is 'no sloppy interventionist' -
The former health minister who will guide the proposals through the Commons
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Treasury is regarded as the rightwing redoubt of Mr John Major's
government. Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, is as dry on economic policy
as any member of the cabinet. Mr Michael Portillo, the chief secretary, is
as close as anything the Thatcherite wing of the party has to an
heir-apparent.
But every rule has its exception. In the case of the Treasury it is Mr
Stephen Dorrell.
The financial secretary, charged over the next few weeks with piloting the
Finance Bill through the Commons, is now firmly established among the rising
stars in the middle ranks of Mr Major's administration.
The responsibilities of the third-ranking member of the Treasury team
include the detailed tax work involved in Budget-making along with a brief
to give substance to Mr Major's pledge to create a nation of savers and
share owners. He is also the minister directly responsible for
privatisation, competition and de-regulation.
More immediately, Mr Dorrell's oversight of the Civil Service means that he
will have to grapple with what is shaping up as a bitter clash over pay with
the Whitehall unions.
His boyish looks belie a grasp of economics as well as politics that have
allowed the 'wringing wet' rebel of the early 1980s to become the Treasury
minister of the 1990s. If he proves his mettle over the next two or three
years, the reward should be a place on the shortlist for the next batch of
entrants to Mr Major's cabinet.
It is quite a turnround for the 40-year-old MP for Loughborough, the
youngest of the Tory arrivals at Westminster in 1979. He spent most of the
first half of the 1980s rebelling against his government's economic
strategy. He was once driven by Mrs Thatcher's faith in monetarism to
describe his party as 'the better of two evils'.
When Mrs Thatcher appointed him to the whips office in 1987, colleagues at
Westminster saw it as an inexplicable act of forgiveness by the prime
minister.
Mr Dorrell, long an acolyte of Mr Peter Walker, is refreshingly unfussed
about a past that embraced public opposition to Treasury cuts in
unemployment benefit and repeated defiance of Mrs Thatcher's opposition to
the European exchange rate mechanism.
In the present government the latter view - which in 1986 prompted a public
rebuke from Mrs Thatcher - has served to strengthen the relationship he
forged with Mr Major during his spell as the whip responsible for Treasury
affairs.
Like most attached to the One-Nation strand of Toryism, the financial
secretary's thoughts on economic policy have moved on: 'We all change, don't
we, as we respond to new influences. So, yes, they (his opinions) have
changed'.
Not all. He is still firmly wedded to the concept of a welfare state that is
more than a basic safety-net for the very poorest. 'I'm personally totally
committed to the principle, for example, that health and education are
services that we should seek to provide not as a safety net but as a
universal service . . . and they don't come free.'
As the former health minister who spent much of the past two years defending
the NHS reforms, though, he is convinced that those services cannot be
immune from the disciplines of the private sector.
'What we need to be doing is constantly testing which (public services) have
to remain in the public sector and ensure that the efficiency of those which
do remain there is constantly tested.' An official who worked with him
attests that he is 'no sloppy interventionist'.
A large shareholder in and former manager of his family's textile business,
Mr Dorrell insists that he has always been committed to low direct taxation
to sharpen the incentives that drive wealth creation.
He insists that there is no contradiction between the government's pledge
for better public services and his responsibilities as financial secre-tary
to find new ways of reducing the tax burden.
He displays little of the evangelical zeal of those in the party - including
Mr Portillo - who believe that a renewed drive to cut income tax must be
given priority over virtually all else.
Pressed on the right balance between public spending and taxation, Mr
Dorrell retreats to the pragmatic response that there is no 'final state of
knowledge' on where the line should be drawn.
He comments: 'Life isn't like that'.
Closer to home, Mr Dorrell is cautious about how the government will live up
to its promise to entrench the habit of saving among the less affluent as
well as the wealthy.
This year's finance bill is unspectacular in polit-ical terms, the
left-overs
Mr Dorrell's Treasury officials can be expected to explain that, even with
the next budget still nine months off, it is not quite as easy as it looks
to manipulate the tax system to turn us into a nation of savers.
For now, he is reluctant to pre-empt anything that Mr Lamont might have in
mind on the tax front. He is apparently unsure how to persuade a sceptical
City to support the government's efforts to provide new incentives for
individual shareholders.
That should not prove too much of a handicap to a man who is as astute a
politician as he is hard-working as a minister. It does no harm these days
to be seen as the young face of Majorism.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
