<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Teacher vacancies well down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of teacher vacancies in England is sharply down on last year
according to government figures released yesterday.
The overall vacancy rate has fallen by nearly two thirds since last year -
from 1.5 per cent of all posts to 0.6 per cent - taking the number of
unfilled posts to 1,955. Overall teacher numbers are slightly up at 394,000.
The altered trend is particularly marked in London, where the vacancy rate
has fallen to 1 per cent, its lowest since 1988 - and the lowest for
secondary schools since 1984.
Vacancies in science subjects fell by two thirds, but the decline in other
shortage subjects was below par. Maths vacancies were down by half, and
unfilled posts in modern languages declined by only a third.
High levels of graduate unemployment account partly for the renewed
attraction of teaching, but substantial real pay increases in the past two
years, and promotion and bursary schemes to attract students in shortage
subjects, may also have made an impact.
Lady Blatch, schools minister, said: 'Any lingering claims that the national
curriculum cannot be delivered in full because of teacher shortages should
now fade away.'
</TEXT>
