<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / 'Signs of life' in housing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE has been a widespread increase in confidence among potential house
buyers and sellers since the general election, according to a survey of
almost 100 English and Welsh estate agents, published today.
The Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors, which conducted the survey,
said the number of people making inquiries about properties for sale has
risen since polling day. 'The clearest signs of recovery are coming from
East Anglia, where increased sales are reported, particularly in Norwich and
Peterborough,' it said.
'The London housing market, worst hit by the property slump, also shows
greater signs of life, with more people house hunting and a detectable rise
in optimism. After several false starts, a recovery in the housing market is
at last within sight.'
The institution warned that it would take a long time before house sales
returned to normal levels.
The survey said 30 per cent of agents reported price falls in the three
months to the end of April, compared with 68 per cent who said prices had
remained static. Most agents expect prices to lag, even if sales increase
this year.
</TEXT>
