<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / BNFL to cut further 550 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Nuclear Fuels (BNFL) is to shed at least 550 jobs at its Capenhurst
uranium enrichment plant, in north-west England, because of the collapse of
the world market since the cold war ended.
The job losses are in addition to 400 last year, and a further 500 jobs are
under threat because of technological improvements.
BNFL also announced plans to sell enriched uranium worldwide through a new
joint venture with counterparts in the Netherlands and Germany.
Enriched uranium has been treated to increase the proportion of uranium-235,
the isotope that sustains chain reactions. BNFL produces U-235 by turning
uranium into a gas, then centrifuging out the heavier atoms of the unwanted
U-238 isotope.
Enriched uranium is used in nuclear power station reactor rods and for
military purposes. The end of the cold war has cut military requirements and
opened the world market for reactor rods to Russian producers with low
labour costs.
BNFL said yesterday: 'There is now worldwide oversupply and the competition
is becoming cut-throat.' BNFL, a public limited company with the government
as its sole shareholder, said it would have lost Pounds 6m in the current
year had it tried to carry on.
It is negotiating to convert Urenco, its partnership with Ultra-Centrifuge
Nederland, of Almelo, and Uran-Isotopentrennungs Gesellschaft, of Julich,
Germany, into a company.
Urenco was formed in 1971 after the British, Netherlands and West German
governments agreed to co-operate on commercial exploitation of the gas
centrifuge process. Ownership of the new venture will be split equally.
Capenhurst's military and civil uranium enrichment operations are being
split, with 600 staff being temporarily 'parked' in a new subsidiary until
they can be transferred to the European company.
The other 550 staff will stay with BNFL to dismantle and decommission
Capenhurst's old diffusion plant and carry on making enriched uranium for
the Ministry of Defence until the contract to do so expires next year.
Fewer than 100 people are likely to be needed at Capenhurst in five years,
when Urenco should have developed new, labour-saving technology.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
