<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Bank seeks tougher standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England is pressing for a change in international banking
regulations to ban banks from branching outside their home countries if they
fail to meet certain standards.
The Bank's tough stance in talks with other regulators on the Basle
Committee for Banking Supervision emerged yesterday when the Bank published
its annual report and a separate report of its supervisory activities.
It is understood that Mr Brian Quinn, the Bank's representative on the Basle
committee, hopes that by the end of the year bank supervisors from the big
industrial countries will have agreed to radical changes in the 1983 Basle
Concordat, which lays down a regulatory framework. Mr Quinn is believed to
support a proposal that bank supervisors should ban bank branches from their
countries if the branches' owner fails to meet standards laid down in the
concordat.
In the wake of last year's closure of Bank of Credit and Commerce
International, a change in the concordat is likely to be that international
banks should submit to being regulated worldwide by at least one supervisory
authority. A second change to the concordat would be that banks must meet
the international capital adequacy standard, the Basle ratio, intended to
ensure that banks are robust enough to withstand shocks.
The Bank's reports contain much information on its work and views.
Highlights include:
The Bank criticises the 'lending criteria' observed in the 1980s. UK banks
expanded their lending portfolios very rapidly in that period and have
recently suffered big losses on those loans.
The Bank says it has encouraged UK banks to review their procedures for
making loans. However, it is adamant that in a market environment it would
have been inappropriate to prevent the banks from making such mistakes. It
discloses that it became concerned last year that small banks might run into
serious difficulties. Many small banks' access to liquid funds became
severely reduced because local authorities, public-sector corporations and
other professional investors transferred their deposits to bigger banks.
They made the transfers because of fears that small banks might fail as a
result of big losses on loans. Their concerns became even greater after the
closure of BCCI.
The Bank of England kept a very close watch on the small banks in this
period and believes they handled the crisis prudently. A few decided to wind
down their business in an orderly way and all were urged by the Bank to
explore whether they could reduce dependence on volatile sources of
deposits.
The Bank made an operating profit of Pounds 166m in the year to February 29
1992, 3 per cent up on the previous year. From that it paid the UK Treasury
Pounds 67.6m, down from Pounds 81.5m.
The number of authorised banking institutions operating in London fell from
530 to 518. The Bank of England revoked the banking licence of only one
institution, BCCI. The fall in authorisations was the result in part of
mergers of banks and reorganisations of international banking groups.
The Bank reiterates its view that the banks do not operate a cartel in the
small-business loan market. Nevertheless, it is concerned that
small-business customers may find it difficult to shop around for a new bank
because of technical difficulties in terminating an existing bank
relationship.
However, the Bank believes that competition in the small-business loan
market has increased greatly in the past decade, with the entry into the
market of TSB Group and foreign banks and the growth of the Scottish
clearing banks.
It has given those views to the Office of Fair Trading, which is deciding
whether Lloyds Bank's proposed bid for Midland Bank should be referred to
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
The Bank gives aggregated figures for the trading results of the big UK
banks - Barclays, National Westminster, Lloyds, Midland, Standard Chartered,
Royal Bank of Scotland, Bank of Scotland and TSB Group. They show that the
banks collectively made record provisions to cover losses on loans of Pounds
6.8bn, up from Pounds 4.1bn in 1990.
The running costs of the banks as a percentage of total income fell, ending
a trend which began in 1985.
USE of the Pounds 20 note is increasing rapidly, according to the Bank of
England's annual report.  In the past year, 489m Pounds 20 notes were
issued, compared with 252m the previous year. The Pounds 10 note remains the
most commonly issued denomination, with Pounds 5.74bn worth of them in
circulation, compared with Pounds 5.29bn for the Pounds 20 note.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
