<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Housing may be cut from RPI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSING costs may disappear from the retail prices index if Britain is to
bring its measure of inflation more closely into harmony with other European
Community countries.
Half the EC's member states make no allowance for housing costs in their
calculations of the main inflation rate - only the UK and Ireland include
mortgage interest payments.
Other countries, such as Germany, measure home-owning housing costs with an
'imputed rent' system - the cost is treated as if the properties had been
rented.
That approach was used in Britain until 1975 but dropped because the private
rented sector was too small and unrepresentative a market on which to base
the housing costs of most of the population.
At the International Conference of Labour Statisticians in 1987, the
International Labour Organisation recommended that countries should provide
an all-items index that excludes shelter in order to ease international
comparisons.
The ILO said that although the exclusion of shelter from the all-items index
would not eliminate all the differences encountered when making such
comparisons, it would make rates of price change more comparable across
countries.
The recommendation stemmed partly from concerns about the different
methodologies used to calculate housing costs, but another concern was that
housing markets were distinctive to different countries. Whether because of
rental controls or tax incentives, markets did not behave in an identical
manner.
Although Eurostat, the EC's statistical office, has looked at the issue of
the harmonisation of inflation measures across the EC, little has yet been
heard of any definite proposals.
A report published by Eurostat in 1989 suggested that imputed rents could be
used as the yardstick for measuring owner-occupiers' housing costs.
The Confederation of British Industry, which criticises the inclusion of
mortgage interest payments in the calculation of the RPI, says that would
not be difficult to implement in the UK, since imputed rents are already
used in the UK's national accounts for measuring owner-occupiers' housing
costs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6863</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAD9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / A pervasive influence on the economy: The impact of the
retail prices index and the way in which it is calculated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RETAIL Prices Index has become a pervasive influence in many aspects of
the British economy.
That is in spite of the existence of various other measures of inflation -
such as the GDP deflator, the producer price index for manufactured goods
and the pensioner price index - which may have theoretical advantages or be
more suited to particular purposes.
The RPI has become the dominant measure because it is rapidly available (by
about the middle of the next month), is adjusted in scope to reflect
changing spending patterns and is protected from undue political
interference by an advisory committee that includes independent members.
The RPI has an unrivalled effect on the level of pay increases - the average
level of pay rises is invariably close to the latest inflation rate.
Many wage bargainers, particularly among trade unions, would resist
reforming the RPI, but they would probably have little option but to
continue to use it as the main yardstick in negotiations.
Mr Norman Willis, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, said
yesterday: 'Mortgage rates are part of the cost of living. If costs go up
and are not reflected in the RPI then that would produce a horse laugh.'
But Mr Alastair Hatchett, of the Incomes Data Services pay research group,
believes negotiators would use the official RPI, however it was calculated.
Mr Peter Ball, deputy director-general of the Engineering Employers
Federation, said: 'There would be a lot of hot air spoken if the formula
changed but eventually people would follow it.'
A change in the RPI calculation would present difficulties for a sizeable
minority of companies that have negotiated long-term pay deals linked to
inflation. Those are far less popular than they were in the late 1980s, but
most car manufacturers, including Ford and Vauxhall, still favour two-year
deals, as do British Airways and the Civil Aviation Authority.
If the method of calculation were to change, there might be argument in some
companies over what the second-year rise should be.
Mr Hatchett said clauses laying down that inflation would be as calculated
at the time of the agreement were likely to grow in popularity, but would be
based on the assumption that the RPI as currently constituted would still be
available - which was by no means certain.
A potentially sensitive area is the impact of RPI changes on social security
benefits, including state pensions, unemployment benefit, income support and
housing benefit, which are upgraded annually according to the RPI.
Any suggestion that the government was trying to suppress statistical
evidence of rises in living costs would create a political storm. But in
some respects an index excluding mortgage interest would be a more suitable
determinant of the level of social security benefits.
Regulation of utility prices has also become an important area for the
application of the RPI. It forms the benchmark for regulating BT's main
prices, for example.
The price formulae are being reviewed by Oftel, the telecommunications
regulatory body, but it is almost certain that the RPI will continue as the
benchmark. Oftel has resisted switching to another index, arguing that RPI
is the only inflation measure widely understood.
BT and Oftel had no comment yesterday on the merits of excluding mortgage
interest payments from the RPI. It is thought, though, that in the long run
such a change would have little effect on the company's finances.
Ofgas, the industry regulator that devised the formula controlling British
Gas's price rises to domestic customers, said it was unlikely to revise the
formula if the RPI figure was calculated differently.
The RPI similarly plays a central role in the complex formula used for water
charges. The Office of Water Services said it was assumed that water
companies would have to take account of any new method of calculating the
RPI before deciding charges.
Investments such as index-linked gilts depend on the RPI for their value.
Index-linked gilts showed modest gains in prices yesterday, as investors
reacted to the possibility of the proposed change - both the repayment value
and the interest on the gilts are linked to changes in the RPI.
Prospectuses for index-linked issues have a clause saying that, in the event
of a 'fundamental change' in the calculation of the RPI which would have a
'materially detrimental effect' on stockholders, the stock might have to be
redeemed.
Since the index-linked issues currently trade at a discount to their
inflation-adjusted value, that would be expensive for the government.
According to the Bank of England there are about Pounds 19bn of index-linked
gilts in issue.
Since prices excluding mortgage costs are rising faster than the RPI, it
would be hard to argue that a change would be 'materially detrimental'.
National Savings said its index-linked savings certificates, which rise
according to the RPI, would simply adjust to reflect any change in the
index's constituents.
Indexation clauses also crop up in occupational pensions legislation.
Limited price indexation - inflation-proofing parallel with the RPI with a
ceiling of 5 per cent - applies to deferred pensions payable to workers who
leave a company before retirement age.
The same protection will one day be applicable to pensions in payment -
legislation is on the statute book but has not yet been implemented.
There is a pensioner price index that excludes housing and has consequently
been rising more rapidly than the RPI recently. This PPI is not applied to
pension benefit, although the changes might mean it would move more closely
in line with the RPI.
Additional reporting by Philip Coggan, Michael Smith, Hugo Dixon, Richard
Evans and Neil Buckley
</TEXT>
