<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Momentum of recovery still in doubt: The strength of upturn
from economic recession in the US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW US forecasters envisage a repeat of last year, when a promising economic
recovery unexpectedly ground to a halt late in the summer. That said, this
week's report of a 17 per cent fall in housing starts in the single month of
April is not the kind of statistic destined to bolster confidence in the
economy's underlying momentum.
The drop in starts was partly a reaction to strong advances in preceding
months. But it was much more severe than expected, and by no means the only
discouraging news. Consumer confidence and car sales are still depressed;
claims for state unemployment insurance remain stubbornly high.
The Federal Reserve, meanwhile, is again embarrassed by sluggish monetary
growth, a problem that has plagued it for two years. M2, the main measure of
broad money, is only just above the lower limit of its 2.5-6.5 per cent
growth target.
The signs of continuing fragility are offset by positive indicators, such as
last week's report of a solid rise in industrial production in April, the
third consecutive monthly gain. Employment and retail sales have also risen
substantially since the year began.
Few economists are thus inclined to revise their forecasts, which mostly
point to growth of about 3 per cent at an annual rate in the second half of
the year.
But the negative indicators are fuelling demands that the Fed buy a little
extra insurance by nudging the federal funds rate (the cost of money in the
interbank market) a quarter-point lower, to 3.5 per cent. A move in the next
few weeks would exploit fully the scope for lower short-term rates created
last December when the Fed cut the discount rate a full percentage point to
3.5 per cent.
The discount rate is the rate at which the Fed lends to banks, but it is of
largely symbolic significance because banks rarely borrow from the central
bank. Analysts believe another small cut in the federal funds rate would be
helpful because it would probably trigger a half-point cut in banks' prime
lending rates to 6.0 per cent. This would reduce the cost of a range of
consumer and business loans.
Encouraging recent figures for inflation are seen as enhancing the Fed's
room to manoeuvre. The core consumer price index (food and energy excluded)
is still rising at an annual rate of nearly 4 per cent, but other measures,
including the gross domestic product deflator and an index of employment
costs, point to an underlying inflation rate of perhaps only 3 per cent.
The counter-argument is that short-term rates are already at their lowest
level for a generation. The Fed regards the failure of long bond yields to
decline significantly below 8 per cent as the more important brake on
economic growth.
The risk in cutting short-term rates further, with the recovery already
under way, is that expectations of inflation will rise, putting upward
pressure on bond yields. The Fed's failure to move yesterday probably
indicates that it believes further easing would be counter-productive in the
absence of more conclusive evidence of economic weakness.
In the short run, growth estimates are likely to be revised up. Last week's
report of a sharp rebuilding of corporate inventories in March is expected
to prompt an upward revision of GDP in the first quarter, to show growth at
an annual rate of 3 per cent rather than 2 per cent. This would be by far
the best performance since President George Bush took office early in 1989.
Some bulls, such as Mr Robert Brusca, chief economist at Nikko Securities in
New York, regard the first-quarter expansion as a launching pad for faster
growth - perhaps 4-5 per cent at an annual rate later in the year. But
others are more cautious. The fact that inventories have already rebounded,
say economists at JP Morgan, the New York bank, undercuts a potential prop
for growth in the second quarter.
Trade figures released yesterday were a warning that higher imports may
siphon off some of the stimulus from rising domestic demand. The trade
deficit widened to Dollars 5.8bn in March from Dollars 3.3bn, largely
because of a 4.5 per cent increase in imports.
Residential housing was the one sector of the economy to stage a 'normal'
recovery in the past year.
Rapid growth of personal consumption spending - another strong motor in the
first quarter - reflected special factors such as tax rebates and an
unsustainable fall in personal saving. The consumer is likely to remain
inhibited by historically high ratios of debt to income.
The biggest difference between this year and last is the substantially lower
level of short-term interest rates and a significant strengthening of
corporate balance sheets. This greatly reduces the risk of a 'triple dip'
into recession. But the Fed and other policy-makers would be unwise to take
the health of this erratic recovery for granted.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
