<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Perot scores with write-in primary votes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO MORE easy presidential primary victories for President George Bush and
Governor Bill Clinton in the US on Tuesday have again been overshadowed by
evidence of Mr Ross Perot's growing political appeal in the Far West and
nationally.
However, the Texan businessman was himself embarrassed yesterday by a
published report in which Senator Warren Rudman, a Republican from New
Hampshire, expressed his annoyance that Mr Perot seemed to have hired a
private investigator to make 'unauthorised inquiries' about his background.
Mr Rudman had been viewed as a possible vice-presidential running-mate for
Mr Perot, but said he had no interest in the prospect now.
The primary story from Oregon and Washington state was familiar. Mr Bush
scored 76 and 83 per cent respectively, against 22 and 13 per cent for Mr
Pat Buchanan, his remaining nominal challenger for the Republican
nomination. The president won 53 delegates in the two states to Mr
Buchanan's five, further padding his already sure majority to take to the
party convention.
Mr Clinton took 50 per cent of the vote in Oregon and 51 per cent in
Washington, against former California governor Jerry Brown's respective 35
per cent and 29 per cent, with former Massachusetts senator Paul Tsongas,
who has pulled out of the race, winning 11 and 16 per cent.
Washington state names convention delegates in separate caucuses. The 29 Mr
Clinton won in Oregon give him more than 1,850 of the 2,145 needed for the
Democratic nomination, which he may well secure in the final primaries -
including those of California, Ohio and New Jersey - on June 2.
Primaries next week, in Kentucky and Mr Clinton's native Arkansas, do not
award enough delegates to put him over the top.
However, in both the Democratic and Republican primaries this week, there
was evidence of a surprisingly large write-in vote for Mr Perot. Neither
state is obliged to disclose such votes immediately, but a CNN exit poll
suggested Mr Perot's support exceeded 10 per cent in Oregon and might have
carried some rural counties in Washington.
That said registered Democrats in Oregon preferred Mr Perot to Mr Clinton by
45 to 41 per cent. On the Republican side, 49 per cent went for Mr Bush and
40 per cent for Mr Perot.
The Pacific north-west has long been fertile ground for iconoclastic,
outsider politicians. In 1968, Oregon voted for Senator Eugene McCarthy over
Senator Robert Kennedy.
Several recent local polls have put Mr Perot ahead of the current pack.
The NBC-Wall Street Journal survey, out yesterday, had Mr Bush in the lead
with 35 per cent, followed by Mr Perot at 30 per cent and Mr Clinton with 27
per cent.
Moving closer to a formal declaration of candidacy, Mr Perot has now filed a
123-page financial disclosure statement with the Federal Election
Commission. This does not reveal a net worth - assumed to be over Dollars
3bn - but points to recent annual incomes from investments ranging from
about Dollars 25m to as much as Dollars 130m.
It suggests he has mostly been a conservative investor of his private
wealth, being heavily into tax-exempt municipal and utility bonds as well as
property, with some hedged bets in stock and currency options, and venture
capital partnerships. It was, according to the FEC, easily the largest such
statement of wealth received from a presidential aspirant.
It underlines his ability to finance a campaign from his own pocket without
recourse to federal funds.
The question of Mr Perot's ability to buy the presidency, as it were, may
become an issue late in the year.
</TEXT>
