<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / World Trade News: Developing countries look for better deal
on trade - Why the Generalised System of Preferences is regarded as only a
qualified success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RICH and poor countries are meeting in Geneva this week to look at ways of
strengthening the preferential trading arrangements for developing nations
under the so-called Generalised System of Preferences (GSP).
The GSP, first introduced in 1971 under the auspices of the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development (Unctad), provides for countries to
reduce or waive normal customs duties for Third World imports. As Unctad
shows in its latest review of the system, the GSP has been a qualified
success.
On the plus side, there are now some 15 schemes in operation, giving
preferential trade treatment to more than Dollars 60bn (Pounds 33bn) worth
of exports a year from over 100 developing countries.
Preferential imports into the OECD countries grew roughly twice as fast as
total imports between 1976 (when the US introduced its scheme) and 1989 (the
most recent available year). Product coverage has been expanded, and an
increasing number of poor countries are benefiting from the schemes. That
suggests the GSP is working as intended: promoting development through
trade.
But both sides concede the system also has serious weaknesses. Unctad
estimates that in 1989 only half the Dollars 226bn worth of imports from
developing countries subject to duties were covered by the GSP schemes -
mostly manufactures and semi-manufactures. Only half of those actually
received preferential treatment.
In addition, because the scheme is designed to encourage industrial exports,
advanced developing countries have grabbed the lion's share of the benefits.
The US dropped the four Asian 'tigers' - Hong Kong, Singapore, Taiwan and
South Korea - from its scheme in 1989.
Even so, the top 10 beneficiaries accounted for over 80 per cent of GSP
benefits granted by the US the following year, with Mexico alone garnering a
quarter.
Overall, the top 10 beneficiaries account for more than 60 per cent of GSP
preferences. The 40-plus least developed countries (LDCs), which are most
reliant on traditional commodity exports, had preferential exports in 1989
of a meagre Dollars 710m, or just over 1 per cent of total GSP exports by
all developing countries.
To remedy these deficiencies, developing countries, supported by the Unctad
secretariat, are pushing hard for broader product coverage of the GSP
schemes. These currently exclude many agricultural products and often
'sensitive' industrial goods such as textiles and footwear, the traditional
springboards for industrialisation. Third World nations also see expanded
coverage as partial compensation for the reduction in the value of
preferences that will inevitably follow from the general lowering of tariffs
now being negotiated in Gatt's Uruguay Round of global trade talks.
But for the first time developing countries openly acknowledge that the quid
pro quo for broader product coverage will be 'graduation' out of the GSP
schemes for the most successful Third World exporters. Australia is to
follow the US in graduating the Asian 'tigers' from 1993.
With the writing on the wall, developing countries are backing Unctad
proposals to draft multilateral 'graduation' guidelines in a bid to prevent
gross disparities between schemes and protect countries from arbitrary
delistings due to protectionist and other pressures.
In practice, many Third World nations see advantages in orderly graduation
in spreading GSP benefits more equitably. The indirect effects can also be
important. In Asia, the US decision has already led to plans for substantial
direct investment by South Korea and Taiwan in Thailand, Indonesia and
Malaysia to take advantage of trade preferences these countries still enjoy
in the American market.
The meeting is also discussing ways of remedying two other major defects in
the GSP scheme. The first is the fact that the schemes differ in operation
as well ascoverage. Thus the same good can satisfy origin rules for one
scheme and not for another. More difficult to tackle are differences due to
the use of GSP benefits to pressure countries over policies. The EC withdrew
GSP benefits for a time from South Korea in a row over intellectual property
protection.
The US routinely threatens to withdraw benefits to countries whose trade
policies it dislikes or which deny basic worker rights. Green criteria may
be added if US environmentalists have their way.
The second problem is the negation of GSP benefits by non-tariff measures,
which Unctad reckons (based on 11 OECD schemes) affect over one-fifth of
dutiable imports from developing countries. These measures can take the form
of quotas or ceilings, which limit benefits from preferences, or of
anti-dumping or anti-subsidy duties which can wipe them out altogether.
In the 1980s the World Bank voiced the views of many development experts
that the Third World had made a 'Faustian bargain' by relying on trade
preferences that could be withdrawn at will rather than playing an active
role in multilateral trade talks.
This week's meeting has revealed a new consensus that, while the GSP and
other preferential arrangements are no panacea, and certainly no substitute
for Gatt, they are a useful and worthwhile form of development assistance in
their own right.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6873</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBADZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / World Trade News: EC warned not to cut tariff on chips
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN semiconductor industry would be unlikely to survive if it
dismantled its 14 per cent tariff on chip imports, a report by the industry
market research group Dataquest says.
The EC is being pressed by the US and Japan to dismantle the tariff. It is
the only main industrial region that has kept tariffs on semiconductors. The
US, Canada and Japan suspended theirs in 1985. The EC Commission has offered
to cut the 14 per cent tariff on imports of integrated circuits by a third,
to 9 per cent, in exchange for reciprocal lowering of trade barriers.
Such a cut could sharply reduce competitiveness of the European industry and
is unlikely to lead to lower prices. The declining trend in European
manufacturers' own share of their market and low market prices of many chips
in Europe have created a situation where dismantling the tariff overnight
'is likely to spell the death of the European semiconductor industry,' Mr
Byron Harding, industry analyst at Dataquest, asserts.
The EC, the US and Japan are discussing the issue in Gatt's Uruguay Round.
Calls have come from within the US to reinstate the suspended 14 per cent
tariff on chip imports if Europe fails to cut its tariff. EC chip users have
been urging a cut in the tariff, which, they say, damages their
competitiveness.
The study indicates that despite the EC tariff on imports, prices of certain
chips in Europe have been as low as, or at times lower, than prices in other
main markets. This is because foreign makers are ready to sacrifice profit
to revenue, to boost European market penetration, Mr Harding believes.
* EC Semiconductor Tariffs and Related Issues. Published by Dataquest.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
