<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / World Trade News: Investors 'avoiding cheap-labour states'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN investors are no longer hunting for cheap labour in developing
countries - they want big markets, quality infrastructure and high skill
levels, according to the International Finance Corporation, the World Bank's
private lending arm.
Strongest growth in private investment has occurred in Chile, Papua New
Guinea and Thailand over the five years from 1986 to 1990, the study shows.
All three countries saw private investment more than doubled.
The strongest magnets for foreign direct investment are also countries with
high savings, the IFC says in its third annual study of trends in private
investment in developing countries.
'Most of the countries whose savings ratios improved, typically by virtue of
cuts in the public sector deficit, show a strong investment response by the
private sector,' it says.
Foreign investment has grown in the past decade, now accounting for 10 per
cent of all private investment in the 40 developing countries examined. Low
labour costs 'have been of diminishing importance', largely because they
account for a dwindling share of overall manufacturing costs, on average
10-15 per cent.
'Foreign investors are strongly influenced by structural factors such as
market size, the quality of infrastructure, the level of industrialisation
and the size of the existing stock of foreign investment,' the report adds.
Foreign investors display a 'herd' mentality in following where others have
invested. This is partly because the presence of other foreign companies
raises the likelihood of reliable suppliers and a pool of trained labour.
Political risk has not deterred investors where returns are sufficiently
high.
</TEXT>
