FT  21 MAY 92 / World Trade News: New HK trade commissioner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S new trade commissioner in Hong Kong - equivalent to Britain's
ambassador to the territory - is to be Mr Stephen Day, a career diplomat who
has for the past five years been ambassador in Tunisia, writes David
Dodwell.
Hong Kong's anomalous colonial status, under which the governor is the
queen's representative in the territory, but at the same time speaks for
Hong Kong rather than Britain, makes Mr Day the UK's top spokesman for
British interests - particularly those of business.
Hong Kong is the UK's 15th largest export market and an important
springboard for business in the region.
UK visible exports to Hong Kong in 1991 were Pounds 1.38bn. The value of the
market would be even greater if invisibles, and goods transiting Hong Kong
for China, were included.
