<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / India's satellite launch success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By K K SHARMA and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI, MADRAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDIA yesterday successfully launched a satellite into orbit using a locally
developed rocket. The launch follows two failures four years ago.
The launch of the rocket, the third version of the 'augmented satellite
launch vehicle', took place at the Sriharikota launching station of the
Indian Space Research Organisation (Isro), north of Madras.
The satellite is part of a series launched by the Indian government for
research purposes. Although designed by Isro, components for the rocket and
the satellite were obtained from various sources, including the US which
last week banned exports to Isro because it had bought cyrogenic rocket
technology from Russia.
The ban is bound to slow India's space programme which the government claims
is for peaceful purposes and not for development of missile technology, as
the US alleges. Prof U R Rao, chairman of Isro, said after the launching
that it was a 'total success'.
The two tasks of proving the functioning of the rocket and orbiting the
satellite had been completed successfully, he said.
India issued charges yesterday against the head of a Sri Lankan Tamil
guerrilla group for the murder a year ago, of Mr Rajiv Gandhi, the former
prime minister, Reuter reports from Madras.
The special investigation team looking into Mr Gandhi's killing on May 21,
1991, charged Mr Velupillai Prabhakaran, head of the Tamil Tigers, and his
intelligence chief, Mr Pottu Amman. India has asked Sri Lanka to arrest and
extradite Mr Prabhakaran.
