<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Kings fall out over Jerusalem shrine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IN ONE of those arcane and highly personalised disputes that swirl about the
Arab world, King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and King Hussein of Jordan find
themselves in potentially bitter competition over renovations to Islam's
third holiest shrine after Mecca and Medina.
It is not clear who will emerge with the privilege of paying for repairs to
the Al Aqsa mosque and other holy places in Jerusalem, but the Saudi
monarch, whose personal wealth is put at Dollars 18bn, certainly has the
wherewithal.
The contest of the custodians of Islam's holiest shrines - the dispute owes
more to past rivalries than present differences - began earlier this year
when Unesco appealed for help to restore Al Aqsa's distinctive gold dome and
marble facade on the site where the Prophet Mohammed, according to Moslem
belief, ascended to heaven.
King Fahd responded swiftly, offering Dollars 70m for renovations to all
Islamic sites in Arab East Jerusalem. King Hussein, whose Ministry of
Religious Endowments is still responsible for Jerusalem's Islamic holy
places, felt obliged to try to match the Saudi monarch's largesse where Al
Aqsa is concerned. He offered Dollars 8.25m, and battle was joined.
Not that the two men are likely to be consulting each other. King Fahd has
not spoken to his Jordanian counterpart since King Hussein expressed
sympathy for Iraq's position early in the Gulf crisis. And worse from
Jordan's point of view, Saudi Arabia has cut off aid that had helped to keep
the impoverished Hashemite kingdom afloat.
Behind the battle of the dollars lies a complex story of family rivalries
that date back to early this century when Abdul-Aziz Ibn Saud, the
warrior-founder of the House of Saud, drove the Hashemites from their
strongholds in the Hejaz along the west coast of what is now Saudi Arabia,
including Mecca and Medina.
King Hussein re-opened wounds during the Gulf crisis when he asked subjects
to refer to him as Sharif Hussein in memory of his great-grandfather, Sherif
of Mecca, who helped inspire the Arab revolt against Ottoman Turks in 1916.
The dispute among Arab royalty has been further complicated by Egyptian
intervention, and more recently by the Palestinians in the person of Mr
Yassir Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organisation who is
risking an unholy row with King Hussein over his apparent endorsement of the
Fahd offer.
Egypt's press reported this week that Egyptian engineers, working under the
auspices of Saudi Arabia, were being despatched to Jerusalem to examine the
Islamic sites.
Jordan, which controlled East Jerusalem and the West Bank until the 1967
war, was not amused, and strong criticism was voiced in its press.
Enter, at this point, Mr Arafat, who expressed his deep gratitude this week
to King Fahd. 'In the name of our struggling Palestinian people. . . we
would like to express our many thanks and brotherly gratitude for your wise
decision,' he said in a message to the Saudi monarch.
Cynical observers might suggest Mr Arafat was trying to curry favour with
wealthy Saudis whose anger at PLO support for Iraq in the Gulf crisis knew
almost no bounds.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6884</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Bonn will defend east's shipbuilders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL and CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE German government said yesterday it would fight European Commission
proposals to cut capacity in the ailing east German shipbuilding industry.
The Commission agreed plans to lift the ceiling on state aid to 36 per cent
of contract value for yards opened before October 1990.
All aid would have to be paid before the end of 1993. But yards will have to
be closed and jobs cut to ensure shipbuilding capacity in the new German
Lander falls by 40 per cent before the end of 1995.
Other Community shipbuilders, notably the Spanish, have campaigned hard
against relaxing the rules for the east German yards.
The Bonn Economics Ministry said it could accept the increase in the
ceiling, which compares with an EC-wide limit of 9 per cent for production
aid. But a spokesman added: 'In the light of cuts already undertaken,
reduction of capacity on this scale will give us great difficulties.'
The proposals will be discussed by EC ministers next month. Germany alone
will be unable to block agreement by a majority of other member states.
The Commission said its proposals were in line with policy in other member
states and that apart from the increased ceiling, the normal rules on aid to
shipyards would be applied.
Lightning strikes among printers hit production of yesterday's German
newspapers after Tuesday's arbitration talks failed to produce a pay deal.
IG Medien, the main union involved, and one of the most militant in Germany,
said it would call a strike ballot immediately if there was no result from
conciliation talks scheduled for today. Further disruption was expected last
night.
The threat of strikes also loomed over paper manufacturing yesterday.
