<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Consumer credit rise adds to Bundesbank fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BUNDESBANK yesterday again voiced concern about the rapid expansion of
German money supply, coinciding with a strong rise in consumer credit, and
weak growth in capital formation.
In spite of adjusting its calculation of money supply growth in March
downwards, from an estimated 9.75 per cent to a corrected annual rate of 9.4
per cent, the central bank emphasised that the expansion had accelerated
again: from a rate of 8.9 per cent in January, 8.6 per cent in February, and
now 9.4 per cent in March.
At the same time it published figures for the growth of west German private
indebtedness for consumption in 1991, showing that it expanded by DM28.6bn
(Pounds 9.7bn), compared with DM23.7bn in 1990, DM21.1bn in 1989, and only
DM13bn in 1988.
The other particular concern expressed in the Bundesbank's monthly report is
the failure of capital formation to match the growth in credit to the
private sector, underlining the fact that credit is being used primarily for
consumption.
The trend reflects in part the massive transfers of capital from west
Germany to the east, to finance consumption rather than a corresponding
expansion in investment there. But it also shows that western consumers are
financing their spending increasingly from credit, and not income - and that
easterners are rapidly acquiring the habit.
The pessimistic tone in a series of articles by the bank's economics
department underlines the determination of its governing council to maintain
a tight monetary policy until the growth of money supply and inflation are
brought down.
Even the fact that industrial production in the west expanded by 3 per cent
in the first quarter, compared with the last quarter of 1991, was
discounted: year on year, the growth was only 1 per cent, and the reason for
the strong recovery was a combination of unnaturally low production at the
end of last year, and a very mild winter, outweighing the normal seasonal
adjustment.
The independent German Economics Institute (DIW) in Berlin published its own
estimate yesterday of real 3 per cent growth in gross domestic product in
the first quarter - in spite of the fact that GDP in eastern Germany
actually fell by 2 per cent. The institute said that a sustained recovery in
the east German economy was still not in sight, although, thanks to the high
level of earning from 'commuters' travelling to west Germany to work, the
gross national product of the east actually increased by 4 per cent compared
with the first quarter of 1991.
</TEXT>
