<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / European corps units to remain separate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE and Germany have agreed that their European defence corps, to be set
up by President Francois Mitterrand and Chancellor Helmut Kohl tomorrow,
will consist of separate national units under a joint command.
Germany has rejected a French proposal to assign troops fully to the corps
in peacetime, insisting that they remain 'nationally assigned' just as they
are in Nato, Bonn officials said yesterday.
The corps is nonetheless seen as an important move in creating a European
defence identity, within Nato and complementary to it, but also capable of
being used in non-Nato operations within and outside the territory of the
alliance. The corps will be set up 'in the perspective of European union',
and put under the umbrella of the nine-nation Western European Union.
It is clear, however, that the German troops in the corps may not be able to
participate in all its potential operations because of the constitutional
restriction on combat missions outside the Nato area.
Mr Volker Ruhe, German defence minister, believes it will be possible to
agree on a change in the constitution allowing use of German troops in
United Nations peace-keeping operations, without geographical restriction,
by the end of the year. But he admits it could be 10 years before they take
part in other activities.
The Franco-German agreement provides for three precise uses of the corps:
the common defence of the Nato allies, the maintenance and restoration of
peace, and humanitarian missions. A planning staff will be set up in July,
and the corps should come into existence in 1995, with a headquarters in
Strasbourg.
From the German point of view, a major benefit will be in bringing the
French troops in the corps openly under the Nato umbrella for the defence of
the allies.
Europe's new muddle army, Page 20
</TEXT>
