<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Swiss cultures clash over request to join Community: The
decision, says Ian Rodger, has aroused both joy and suspicion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SWISS government's decision this week to make an early application to
enter the European Community may turn out to be a case where Swiss French
logic crumbles before Swiss German stubbornness.
Reaction to the decision has certainly been very different in the country's
two main linguistic communities. In French-speaking Romandy, which has long
had a cosmopolitan culture, there was near-unalloyed joy; in the more
inward-looking German-speaking cantons suspicion prevailed.
Neue Zurcher Zeitung, Zurich's leading newspaper, relegated the news to page
21 and grumbled about the 'undignified' way it leaked out. Even strong
advocates of joining the EC worried that the move was premature and risked
undermining public support for two other Europe-related plans which are to
be put to plebiscites later this year.
Most Swiss business leaders believe that their country must have closer ties
with the EC if the country's economy is to thrive, but they suspect that the
only way to convince the independent-minded German-speaking majority is by
proceeding very gradually.
That had also been the strategy until last October of the federal
government. With the governments of the other six member states of the
European Free Trade Association (Efta), Bern was negotiating a trade
agreement with the EC to create a European Economic Area (EEA).
Even that would be tough enough for many Swiss to accept. The idea was that
the Efta countries would take on the four freedoms of the EC's single
market, meaning Switzerland would open its doors to EC workers and home
buyers and remove several mechanisms that protected professionals and many
businesses from EC competitors.
If all that was accepted and implemented, there would be plenty of time to
try to cajole the Swiss into joining the EC itself. And even if they
ultimately decided not to join, the Swiss economy would already be getting
virtually all the benefits of membership.
But in October, the government announced that joining the EC was official
policy and that the EEA should be considered only a step towards it. From
there, it was, as Swiss President Rene Felber said yesterday, only logical
to actually send in an application.
Coming when the country is approaching two plebiscites on the EEA treaty,
this decision had the appearance of an attempt to get a Euro-bandwagon
going.
In September, a referendum is to be held on a proposal to spend SFr30bn
(Pounds 11.1bn) to dig two new rail tunnels through the Alps. This is part
of the EEA agreement intended to resolve the long-running dispute over
transit rights through Switzerland and Austria for EC lorries, and it was
always going to face strong opposition from both environmentalists and
people worried about the cost.
Then, probably in December, the referendum on the EEA treaty itself will be
held.
Both a majority of the population and a majority of the 26 cantons must
approve the proposals. Most cantons are German-speaking and their lingering
suspicion of international organisations was shown on Sunday when they
approved by only the slimmest of margins a proposal to join the
International Monetary Fund.
The IMF would not directly hurt any Swiss. The EEA, on the other hand, would
cause considerable upheaval, especially among the small and medium-sized
businesses that are the core of the Swiss German economy. As Mr Pierre
Borgeaud, president of the national business association, Vorort, pointed
out, 'the feeling of being threatened is most strongly felt in eastern
(German-speaking) Switzerland'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
