<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Thailand's king seals accord to end violence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET and PETER UNGPHAKORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE KING of Thailand last night sealed an agreement between the government
and pro-democracy demonstrators to end four days of confrontation in which
at least 40 people have been killed.
King Bhumipol Adulyadej, the country's 64-year-old constitutional monarch,
summoned Gen Suchinda Kraprayoon, the prime minister, and Mr Chamlong
Srimuang, the opposition leader arrested on Monday, and told them to make
peace for the sake of the people and the economy of Thailand.
Both Gen Suchinda and Mr Chamlong were seen on television crawling on their
knees into the presence of the king.
In a televised address soon afterwards, Gen Suchinda said Mr Chamlong was
being freed, along with all others arrested during the bloody clashes.
MrChamlong, sitting alongside him, appealed to protesters to refrain from
violence.
The agreement will bring relief to Thais and to foreign investors, although
there are still many uncertainties.
Most Thais think Gen Suchinda will have to step down and may even have to
leave the country after presiding over the shooting of protesters, but he
and his supporters appear reluctant to relinquish control.
Gen Suchinda, the former armed forces chief appointed as premier by a
coalition of pro-military parties which won elections in March, is not an
elected MP and is likely to have to resign within a month. He may choose to
stand in a by-election to retain his post, although he has previously
rejected this course.
He said that he would ask parliament to meet on Monday to amend the
constitution, one of the key demands of the demonstrators, who want to
reduce the influence of the military in politics and restrict the post of
prime minister to elected MPs.
Mr Chamlong, himself a former army general but a man noted for his campaigns
against corruption, told Thais: 'I ask you not to support any people who are
being disorderly, so that the situation can return to normal as fast as
possible.' He added: 'The situation has eased because of the good offices of
the king.'
King Bhumipol told the two men to use the good offices of Mr Prem
Tinsulanonda, prime minister between 1980 and 1988 and one of his closest
advisers.
'You, especially you two, General Suchinda and Major General Chamlong, must
turn towards each other and not confront each other in order to solve this
problem,' the king said.
'In the end people no longer know why they are fighting. All they want is to
win and this is dangerous.'
Before the midnight announcement of a deal, there had been feverish
speculation in Bangkok that Gen Suchinda would be overthrown by disaffected
colleagues in the military.
Bangkok remained under a night curfew after the king's intervention and
troops continued to patrol the streets.
But thousands of demonstrators manned barricades around the Ramkamheang
University in the capital's north-east in defiance of the curfew.
Gunshots could be heard elsewhere, even after Gen Suchinda's announcement.
Undimmed loyalty, Page 4
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
