<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / EC farm policy on verge of wide-ranging reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE MOST radical reform of the European Community's Common Agricultural
Policy was within reach last night as EC farm ministers were locked in a
second night of hard bargaining.
Agreement on the reform would send a signal that the Community is at last
serious about restraining its chronic overproduction of food - now running
at about 20 per cent over consumption and rising.
A deal could also clear the way for a conclusion of the Uruguay Round
negotiations to liberalise world trade. These talks have been stalled for
the past 18 months because the US and other agri-exporters regard EC
commitments to cut farm subsidies as inadequate.
As well as clearing the food mountains, the reform could bring cheaper food.
It could also gradually bring about a cleaner rural environment by making
intensive farming less economically attractive.
Independent estimates calculate that the reform could cut Ecu15bn-Ecu20bn
(Pounds 10.5bn-Pounds 14bn) off EC food bills, with 15-20 per cent cuts on
pork and poultry, 15 per cent reductions on beef, 7 per cent cheaper butter
and 3 per cent off bread.
Mr John Gummer, the UK agriculture minister, predicted that a CAP reform
deal was 'more likely to be late tonight than next time'. Mr Louis Mermaz,
representing France, the EC's agri-superpower, said that in broad terms 'we
accept the proposal . . we are very satisfied'.
The main obstacle to a deal was a brewing north-south row over demands by
Italy, Spain and Greece for the right to produce more milk than they are
allowed under the EC quota system - which none of the three has rigorously
applied. Their partners appeared likely to concede to Spain and Greece, as
relative newcomers to the EC, but remained obdurate on Italy.
Ministers were last night taking turns to negotiate bilaterally, on this
issue and other loose ends, with the European Commission and EC presidency,
before regrouping for a final push at about 4am.
Mr Ray MacSharry, EC agriculture commissioner, and Mr Arlindo Cunha,
Portuguese farm minister currently chairing the council of ministers,
reached a compromise yesterday morning which preserved the radical structure
of the Commission's blueprint and offered a number of sweeteners to farm
interests.
The reform includes subsidised prices cut towards world market levels, and
full compensation paid directly to the farmer. For all but small farmers
this refund is conditional on their taking 15 per cent of their land out of
production. This scheme should slice into oversupply while buttressing farm
incomes.
'What we are involved in here is a totally different philosophy to what has
existed for 30 years,' said Mr MacSharry.
The main cut is likely to be a 29 per cent reduction on the subsidised price
of cereals over three years. This will virtually eliminate the export
subsidies at the core of the Uruguay Round impasse and looks set to be
endorsed in spite of the misgivings of Germany, whose inefficient
agricultural sector has dictated the high prices of the CAP.
Mr Ignaz Kiechle, the German farm minister, appears to have come to this
meeting with instructions to do a deal, and last night said he was ready to
conclude the reform debate.
Basis for a deal, Page 38
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
</DOC>
