<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (16): From office to mosque - Religious
affairs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR HAMDI MERT's office, complete with the standard portrait of Ataturk above
his desk and the Turkish flag beside it, looks exactly like that of any
other senior government official.
With a departmental budget this year of TL 2.3 trillion (Pounds 200m) and
84,000 personnel, it is a substantial government department by Turkish
standards. A glance outside the window, however, at the giant dome of the
Kocatepe Mosque, complete with an inscription in Arabic letters, quickly
reminds visitors that Mr Mert's office is not quite like any other
department of state.
He is deputy president of the Department of Religious Affairs, the state
body which administers all Sunni Shi'ite religious activity in Turkey, but
is also a spiritual body. About 69,000 of the department's staff are hodjas
(clergymen) serving mosques.
From time to time, Mr Mert himself puts aside his grey suit and tie and dons
religious garb. He then leads prayers in the mosque (where the president and
prime minister may be among the worshippers) and delivers sermons.
Is this a contradictory situation in a state which claims to be secular? No,
says Mr Mert. He believes that some sort of secularism, in the sense of a
division of duties between spiritual and worldly affairs, arises naturally
from the Islamic religion itself.
His superior, the President of Religious Affairs (PRA) is a direct successor
of the Seyhulislam, the traditional head of the Sunni Islamic clergy in the
Ottoman Empire. Religious and political boundaries, as elsewhere in the
Middle East, tend to overlap.
As Mr Mert sees it, the duty of the PRA is to attend to the religious side
of citizen's lives and to instil a sense of unity. 'We are all Muslims,' he
says, 'no matter what particular rite of Islam we happen to observe.' He
also believes in inter-faith dialogue: the PRA holds meetings with
representatives of other religions, including Christianity, from time to
time.
'Turkey is the only secular country in the Muslim world. We Turks are both
Muslim and secular, but the west doesn't seem to accept this fact,' he says.
Some Christian clergy serving the less than 1 per cent of Turkish citizens
who are non-Muslims but include ancient and exotic linguistic groups such as
the Chaldians and Syriacs alongside the better-known Greeks and Syriacs,
challenge this view.
'How can you call a country secular where religious education is
compulsory?' asks one Catholic priest, pointing out that during the 1980s,
Islamic religious education in schools was made compulsory not just to
secular Turks but also for non-Muslims. After discreet lobbying by the
French, the obligation was suspended two years ago.
Mr Mert says, however, that he believes that religious instruction is a
moderating force. 'Religious fanatics tend to come from those who do not
attend the religious vocational schools,' he says.
There has been a steady expansion of religious education in Turkey over the
last decade. About 350,000 students are now enrolled in religious secondary
schools, alongside the western-style lycee system, and they are now allowed
to enter universities though not the military cadet schools afterwards.
Alarm at growing fundamentalism, however, is less strong in Turkey today
than it was before the Gulf War. Turkey's western middle class is no longer
as fearful as it once of being swamped in a tide of religious revivalism.
'Fundamentalism has peaked in this country,' says one Istanbul professor
confidently.
It is, nonetheless, still a powerful force. Religious groups collect funds
to sponsor mosque-building and religious schools in the Turkish-speaking
republics of the former Soviet Union.
Proposals to revive the fetva, a formal Islamic comment on whether a course
of action is correct or not from the religious point of view, were mooted
recently and strongly condemned in the press.
The High Islamic Council, a committee of senior clergy and theologians, has
also been reactivated after more than a decade. Mr Mert denies Turkish press
reports that the council is planning any kind of religious reformation,
something that some Turkish nationalists have hankered after since Ataturk's
days.
'Our religion is an unchanging system. We believe it is the final revealed
religion, so reform is out of the question,' he says.
He is more coy about a surprising initiative taken by the PRA in the last
six months: the opening of a formal dialogue with representatives of
non-Sunni Moslems in Turkey. About one in five of all Turks are Alevis, a
version of Twelver Shi'ism.
Alevis do not worship in mosques but in cemevis or community houses, where
food and wine are passed around, and members of the congregation speak in
turn, rather as in a Quaker meeting, and there is dancing.
In addition, Alevis have an awkward relationship with the state. They are
given no money to finance their mosques or clergy - and their children have
to receive Sunni religious instruction in school.
There are deeper tensions below the surface. Alevis strongly supported the
secularising reforms introduced by Ataturk and they tend to vote for
centre-left political parties against Turkey's right-wing majority.
Some Sunnis regard Alevis as non-Moslem (though Mr Mert says he is not among
them) and there were outbreaks of intercommunal fighting before the 1980
coup when Sunnis attacked Alevi immigrants in some towns.
The attacks were promptly and effectively suppressed by the Turkish
military, but they reawakened old communal memories going back to the day in
the 16th century when the Sultan Selim the Grim slaughtered 40,000 Alevis in
a single night, accusing them of support for the Ottoman empire's Iranian
enemies.
'Some sort of recognition will have to be given to this country's largest
religious minority before much longer,' says one Alevi intellectual in
Ankara. Cultural associations - such as one to commemorate the work of Pir
Sultan Abdal, a politically radical folk poet who was hanged by the Ottoman
authorities - are now emerging, where only a few years ago plays and poems
about Pir Sultan were officially banned.
The dialogue with the state has exposed differences inside the Alevi
Community between conservatives (who seem to favour the new dialogue) and
radicals who suspect the PRA's motives. The ancient tensions may be
disappearing, but they are doing so only slowly.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
