</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (13): Investors go elsewhere  -Stock
Exchange
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TURKS HAVE been living with high inflation for so long that they tend to
take it for granted. Yet nowhere does the damage to the economy show more
clearly than in the country's stock exchange at Istanbul.
The market was set up in its present form in 1986 and, despite Turkish
misgivings about unfettered capitalism, the bourse has established itself as
a permanent feature of the country's business scene. Small investors quickly
took to the idea that there are times when company stock can offer a better
return than more familiar investments in gold, foreign currency, or one-year
bank deposits.
The number of companies whose shares are traded and the number of shares
traded has also been rising rapidly. The average number of shares traded
each day rose from 6,224 in 1990 to 18,345 in 1991.
Despite the striking increase in volumes, the market's best days came as
long ago as the summer of 1989 when it was one of the best-performing
markets anywhere. The last notable rally was in February last year. For most
of the first quarter of this year, the index has lingered around the 4,000
mark.
In April, Turkey was stuck at the bottom of the emerging markets performance
chart. Yet the country has obvious investor potential. Why the lacklustre
performance?
For much of the winter, political uncertainty was widely given as part of
the reason for the market's sluggishness. But Mr Demirel and his team have
turned out not to be foes of the exchange. Quite the opposite: the coalition
government plans to raise more funds than its predecessor did through
privatisation operations.
The main reason for the market's dull performance is that local investors -
most of them small short-term investors - have been putting their money into
other investments, ranging from treasury bonds to foreign currency deposits,
which offer a better return under present circumstances.
Considering that Turkey had something of a recession last year in which
manufacturing industry grew by only 2.6 per cent (a dire figure by the
standards of the last two decades), things might be worse.
There have been few share price collapses, but cement companies, the market
star performers in 1991, have done less well recently, and food and beverage
stocks have tended to lead the market.
All this is fairly discouraging to foreign investors, at least for the time
being. 'They are going to be loath to invest in Turkey until they see some
sign of a sustainable decrease in the country's inflation rate,' says Mr
Peter Bennett, portfolio manager of Morgan Stanley's Turkish Investment Fund
which is listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
He believes that sooner or later, Turkey will have to follow most of the
Latin American countries and take steps to bring down inflation and that
until then the market will not be able to tap its full potential.
That would mean a government decision to bring inflation well below 20 per
cent: something which does not seem to be in prospect at the moment, even
though some economists forecast a slight dip in Turkish inflation by the
year end.
Meanwhile the government has pushed through legislation which should help
the market grow. Companies will be able to raise funds by issuing futures
and asset-backed securities provided they have an approved rating.
The Capital Markets Board will be given new powers to curb irregularities by
brokerage houses, including the issue of forged share certificates.
Abuses such as insider dealing will become punishable for the first time and
independent auditors will be made responsible for any deficiencies in
company accounts.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6907</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAC1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (10): Cities try to close gap with Europe -
The quality of life in Ankara and Istanbul
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY 11m of Turkey's 58m inhabitants live in two cities, Ankara, the
national capital, and Istanbul, Turkey's main business centre and largest
city.
The citizens of Ankara and Istanbul make up the overwhelming majority of
Turkey's political and business class, its civil service and intelligentsia,
and its growing consumer middle class. They also pay most of the country's
taxes.
Until the late 1980s, however, it is probably fair to say that conditions in
both cities were more reminiscent of the third world than of the typical
European metropolis. Migration from the countryside enlarged their
populations by around 6 or 7 per cent each year. Most of the new arrivals
lived in vast shanty-town districts.
Services and urban infrastructure were correspondingly poor. Interruptions
in water and electricity supplies were more or less routine. Public
transport was limited and there was little public housing development or
planning.
Since the late 1980s, this picture has been changing. For a start, the pace
of migration has slackened slightly, though Ankara's 2.8m inhabitants are
still growing by an estimated 100,000 a year and Istanbul's 8m population
rises by over 6 per cent annually.
More importantly, the population of the two cities has come to expect
improved services. In both Ankara and Istanbul, social democrat mayors are
struggling to improve basic utilities such as water, sewerage, gas supply
and transport.
There have been some striking successes. The previous Motherland party
administration in Istanbul under former Mayor Bedrettin Dalan (who has since
switched parties and represents Istanbul for the ruling True Path party in
the present parliament) installed the city's first ever sewage treatment
plant and managed to improve the water supply.
In Ankara, the city's council, under a joint venture with British Gas, has
fitted 200,000 homes to take Siberian natural gas. A second stage is planned
shortly. As a result, this winter was Ankara's first without heavy air
pollution for half a century.
'My aim is to bring conditions in Ankara at least to the level of the
nearest European capital cities, such as Athens, over the next three to five
years. Ankara is going to be one of the best cities in the region,' says Mr
Murat Karayalcin, the capital's mayor.
In pursuit of this goal, Mr Karayalcin has drawn up a masterplan to take the
city, until now something of a Cinderella among those in the Mediterranean
basin, through to 2015 and is embarking on a range of projects, from a light
rail system and metro through to a new cultural and exhibition centre.
The city's annual budget of TL7 trillion (Dollars 1.2bn) includes investment
spending of between TL2-3 trillion. Spending on infrastructure has overtaken
that on new housing for the first time in Ankara's post-war history.
Revenues come almost entirely from a central government block grant:
municipalities in Turkey have very limited ability to raise cash through
local taxes.
The Ankara metropolitan municipality has also started tapping syndicated
loans on the international market and earlier this year raised Dollars 230m
in bonds and now has a credit rating in Frankfurt and Tokyo.
The challenge of developing Ankara, however, is relatively modest compared
with Istanbul, a city which takes in up to 500,000 rural migrants a year and
which has become a vast sprawling megalopolis, part of a conurbation in
which one can drive for over 50 miles without seeing the countryside.
'We would like to see the government developing new industrial centres in
other parties of Turkey such as Zonguldak and Bolu and in the eastern Black
Sea around Trabzon and Artvin to take some of the migrant pressure off
Istanbul,' says Mr Icen Bortucene, the Istanbul Metropolitan Municipality's
deputy secretary-general.
Istanbul's development budget this year will be around TL5.9 trillion, and
it already has an international debt burden inherited from the mid-1980s,
costing it around Dollars 600m a year to service.
'It is relatively small. We certainly are not fearful about further foreign
borrowing for important projects,' says Mr Bortucene.
Asked how the city plans to spend its cash, Mr Bortucene has a simple
answer. 'We want to make life less intolerable for the ordinary citizen.
Quite simple investments in transport for example could stop large numbers
of our people losing up to three hours a day travelling to work and back.
Transport at present is so poor that sometimes you see clerical workers
hitching lifts to and from work.'
Like Ankara, Istanbul is also building its own light rail mass transport. A
first stage of 8km has already been completed and work is currently under
way to build a 26km extension. Work on a second tramway system also starts
this month, while the city's bus fleet has taken on an extra 800km capacity
with the purchase of a 845 new buses.
Again like Ankara, Istanbul's planners are ambitious. The city is competing
with other international cities to host the Olympic games early in the next
century.
'We want Istanbul to be a world metropolis, serving not only Turkey but also
the world as a whole. Its international economic, trading and political
importance has changed enormously since the break up of Soviet Union,' says
Mr Bortucene.
Shortage of cash is, however, not the only problem standing in the city's
way. The sprawling megalopolis is run by an equally unwieldy administration,
working more or less along Ottoman lines with paper dossiers travelling
slowly between departments inside the city's vast municipal headquarters.
Reliable statistics are scarce. Istanbul does not appear to have the tightly
focused urban development plans which have been produced in Ankara. It also
has other problems - including a powerfully entrenched local underworld or
mafia - which if it exists at all in the capital is far less effective.
Mr Bortucene believes some sort of administrative overhaul is long overdue,
especially in management and information technology. 'We lack a good
management information system, especially where specific projects are
concerned,' he says.
Just how swiftly such changes can be achieved remains to be seen. On the
other hand, Istanbul is a genuinely powerful and rich industrial city, where
average per capita income is around Dollars 10,000, much closer to the
income levels of a developed country than to those of the rest of Turkey -
even if income distribution is highly uneven.
That fact seems to be slowly driving the city to close the gap with Europe.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
