<DOCNO>FT922-6908</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAC0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (11): Aiming to rise to the top - Profile,
Mayor Karayalcin of Ankara
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW JOBS in Turkey are quite as thankless as that of mayor of Ankara.
Trying to satisfy the insatiable expectations an electorate for rapid
benefits in the quality of life while having to rely on inadequate financial
and administrative resources is a daunting prospect for even the most
ambitious politician.
None of the mayors of the Turkish capital in the last 15 years has served
more than one term in office and none has made a successful transition to
national politics.
Even Mr Bedrettin Dalan, the ultra-popular Motherland party mayor of
Istanbul in the 1980s, sits as a backbencher in Mr Demirel's True Path
party.
At seven o'clock in the evening on a typical working day, Mr Murat
Karayalcin, Ankara's social democratic mayor, still has a chaotic and
gruelling schedule ahead of him.
Crowds of visitors mill around in the anteroom to the mayor's office. The
streets outside are even more chaotic: in normal times they are the main
arteries for the city's traffic.
Now, they have been closed to traffic for months. Only a few of them will
make it to the relative calm of the mayor's inner sanctum, a grandiose
dark-panelled room inherited by Mr Karayalcin from his predecessors.
Once inside they meet a quiet, unpretentious social democrat, who plays down
political antagonisms between himself and his predecessors and has more the
flavour of the civil servant or technocrat about him than that of Tammany
Hall.
Yet Mr Karayalcin is clearly an ambitious man, who is pledged to making
Ankara one of the best cities in the region and is widely tipped as an
eventual leader of Turkey's social democrats some day if he ever does make
the transition to national politics.
Meanwhile Mr Karayalcin is trying to leave lasting imprint on a teeming city
of 2.8m people. Though much smaller and more orderly than Istanbul, Ankara
lacks some of its rival's advantages: it is not primarily a business centre
but an administrative capital. There is much less wealth around and also a
less glittering cultural life, though Ankara has been a large and important
city since pre-Roman times.
Like most of his voters, Mr Karayalcin was not born in the city he now
presides over, but was brought up on the Black Sea coast, arriving in Ankara
in his late teens for high school and university.
He cut his political teeth in student politics in the late 1960s and early
1970s and graduated from the political science faculty of Ankara University,
the training ground of the Turkish civil service.
In the middle 1970s, he spent two years at the institute of development
studies of the University of East Anglia in the UK studying urban-biased
models for economic development. He retains fairly strong links with the UK.
When the social democrats were in office in Turkey at the end of the 1970s,
Mr Karayalcin became an undersecretary in the Ministry of Rural Affairs and
then worked in the city's municipal administration and was appointed head of
Batikent, a large co-operative housing development on the west of Ankara,
organising the construction of 200,000 housing units.
The aim behind the Batikent project was to develop services and housing well
outside the traditional boundaries of Ankara and so relieve pressure on the
congested centre of the city.
A year or two after the project got going, the 1980 Turkish military coup
swept away the country's civilian political system.
The social democrat mayor of Ankara was replaced by a retired general whose
most striking action as the capital's mayor was to order that all the houses
in the citadel should be painted blue, apparently to discourage rodents.
Mr Karayalcin kept a low profile through the years of military rule and
unlike almost every other social democrat official managed to remain at his
post. The Batikent project moved ahead.
When democracy began to make a gradual return to Turkey in 1983, Mr
Karayalcin rejected advances from the Motherland party and joined the
newly-founded Social Democracy Populist party (SHP) of Mr Erdal Inonu and in
1989, he ran successfully for mayor. He has generally supported Mr Inonu,
rather than his rivals in the fierce factional in-fighting which dogs the
SHP.
'Life is difficult at the moment for social democrats all over the world,
not just in Turkey,' says Mr Karayalcin. 'We have to work out some sort of
practical response to the ideological challenges we are facing.'
As mayor however Mr Karayalcin's sights have been set on less contentious
matters such as infrastructural projects, ranging from the conversion of
Ankara's gas supply to natural gas to new light rail and road systems. He is
a good administrator and the changes have meant less disruption to the daily
life of the capital's population than has been the case in Istanbul.
Nevertheless, his fortunes are clearly bound up with the future of Turkey's
ailing and bitterly divided social democratic movement.
Mr Karayalcin sees a fresh chance to reunite it in current efforts to revive
the pre-1980 Republican People's Party, shut down along with other parties
by the military junta in 1981 in what Mr Karayalcin describes as a legal
disaster.
'Its closure was a mistake and putting it right would be a suitable
opportunity to reunite the left-of-centre in Turkey,' the mayor says.
Founded by Ataturk, modern Turkey's founder and national hero, in 1923, the
RPP was Turkey's largest party in the 1970s and none of its post-coup
successors has ever managed fully to take its place. The parliamentary
centre-left in Turkey is currently divided into four or five bickering
factions, split between three parties.
So does Mr Karayalcin plan to go into national politics? Asked directly
about his intentions, he replies cautiously: 'A politician always has to be
ready to take on any position and rise in his own party as high as he
possibly can.'
If he ever does go into parliament, he may eventually emerge as a consensus
candidate for the eventual succession to Mr Inonu. But that is unlikely to
be in the lifetime of the present parliament. In the meantime, Mr Karayalcin
will have his work cut out making Ankara into the fairest capital city of
the Mediterranean.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6909</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBACZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (8): Banks start to catch up - The growth
potential of the market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'WE ARE the 73rd bank in the country,' explains Mr Ibrahim Betil, chairman
and chief executive of Bank Ekspres, a new Turkish bank which has just
opened its doors in Istanbul's business district.
Until last year, Mr Betil was general manager of Garanti Bankasi, one of
Turkey's larger private sector banks.
Then he decided to strike out on his own, raising Dollars 16m in capital
from a group of like-minded private investors, a move which is something of
a novelty in Turkey where private sector banks tend to be offshoots of an
industrial empire owned by a single individual or family.
Over the next five years his game plan is to target medium-sized corporate
customers and the retail banking market and build up a branch network of
between 40 and 50 branches, thereby establishing Bank Ekspres as one of the
main players in the Turkish market.
It is an extremely ambitious goal even for a banker who is already
well-known in his own market. Mr Betil, however, is not alone in believing
in the growth potential of the Turkish market where each year sees a few
more hopefuls, usually one-branch trade finance boutiques, being granted
banking licences.
Why is there so much interest in a banking sector whose operating
conditions, judged by the standards of the rest of the world, look extremely
daunting?
Because of Turkey's runaway inflation, interest levels are almost
stratospheric. The inter-bank overnight interest rate at the end of April
was 66.7 per cent. One-year retail deposits can earn up to 81 per cent from
some banks and US dollar deposits 11 per cent. Corporate borrowers pay
between 100 and 120 per cent. Borrowing rates have actually fallen in the
last year because customers are hard to find.
The margin may look still wide but it isn't. According to Mr Erol Sabanci,
vice-chairman of Akbank, Turkey's most profitable bank, required reserves,
taxes and staff costs eat up nine-tenths of every hundred lira held by a
Turkish bank. 'Deposit costs are just not under control,' Mr Sabanci says.
Banks make money not by lending but by holding treasury bonds or other
operations of which trade finance is the most lucrative. There is,
nevertheless, frantic competition for deposits, especially from the smaller
banks.
Deposit rate competition was introduced in Turkey in the late 1980s. Though
the large banks currently pay between 71 and 73 per cent on one-year
deposits (and between 55 and 60 per cent even on one-month money), the
smaller banks can beat this by as much as six percentage points.
Not surprisingly, once in a while savers get nervous in this market. In
early January, savers lined up outside branches of one of the smaller
Istanbul banks. The scare proved groundless and short-lived, but quite a few
savers seem to have been willing to forgo a year's interest just to get
their money back.
There have been no actual bank failures since the first half of the 1980s,
though the treasury monitors each bank's balance sheet and from time to time
stages discreet operations to help banks out of trouble.
There can also be other surprises. In mid-April, Ziraat, the state-owned
agriculture bank which is Turkey's largest, abruptly moved its rates to
depositors up by two percentage points, to the dismay of its main
competitors, Akbank and Turkiye Is Bankasi. Just why Ziraat selected this
moment to move seems to be something of a puzzle.
Mr Sabanci identifies high operational costs and low working capital as
chronic problems of the banking sector. In theory, all Turkish banks are now
moving gradually towards the international standards set by the BIS for
capital adequacy.
In practice, the strengths of the banks are rather more difficult to assess.
Ziraat this year has moved, for example, from being audited by the Turkish
offshoot of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, to a small local accountancy house.
Mr Sabanci points out that the capital bases of many of Turkey's larger
banks look distinctly less impressive when real estate and equity holdings
are deducted, though this is not a requirement under the BIS rules.
The fact that the Turkish banking sector can be measured against
international standards is, nevertheless, a sign of how far it has come in
the last decade - and its success not just in piloting its way through a
hyperinflationary environment, but also in coping with high levels of
non-performing corporate debt throughout the 1980s.
Though most banks are still owned by industrial groups, there are some
changes in attitudes towards non-banking subsidiaries. Turkiye Is Bankasi,
for example, has sold off stakes in three subsidiaries in the past two
years, including most recently its stake in Unilever's Turkish offshoot,
which went to the international parent company for an undisclosed price.
Most of the infrastructure of a modern banking sector has been set in place,
though foreign bankers identify some continuing weaknesses.
'Taxes on inter-bank transactions are still holding back the inter-bank
market. With taxes on transactions and volumes, not on revenues, you do not
get a deep inter-bank market and without that bankers cannot develop
derivative products and sophisticated financial instruments to eliminate
costs,' says one American bank in Istanbul.
However, some parts of the banking sector are becoming much more like large
banks in a modern country. Akbank, set up after World War II, has already
overtaken the other large private sector and the public sector banks in
profitability and will probably pass in them in asset size in a few more
years.
It has a notably less bureaucratic atmosphere than that which still prevails
among some of its rivals. At one of Turkey's largest banks last month, the
deputy chief executive folded his arms and confessed nervously to the
Financial Times: 'I am just an appointed clerk. You can't expect me to be
able to comment on anything.'
But at the retail end of the market, changes are under way, driven by the
emergence of a consumer middle class and expectations of higher standards of
service than in the past.
The dozen or so largest banks are developing modern cheque clearing and
money transmission houses. An automated clearing house is being set up with
a pilot stage in Istanbul which will offer clearing one day in Istanbul and
three days across the entire country.
A new inter-bank electronic funds transfer scheme began operating on April 1
for corporate and retail customers, and BKM, an inter-bank ATM network
service, has also been launched.
Turkey has virtually nothing in the way of credit reference services. So a
limited debit card service which is being set up operates with all
transactions being authorised by computer at the point of sale.
Nevertheless, the plastic card market is growing rapidly. BKM expects that
there will be around 10m cards, the vast majority of them cashcards for use
in automatic teller machines, in circulation by the end of this year.
That sort of rapid expansion, originally led by the Yapi ve Kredi bank, is
proving to be more profitable than the other large banks expected.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6910</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBACYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (9): Where cost control counts - Profile,
Akbank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BE THEY large or small, most Turkish banks operate from glitzy modern
headquarters designed to suggest vast opulence. Not so Akbank. Its
headquarters are a distinctly unpretentious 1950s building on a busy street
in Istanbul's Findikli district.
'The moment you set foot in that building you know you are in an environment
where cost control counts,' says one foreign banker in the city.
Eschewing the glitter, Ak, set up in 1948 and owned by the Sabanci Group,
one of Turkey's two main conglomerates, has set its sights over the past two
decades firmly on containing its costs and raising its profits. In doing so,
it has risen from the ranks of the smaller and medium-sized banks with 30
branches to become of the dominant players in the country's financial system
with 599 branches.
Still smaller by asset size than its main competitors, Turkey Bankas and
Yapi ve Kredi, Akbank was still far ahead of both last year with TL1,342bn
(Dollars 265m) in post-tax profits, up from TL733bn in 1991. Assets at the
end of 1991 were Dollars 3.65bn.
For the past seven years, Akbank has come out ahead of the rest of the
banking market in terms of net profit. Return on average assets was 9.17 per
cent last year and return on equity 57.7 per cent, figures which places
Akbank well ahead of many other European banks and not just its Turkish
competitors.
'It is fairly clear now that Akbank is on the way to becoming dominant in
the Turkish financial services sector,' says the general manager of another
Istanbul bank.
The results are achieved by fairly old-fashioned banking methods, combined
with a determination to see the bank and its profits grow. 'Other banks tend
to be satisfied with their results. We are not content,' says Mr Erol
Sabanci, the bank's vice-chairman and dominant figure.
During the mid-1980s, when most Turkish banks ran into trouble by lending to
companies which could not pay them back, Akbank managed to keep its
non-performing loans below 1 per cent of its loan book or less: no mean
achievement for a bank which is owned by and closely associated with a large
industrial group.
'We have known most of our customers for 20 or 25 years. We tend to be
cautious about lending to new businesses unless we are very sure about what
sort of management they have behind them,' says Mr Sabanci.
The same caution applies to new types of banking business into which Akbank
has moved in the past decade. It entered the field of trade finance and
merchant banking for example, by setting up a joint venture with Banque
Nationale de Paris and Dresdner Bank. In the UK it has a subsidiary, the
first Turkish bank in London, Ak International, with paid up capital of 65m.
When it became clear at the end of the 1980s that large Turkish banks would
have to invest heavily in money transmission and information technology in
order to tap the potential of an emerging domestic retail banking market, Ak
watched and waited to see how the experiments of its rivals would fare.
'There are advantages in going second or third into a new market,' says Mr
Akin Kozanoglu, the bank's head of retail operations and information
technology. 'We were doubtful whether or not automated teller machines would
be appropriate in Turkey for example,"
Once convinced that there were indeed profits to be made in retail banking,
Ak pushed ahead, setting up a network of 300 ATMS and spending up to Dollars
100m a year on software development, through its own software house, Aknet,
and developing on-line real time computerised links with all its branches.
As a result Akbank customers now enjoy some facilities not generally
available to European consumers: for example, they can dial a debit card
number and learn the balance of their account over the telephone.
The move into modern retail banking has brought other changes, especially in
the bank's management structure.
'Akbank used frankly to be a one-man show, with most of its top managers
relatively insignificant figures compared to Erol Sabanci,' says another
banker. 'You can see that he is now consciously trying to replace the
one-man show with young executives who are intended to be the backbone of a
new management team for the future.'
It may sound like a potentially difficult transition for a bank which was
only a small family business little more than a generation ago. But other
bankers point to the strong corporate culture which Mr Sabanci has developed
at Akbank.
'Akbank executives rarely move to other banks, and they tend to understand
what is expected of them much better than bankers in the other large banks.
It is an old-fashioned outlook, but also a very tightly focused one. If you
want to explain why Ak is probably going to go on outperforming the
competition, I think that tight focus is the main reason,' says one banker.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
