<DOCNO>FT922-6913</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBACVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (5): Slow moves on asset sales - The public
deficit is spiralling, but privatisation is being held up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TURKISH POLITICIANS rarely discuss the issue with the zeal you find in
eastern Europe, or in Argentina where reformed Peronists are now rolling
back the frontiers of the state.
Today in Ankara, with a coalition government at the helm, the debate about
privatisation has been hijacked by bureaucratic infighting, and the
opposition of vested business interests, concerned at the growing foreign
presence in the country's economy.
It has always been easier to make the economic case for the privatisation of
Turkey's state-run industries. The state's interests in 235 enterprises,
either as the majority shareholder, as an affiliate or a minority partner in
a privately-managed concern, are responsible for up to a third of the public
sector borrowing requirement, which in 1991 was running at around 12 per
cent of GNP. They account for almost half of all fixed investment in Turkey
and employ close to half a million people.
Mrs Tansu Ciller, the economics minister, has still to convince her cabinet
colleagues of the need for swift remedies if Turkey is to contain the
spiralling public deficit which is the main cause of the country's 70 per
cent rate of inflation.
The former Bosphorus University professor seems increasingly estranged from
the bureaucrats whose job it is to carry out her policy. The problems have
been exacerbated by her public differences with Mr Cavit Caglar, the state
minister who has repeatedly challenged her views on the economy.
In the eight months since the election, the government has yet to give a
clear signal on the issue.
The current privatisation programme is centred on the sale of the
government's minority stakes in a number of privately managed companies, the
details of which were already approved under the last government. While
moving ahead, it is little more than a revenue-raising exercise and does
nothing to transform the structure and ownership of Turkish industry.
Moreover, there are no plans regarding the main lossmakers - the railways,
the ports authority, Tek (the power utility), the grain board, the coal
corporation and the tobacco and alcohol monopoly.
A World Bank report called for a radical restructuring of the state sector.
Tusiad, the Turkish businessmen's association, also called for strong
action. The Bank suggested that many of the state companies would have to be
closed down. Others would be restructured, by selling their distribution and
marketing arms. All of the state enterprises needed to be brought under the
commercial code to instil the discipline of the market and allow the
managers to make decisions about price.
Two months ago, in a somewhat desperate gesture, Mrs Ciller asked Peugeot,
the French carmaker, to consider locating its new investment in the old
mining town of Zonguldak on Turkey's Black Sea coast. However, the French
company is expected to stick to its original plan to build the plant near
Izmir. The loss-making state-owned Zonguldak coal corporation, with its
payroll of close to 50,000 miners, is one of the principal drains on the
Turkish exchequer.
In April, after several months of exhaustive discussion, the Turkish cabinet
cleared the way for the creation of a new body to handle the disposal of
state assets. The idea was to put the state enterprises under the control of
an independent authority drawn from political but also academic, business
and labour circles. The plan was to restructure the companies in preparation
for a sale to the public. However, the powers of Toyok, as the agency is
known, have been severely curtailed. The council of ministers retains an
effective veto on key decisions, such as the closure of plant and staff
redundancies and lay-offs.
The privatisation programme was launched by the former Motherland party
government in 1986. The gains have been modest. Total revenue from the sale
of state assets either by public offering, by block share sales or
flotations on the Istanbul stock market, comes to less than USDollars 1bn.
Turkey's bid to revive the programme has now met with opposition from
businessmen, worried at foreign encroachment in a number of key industrial
sectors. The problem is in part a practical one. Turkey's infant stock
exchange will find it difficult to digest a large-scale flotation of
state-owned assets. On the other hand, few Turkish groups are in a position
to raise the sort of cash required to buy state shares in block, which is
currently the government's favoured method. In the short term, foreigners
may prove the only buyers ready to invest.
This year, the newly-created Public Participation High Council, the agency
entrusted with handling the sale of state assets to the public, expects to
raise Dollars 868m. Officials talk of selling off parts of PTT, the Turkish
telecommunications monopoly. The government says the company's cable, TV,
car telephone and computer networks are earmarked for disposal. Mr Yasar
Topcu, minister of transport, has all but ruled out the sale of Turk Hava
Yollari (THY). Any early moves to sell off Petrol Offisi, the state's petrol
products retailer, and Tupras, the state refineries corporation, have also
been put back.
Mr Ustun Sanver, head of the high council, says the government may sell some
Petrol Offisi gas station outlets. In the case of the refineries, the
government is more likely to look for a foreign investor to form a joint
venture with the existing plant.
In addition to the cement companies, Mr Sanver hopes to raise Dollars 25-27m
from the sale of block shares in Polinas Plastik, a packaging producer;
Seker Sigorta (insurance); Istanbul Demir Celik, a mining concern; Turk
Tractor, an agricultural machinery business; Trakmak, its marketing arm; and
Turk Otomotiv, the car parts manufacturer.
Several state companies are to be re-offered to the public, after the PPHC
rejected earlier bids. These include Ray insurance, Gima department store
and Meysu, a fruit juice and food producer. Mr Sanver expect these sales
will realise Dollars 28-34m.
There are plans for the public offering of the government's remaining 49 per
cent of Netas, which is part-owned by Northern Telecom of Canada. Mr Sanver
says preparations are under way for the sale of block shares in Teletas, the
telecommunications industry; AEG-ETI, the electric transformer maker;
Guneysu, the fruit juice producer; Tofas, the Fiat joint venture assembly
and its marketing arm; Aksaray Azmi, flour producer and Ankara, the flour
and bread producer.
In January, Citibank organised the sale of 51 per cent of Ipragaz for
Dollars 65m to the French company Primagaz. In March, Sabanci - Turkey's
largest industrial conglomerate - paid Dollars 22.5m for an 87 per cent
stake in Nigde Cimento, a local cement producer.
Cement has become the cause celebre with the French taking a commanding
position after the purchase by Societe Ciments Francais (SCF) of five
state-owned companies in 1989. Lafarge Coppee, the world's second largest
cement producer, and Societe Vicat have also entered the market.
It was Mr Suleyman Demirel, the prime minister, who opposed the sale to SCF,
arguing it contravened a 1987 law on privatisation as the shares had not
first been offered to domestic investors.
This month the role of foreign capital is again expected to come under
scrutiny when the PPHC offers block shares in a further 11 cement companies.
Mr Sanver says the cement sale is open to all investors, local and
international. Any hiccup at this stage could badly damage Turkey's
privatisation programme.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6914</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBACUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (4): Parliament comes back to life -
Politics / A change in mood
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YOU MIGHT think, looking at the political scene in Turkey, that nothing much
has really changed. The politicians have the same old faces. The issues are
little different from a decade ago. Even the excuses sound familiar.
But Turkey is experiencing an important change in mood. Amid signs of
increasing political violence, and a deteriorating economy, parliament - so
long ignored under the previous government - is enjoying a renewed lease of
life.
The 450-seat National Assembly is today the most eclectic gathering of
Turkish political opinion in the country's history. In all, there are six
parties representing every strand, from radicals of the Kurdish minority to
Islamic fundamentalists and extreme nationalists on both the right and left
wing.
In many countries, such a fiery political cocktail would be a recipe for
disaster. In Turkey a consensus has emerged, with a coalition government of
conservative and social democratic parties pushing ahead with what promises
to be the most thoroughgoing reform programme since Ataturk founded the
republic in the 1920s.
The man responsible is Mr Suleyman Demirel, the prime minister and leader of
the right-of-centre True Path party, DYP. He knows only too well the
vicissitudes of Turkish politics. Six times prime minister before, he was
twice ousted by the military, the last occasion being in 1980.
The prime minister's bid to restore the effectiveness of parliament is
something of a personal crusade. More practically, it allows him to ignore
the constant jibes of President Turgut Ozal who has repeatedly used his
office for partisan political purposes in a bid to undermine the growing
public support for his long-time rival.
This uneasy cohabitation with President Ozal casts a deep shadow over
Turkish politics. But Mr Demirel has provided the president with just enough
rope to hang himself, by dangling the threat of a series of corruption
files, where official impropriety is alleged.
The prime minister's tactics are in some ways merely reflect the situation
that he does not have a sufficient majority to unseat the president by
changing the constitution. But many colleagues believe this measured
approach to Turkey's problems underlines Mr Demirel's determination not to
rock the political boat.
At 68, Mr Demirel wants to lay to rest his turbulent reputation and secure
an honourable place in Turkey's history. The real question is whether he can
match his enthusiasm with the necessary urgency to push badly needed
legislation through the house.
The result of the election in October, while reconfirming the strength of
the conservative vote in Turkish politics, did not provide Mr Demirel with
the outright majority he wanted. True Path emerged as the country's largest
party, winning widespread support particularly in the small towns of the
Aegean and central Anatolia. But the outgoing Motherland party, ANAP, also
did better than expected, polling strongly in the big cities where it
successfully harnessed the votes of the business community with its image of
a modern western-oriented Turkey.
The election result also underlined the demise of the left in Turkey with
the Social Democratic Populists, the main left-of-centre party, only too
happy to accept Mr Demirel's offer to form a coalition. The party has still
not resolved its leadership crisis, with Mr Deniz Baykal making a series of
so far abortive bids to replace Mr Erdal Inonu, the SHP leader.
Local elections on June 7 in many parts of Turkey are expected to reinforce
these trends. A strong swing to the DYP might even persuade the prime
minister to go to the country in the autumn in search of a clear mandate.
It is too early to claim what is happening is the renaissance of Turkish
democracy, as the government suggests. But parliamentary sessions now
receive extensive television coverage. The deputies have probably never
worked so hard. Indeed, the legislative timetable is now so congested that
the speaker has had to shelve plans for an early recess. The politicians may
find themselves confined to smoky committee rooms well into the summer
months.
To visit one of the many state ministers who share offices in the old prime
ministry in Ankara's Kizilay district is to run the gauntlet of a throng of
farmers, relatives and free loaders, all waiting for jobs and other official
largesse.
Mr Demirel indulges the electorate with regular audiences in the prime
ministry where, if you can brave the military police on the door, any Turk
can make his point to the prime minister - a custom which seems to have more
in common with the consensus-building traditions of Arab politics.
Another feature of the new parliament is the return of a number of familiar
faces from Turkey's turbulent political past. Mr Bulent Ecevit, the former
socialist prime minister, regained his seat in the mining town of Zongludak.
Mr Alpaslan Turkes, leader of extreme right-wing Turkish Labour party is
also back. The happy triumvirate is made up by Mr Necmettin Erbakan, the
Islamic leader who espouses, among other things, an Islamic common market
and an Islamic Nato.
There are newer faces too, including the attractive radical Kurdish deputy,
Mrs Leyla Zana, who created such a stir when giving her oath of allegiance
at the opening of parliament wearing a headband in tricolour of the banned
Kurdish Workers Party, PKK, which is fighting an increasingly violent
separatist war in Turkey's south-east region. She was one of 22 radical
Kurdish deputies who stood on the Social Democratic ticket - 18 of whom have
now resigned.
In the shifting sands of Turkish party politics, some of the other recent
alliances are already coming unstuck. Mr Erbakan and Mr Turkes, bedfellows
during the election, have already gone their separate ways. The landscape
could soon be changed further if parliament approves a draft bill submitted
in April which would lift the restrictions on political parties banned
following the 1980 military coup. That would allow these political groups to
lay claim to extensive property impounded under the military order.
There is talk of reconstituting the centre-left Republican's People's Party,
founded by Ataturk. There has even been some debate about allowing a Kurdish
party - a suggestion first made by Mr Mesut Yilmaz, leader of ANAP.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6915</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBACTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (2): Market reserves its judgment - The
economy / There are still clouds on the horizon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LATE LAST year, when Mr Suleyman Demirel's coalition government took office,
many Turkish businessmen made little secret of their misgivings. For Mr
Demirel was last in power 12 years earlier, when inflation soared to
three-digit figures, Turkey suffered its worst-ever balance of payments
deficit and industry was paralysed.
Nearly six months on, the market is still reserving its judgment, but it is
clear that times have changed. The Suleyman Demirel of the 1990s believes in
privatisation, realistic exchange rates and - in theory at least - fiscal
reform. Turkey does not look as if it is about to be plunged into a fresh
economic crisis.
That said, there are still plenty of clouds on the horizon. Though Turkey is
managing to keep its external payments under control and last year ran a
surplus of Dollars 272m on its current account, the economy failed to shake
off a recession which began with the Gulf War.
Gross National Product grew by only 0.3 per cent in 1991 in an economy where
growth has averaged between 5 and 6 per cent a year over the past three
decades. Worse still, inflation went up to 71.1 per cent from 60.4 per cent
in 1990 and from the middle of the year, monetary disciplines were abandoned
as it became clear that there would be a general election.
Six months on, monetary self-restraint has not returned. Consumer prices
jumped by an alarming 9 per cent in January, by 5.4 per cent in February and
4.9 per cent in March, taking inflation to 78.7 per cent for the previous
12-month period.
Does this mean that Turkey is on the way to triple-digit inflation? Probably
not, says Mr Deniz Gokce, professor of economics at the Bosphorus University
in Istanbul. He predicts that inflation will slacken this year though
probably not as sharply as official forecasts, but that GNP growth will also
be relatively disappointing.
On the other hand, Turkey's balance of payments seems to be under control
despite a foreign debt burden of around Dollars 43bn.
Turkey's trade deficit fell by 20 per cent in 1991, largely because demand
for imports was very slack. Exports rose by 4.9 per cent to Dollars 13.6bn
(1990: Dollars 12.96bn) while imports dropped by 5.7 per cent from Dollars
22.3bn to Dollars 21.04bn.
As a result, the trade deficit was down from Dollars 9.3bn in 1990 to
Dollars 7.4bn.
Despite this improvement, foreign currency reserves held by the central bank
have slipped by about Dollars 1bn from Dollars 5.1bn at the start of the
year to Dollars 4.08bn, mainly because Turks are selling Turkish liras and
buying foreign currency as the local currency plummets ever further and
faster against the US dollar and the Deutschemark.
The main reason for the currency's ever-faster decline appears to be the
widening public sector deficit.
The 1992 budget has been set at TL208 trillion, and an unchanged TL32
trillion deficit is planned, a target which bankers drily describe as
'implausible' since it would mean a reduction of about a third in the
deficit in real terms at a time when government spending is shooting upwards
and public revenues are languishing.
Official projections are that tax revenues should be TL175.9bn, or about
four-fifths of total government revenues. Around TL3.5 trillion will be
raised from privatisations.
Whether things will work out quite like this is another matter. There are
few candidates for quick, profitable privatisations and the government does
not seem to have the stomach to introduce unpopular new taxes in what may,
after all, turn out to be another election year.
The government announced a new package of tax reforms and other economic
measures on January 17. The main feature appears to be a sharp increase in
indirect taxation. It has also launched a controversial tax amnesty,
intended to enable the Treasury to get at least part of the unpaid taxes it
is owed. Both sets of measures have yet to prove their effectiveness.
The government wants to press ahead with privatisation operations, but five
agencies will not be sold off: TMO (the state grain organisation); TEK (the
electricity authority); PTT; TCDD (state railways); and Tekel, the alcohol
and tobacco monopoly. The trouble is that this list includes the main
loss-makers.
If these cannot be privatised, perhaps some of them at least - for example,
the Zonguldak coal mines - could be shut down. That solution would please
international agencies such as the World Bank, but it is probably too
radical for Mr Demirel to contemplate.
The burden of public sector losses is a heavy one. Most of Turkey's larger
industrial enterprises were set up by the state between the 1930s and 1950s
and were never designed to run at a profit. More than TL11,997bn was lost by
18 state industries in 1991.
The top loss-makers were TEK (the electricity authority) which lost
TL4,326bn, TCDD (state railways) TL3,269bn; and the Turkish Coal board
(TL3,264bn) and the TD (iron and steel works which lost TL2,619bn). But not
all the public sector industries make a loss. Eight state industries made
money: Tekel, the state alcoholic beverages and tobacco monopoly made a
profit of TL1,378bn, while TPAO, the petroleum prospecting agency made
profits of TL1,289bn and the Post Office made TL1,229bn.
The complaint most generally heard is that Mr Demirel's economics team makes
grandiose promises but is short on a focused economy strategy. Mrs Tansu
Ciller, minister of state in charge of the economy, does not seem to have
the clout (or familiarity with the labyrinthine ways of the Turkish
bureaucracy) to match the men who dominated the Turkish economy in the Ozal
era.
Instead she seems to be losing ground to Mr Cavit Caglar, another minister
of state and president of the High Council on Credit and Mr Tevfik Altinok,
the undersecretary of the treasury and foreign trade, a veteran treasury
official who has spent most of the past decade working in Istanbul with Koc,
Turkey's largest industrial conglomerate.
Few of the new appointees have the international whizz-kid touch which
distinguished the top economic officials in the Ozal era and though statism
is out of fashion as an economic philosophy in Ankara, there also seems to
be little enthusiasm for exposing the economy to more competition,
particularly from the outside world, though on the foreign trade front,
Turkey is pledged to achieving a customs union with both the European
Community and Efta by 1996.
Only one of Mr Ozal's men, Mr Rusdu Saracaoglu, the 43-year old central bank
governor, has survived and his prospects look uncertain.
The hardest choices probably still lie ahead. If Mr Demirel truly wants to
stabilise the economy, he is going to have to turn a deaf ear to the pleas
of state employees and farmers for more pay. A fresh round of public sector
pay negotiations got under way this spring and the coalition government's
social democratic minister of labour is planning changes to the law which
would give unions much more power than they have enjoyed in the past.
Agricultural support prices may prove an even trickier issue. Mr Demirel's
main power base is the farming population of western Turkey. Once upon a
time, Turkish farmers could count on the government to hold agricultural
support prices high, allowing (untaxed) rural incomes to rise.
The military and Mr Ozal put a stop to that way of doing things after the
1980 coup. If Mr Demirel reverses that trend this summer to please the
farmers, Mr Altinok and the Treasury will face a gruelling time in 1993. But
there is no way that the main reforms of the 1980s can be reversed, even if
there is still plenty of scope for opening up the economy to genuine market
competition.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
