<DOCNO>FT922-6916</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBACSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Survey of Turkey (1): A worrying indecision - Though the
country has enhanced its reputation as a stable influence in a volatile
region, Mr Suleyman Demirel, the prime minister, faces growing pressure to
deliver on his electoral promise of political and social reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT MIGHT seem like a sentimental indulgence, but the Turks are greatly
flattered that their country, once dismissed as the sick man of Europe, is
now held up as a model by the newly-emerging states of central Asia.
Today the attentions of these distant cousins is welcome vindication of
Turkey's own moves to look west, a policy set in motion by Mustafa Kemal
Ataturk, which has taken on a new urgency in the last decade.
The recognition is particularly timely during a period of deepening troubles
at home, where indecision at the centre threatens to spoil Turkey's best
efforts at reform.
A resurgence of urban terror groups provides a chilling reminder of the
political instability which led to the military's intervention in 1980.
Inflation is running at more than 70 per cent, with the next wage round
looming. More worrying, for the first time, the Kurdish problem challenges
the very basis of this nation state carved from the ruins of Ottoman empire.
But Turks are great survivors and no politician better illustrates this than
Mr Suleyman Demirel, the veteran conservative who became prime minister for
the seventh time following the general election last October.
His return 12 years after he was ousted by the military - for the second
time - is seen as the best hope of restoring the country's fortunes. The
coalition government he leads is described by one western ambassador as 'the
most reform-minded, liberal and democratic in Turkey's history' - not such
an extravagant claim given Turkey's recent political turbulence.
Mr Demirel is best described a patronage politician, never more at home than
when manipulating the small business and farmer groups which control his DYP
party. Today he has also developed a strong instinct for the populist
gesture, epitomised by his election slogan to build the police stations out
of glass. It remains to be seen whether his fragile coalition has the
self-assurance to administer the radical reforms which Turkey so badly
needs.
The search for consensus between Mr Demirel's True Path party (DYP) and the
Social Democratic Populists (SHP) of Mr Erdal Inonu is already proving
painfully slow. Even when legislation makes it through cabinet, it is
destined for a rough ride in parliament where deputies are enjoying the
restoration of those traditional powers largely ignored by the former
government. However, with Turkey taking on the presidency of the Council of
Europe this month, the prime minister is pushing on a broad front of
political and legal reforms before the summer recess.
A draft bill on human rights has been submitted. Its main provisions aim to
combat the prevalence of police torture, which continues to be the single
greatest blight on Turkey's image abroad. Labour laws are being tailored to
bring the country in line with International Labour Organisation
conventions, while proposals for the country's Kurdish minority follow
Turkey's signature of the 1990 Paris Charter on human rights.
Mr Demirel faces a number of other challenges, domestic and foreign. On its
borders, Turkey confronts growing instability in the Caucasus, with
accompanying fears that it could be drawn into defending the rights of
Moslem against Armenian. In North Iraq, the evolution of some sort of
autonomy for the Kurds might encourage similar aspirations from Turkey's own
Kurdish minority.
In Europe, Turkey is anxious not to be isolated by the process of economic
and political union. The Turks have been associate members of the European
Community since 1963, but the current government increasingly accepts that
chances of full EC membership in the foreseeable future are slim. At
Maastricht, Turkey was offered associate membership of the nine-nation
Western European Union defence association, while the Greeks were invited to
become full WEU members. Given Turkey's long-standing disputes with Greece,
the legacy of more than 600 years of shared history, the government will
have a hard task recommending the EC's offer to parliament.
There are problems, too, on the EC trade and investment front. More than
half Turkey's trade is with the Community and Turkey is still broadly on
target for customs union with Brussels in 1996. But there are renewed calls
for protectionism from Turkish business groups concerned at the growth in
foreign competition which has resulted from liberalisation. There are even
those who question whether Turkey will ever implement all the tariff cuts
necessary for customs union, particularly given its needs on the revenue
side.
Turkey alone cannot resolve these issues, and Mr Demirel acknowledges that,
to receive a better hearing, Turkey must first tackle a series of domestic
problems that increasingly impinges on relations with the world at large.
This has been dramatically shown by the Kurdish issue which has taken on an
international dimension since allied intervention to help the Iraqi Kurds.
Recognising this, the government has embarked on a new policy initiative. A
package of economic measures is being introduced to tackle the south-eastern
region's high unemployment, while a Kurdish institute and two Kurdish
newspapers have been established. The government's junior coalition
partners, the SHP, are now openly debating the broader constitutional
question of devolved powers as a means to win back moderate Kurdish opinion
and undercut support for the rebel Kurdish Workers Party (PKK).
The authorities are steering a narrow course, offering liberal reform, yet
giving the military an apparent carte blanche to combat the separatists.
This could prove a difficult line to maintain as the PKK intensifies its
campaign to force further reprisals from the security forces.
Mr Demirel has the added disadvantage of a simmering feud with Mr Turgut
Ozal, who became president in 1989 after dominating Turkish political life
for most of the 1980s. It is on the Kurdish issue that the president has
been most vocal, urging Mr Demirel to introduce Kurdish television for the
south-east where the majority of Turkey's 10m Kurds live.
The president has also used his veto to block key appointments and openly
voiced disagreement with the government on a number of issues, particularly
on the economy where he has accused the coalition of undoing the good work
of the past decade, when he was prime minister.
Turkey's economy is in recession. While the population increases by 2.2 per
cent every year, Turkey's gross national product grew in 1991 by 0.3 per
cent, the slowest rate in more than a decade. This year the picture will be
barely improved. While Turkey remains the least taxed of OECD economies, all
talk of tax reform flounders. Privatisation of the government's minority
shares in privately-run companies still leaves the giant utilities and the
other main loss-making enterprises burdening the exchequer.
On the key issue of wages, so instrumental in Turkey's export drive in the
1980s, the unions are using SHP support to win further concessions, which
economists fear could result in a loss of competitiveness for Turkish
industry.
The policy indecision is now filtering through to the money markets, where
confidence in the Turkish lira looks increasingly shaky. A major
intervention by the central bank in the first quarter of this year
under-lined the vulnerability of the Turkish lira. Stability will be
especially critical now that Turkey is going to the commercial markets for
more than USDollars 1bn and floating bonds for the first time since 1990.
Meanwhile, Mrs Tansu Ciller has progressively lost her authority as chief
economics minister. Her inexperience in dealing with the bureaucracy has
surfaced in a series of embarrassing public disagreements with Mr Rusdu
Saracaoglu, the central bank governor and one of the few top civil servants
to have survived the change of government.
Turkey's promised land is some way off. For many of the country's 58m
inhabitants, a 10-year diet of economic deregulation has been hard to
digest. High inflation is eroding the standard of living of those on fixed
incomes. Investment has dropped while foreign and domestic business waits to
see whether Mr Demirel has the necessary courage to deal with Turkey's
fundamental problems, and allow it to regain its natural position as leader
in the region.
Unless the government can tackle the question of the economy, all Turkey's
problems will get worse. If it fails to do so, even the Central Asian
republics could look elsewhere for their model - a prospect that neither the
west nor Turkey relishes.
</TEXT>
