<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / London Stock Exchange: Hanson rumour lifts BP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MARKET was set alight in early trading with rumours that Hanson had
moved to buy the Kuwait Investment Office's 9.8 per cent stake in British
Petroleum - provoking speculation that the conglomerate was setting its
sights on the troubled oil company.
No basis could be found for the story, although the repercussions acted on
both companies' shares all day, with BP up 10 at one stage before retreating
to close at 261p, a gain of 5 on the day. After an initial rise, Hanson
slipped back to close 3 off at 228 1/2 p. A bulky 22m shares were traded in
BP.
Most analysts were sceptical that Hanson would consider BP, either as an
investment or a bid, because of the illogical fit with its present strategy
and portfolio - although a trader said yesterday's story was the third in
recent weeks linking the two groups.
Argyll retreats
Food retailer Argyll Group was one of the worst performers among the FT-SE
100 constituents as its results failed to excite and a large line of stock
looking for a home held down the share price.
The full-year figures were within market expectations, but after last week's
sparkling results from rival J. Sainsbury, the lack of surprises yesterday
dulled the response. The stock was further undermined by a securities house
having some problems placing 3.5m Argyll shares. However, turnover of 10m
shares by the close, more than twice the usual volume in the stock,
suggested that the house was finally successful.
While the increased dividend helped sentiment, Argyll's current trading was
below some forecasts. One analyst also complained that the group
concentrated too much at its presentation on plans for the Lo-Cost
supermarket operations rather than on the upmarket Presto chain. The shares
declined 10 to 357p.
Composite insurer Commercial Union, which reported first-quarter results
yesterday, and launched a preference share issue, retreated 6 to 504p as
word went round the market that Sun Alliance was about to place its stake in
CU of around 14.5 per cent.
Among those to discount the talk was Mr Steven Bird, of Smith New Court, who
said the stake was 'unlikely to be placed at the moment'.
The market was, however, pleased by the trading performance at CU, which
revealed losses 20 per cent lower at Pounds 19.2m, and at the same time
launched a Pounds 100m preference share issue, to be placed through Hoare
Govett and Cazenove, to finance expansion.
BZW said it remains a seller of the shares 'because we believe they are
over-distributed on the dividend front and are trading above net asset
value'.
On the bull side, Smith said: 'The company has got a superior underwriting
record. Unlike others in the sector, it is looking to make substantial
profits in two years time.'
Profit-taking weakened Sun Alliance, which finished 3 lower at 321p in spite
of an upbeat annual meeting.
Well-received results from Land Securities lifted the stock and other
leading property shares, although there was little news to cheer those
looking for a revival in the sector.
Mr Graham Stanley at County NatWest said: 'There were glimmers of hope in
the retail market outside of the south-east, but these were cancelled out by
the depressing picture elsewhere, particularly in the central London office
market.'
He has reduced his profits forecast for next year to Pounds 233m from Pounds
239m, citing the cost of the group's move away from offices and more into
retail. The shares rose 9 to 440p.
Some investors looked to switch out of Land Securities, preferring instead
British Land, up 11 at 214p, MEPC, 9 ahead at 346p, and Slough Estates, also
9 to the good at 196p.
In spite of figures below expectations, Ranks Hovis McDougall moved ahead as
spurious bid talk was again heard. Analysts were particularly disturbed by
the downbeat theme adopted by the company on present trading conditions,
plus the 62 per cent fall in milling and breadmaking revenue.
Smith New Court pared its current year profits forecast by Pounds 7m to
Pounds 98m, while Nomura reduced its estimate by Pounds 12m to the same
amount. Next year, they forecast Pounds 105m and Pounds 109m respectively.
The shares put on 5 to 234p.
Brewer Bass turned in positive interim results, the shares advancing 11 to
631p. County NatWest is looking for Pounds 528m for the full year and Pounds
638m in 1993.
Talk of a price war in the food retail market led to weakness in the sector.
J. Sainsbury slipped 2 1/2 to 465p, Tesco 8 to 280p and Kwik Save 5 to 625p.
Asda, however, continued to benefit from bid talk, edging 1 1/2 higher to 33
1/4 p in volume of 28m.
The creeping pace of recovery in the hotel market was behind two forecast
downgrades in Forte, which dipped 4 to 245p. Kleinwort Benson cut its
current year estimate by Pounds 10m to Pounds 115m, while another house was
reported to have come down to Pounds 125m.
Turnover in Pilkington rose to 11m and the shares firmed 2 to 161p, after
two blocks of 7.7m and 2.7m respectively went through the market. The bulk
of the volume was said to have arisen from BZW selling the remainder of the
31m shares bought from BTR earlier this month.
The reiteration of a buy recommendation by Kleinwort Benson on Inchcape
boosted the stock, which climbed 12 to 513p on turnover of 1.8m.
Bowater rose 12 to 850p. The shares are favoured by BZW, which has issued a
weighty document on the stock that is due to land on investors' desks today.
The broker lifted its current year forecast by Pounds 3m to Pounds 155m and
the following year's by Pounds 12m to Pounds 188m.
Fears that bankers to Eurotunnel could withdraw funding unless the company
settles a dispute with the tunnel's contractor TML by August hurt the
shares, which shed 8 to 380p. British Airways continued to bask in the glow
of its spectacular results aired on Tuesday. The shares added 13 at 380p on
some 10m traded.
A badly handled order in NFC caused the shares to lose part of an earlier
gain. They ended 9 up at 282p.
