<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Daimler helps Frankfurt to
21-month high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
APART from some weakness in Scandinavia, continental bourses were mostly
firmer, writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT rose to a 21-month high as domestic and foreign investors
responded to this week's engineering and construction pay deals, and
positive comments from Daimler-Benz on Tuesday.
Volume rose to DM9.9bn from DM7.2bn. After a 6.84 rise to 717.40 for the FAZ
index at midsession, the DAX ended 24.24, or 1.4 per cent higher, at
1,787.50, its highest close since August 3, 1990. Some analysts expect it to
approach its all-time, March 1990 high of 1,976.43 within six months.
Optimism hinged largely on Daimler's expectation that 1992 results will be
above those of 1991. In a broadly based gain taking in carmakers and
chemicals, steels and some engineers, both Daimler and AEG were boosted by
the former's statement that it did not expect to book an AEG loss in 1992.
AEG rose DM6 to DM212 and its parent by DM16.50 to DM804.
Construction stocks liked the wage deal, and forecasts of further growth in
the sector. Bilfinger &amp; Berger led them up with a rise of DM24.80 to
DM1,060. Retailers were mixed: Karstadt put on DM24 or 3.8 per cent to
DM655; but Douglas closed DM26 lower at DM615 on a forecast of flat or lower
earnings this year, after an early rise of DM14 to DM655 on higher profits
for 1991.
PARIS inched higher after Tuesday's drop but dealers said investors were
getting cautious after the market's recent rally. The CAC-40 index ended up
7.71 at 2,030.84 in modest turnover of FFr2bn.
Alcatel Alsthom was one of the day's more prominent losers, as the stock
touched a low of FFr639 before closing FFr12 to FFr646 on news that it had
placed 10m American Depositary Shares in the US at Dollars 23 5/8 each,
which traders said was the equivalent to FFr635 in the French share price.
In the afternoon, it was reported that a block of 290,000 American
Depositary Rights in Elf Aquitaine were traded at Dollars 36 1/8 . In Paris,
the shares closed FFr5.20 higher at FFr387.10.
MILAN was enlivened by industrial stocks. The Comit index rose 2.21 to
475.01 in turnover estimated at L95bn after L76bn on Tuesday.
Olivetti added L112 or 3.7 per cent to close at a 1992 high of L3,144, while
Fiat broke through L5,000 on the kerb, having closed L19 higher at L4,960.
Montedison added L10 to L1,475.
The banking sector recovered as Banca Commerciale Italiana (BCI) rebounded
L49 to L2,967 after its 4 per cent plunge on Tuesday.
AMSTERDAM's CBS Tendency index rose 0.8 to 130.2 on foreign institutional
interest. There was active buying in Buehrmann-Tetterode on reports of a buy
recommendation from a UK brokers and it closed up Fl 1.70 or 3.5 per cent to
Fl 49.80.
KLM remained a favourite on renewed speculation that merger talks with BA
had been reopened. It gained 70 cents to Fl 40.10.
Polygram rose 70 cents to Fl 50.90 on news that it had formed a joint
venture with Universal Pictures for the distribution of films in the US,
while Heineken took comfort from the hot weather in Europe and was Fl 2
stronger at Fl 165.
ZURICH brokers said that continuing high Swiss interest rates were keeping
some investors away. The market gave up some earlier gains on a lack of
buying interest, as the SMI index of leading shares rose 5.4 to 1,933.4 in
quiet trading.
Winterthur bearers fell SFr20 to SFr3,350. After the close the insurer said
it would raise dividends after an 112 per cent increase in 1991 profits, and
that it was opening up its share register to foreigners.
STOCKHOLM was little changed as in Astra led most blue chips higher,
balancing declines in domestic stocks and Volvo, where the B free fell SKr8
to SKr423 after Tuesday's SKr248m first quarter loss. The Affarsvarlden
General Index rose 0.9 to 999.3 in heavy turnover of SKr900m.
Astra accounted for SKr360m of total turnover, as the B unrestricted shares
advanced SKr19 to SKr547 after Tuesday's favourable first quarter earnings
report. The company also raised its forecast for full year profit growth to
more than 25 per cent.
BRUSSELS was firmer as dealers squared positions on the last day of the
forward account. The Bel-20 index advanced 4.05 to 1,224.19.
Petrofina rose BFr75 to BFr11,400 ahead of today's dividend payment.
