<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Late fall in futures
causes Nikkei to change course
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LATE afternoon profit-taking and arbitrage-related selling erased initial
gains, and share prices lost ground in tandem with the futures market,
writes Emiko Terazono in Tokyo.
The Nikkei average was down 79.18 at 18,674.93 after a high of 18,927.64 in
the morning and a low of 18,635.89 in the afternoon.
Investors were encouraged at the start by the overnight high on Wall Street,
and sought issues with favourable earnings prospects. However, share prices
receded in the afternoon as a fall in the futures market prompted arbitrage
selling.
Volume declined to 300m shares from 340m. Rises retained a narrow lead over
falls by 497 to 488, with 155 issues unchanged. The Topix index of all first
section stocks shed 1.20 to 1,394.51, and in London the ISE/Nikkei 50 index
ended just 0.66 up at 1,107.10.
Traders said that, in the short term, the market looked vulnerable because
of the high margin activity recently, especially in speculative or 'theme'
stocks. In the longer term, however, fears of a loss of support at the
18,000 level seem to have subsided.
Corporate results have had a substantial effect on some stocks. Surprises on
the negative side stem from losses on securities investments and real estate
development.
Investors have been discouraged by losses at companies which had been known
for their profitable business operations. Shares in Sekisui Chemical, which
reported a 17 per cent fall in pre-tax profits due to losses at its
financing affiliate, have dropped 21 per cent since the results were
announced two weeks ago. It closed Y29 down at Y871 yesterday.
Sato Kogyo, the civil engineering group, slipped Y70 to Y1,080. The company
suffered an extraordinary loss of Y2.3bn in its last fiscal year due to loan
guarantee payments to a resort construction affiliate.
On the other hand, better than expected earnings announcements were
appreciated. Nippon Meat Packers, which saw a 4 per cent rise in pre-tax
profits to Y28.5bn on a 7 per cent increase in sales to Y585bn, responded
with a gain of Y30 to Y1,770.
Short-term trading in theme stocks led activity. The most active issue of
the day was Mitsubishi Kakoki, an industrial waste water treatment equipment
maker, which rose Y90 to Y1,190 on the environmental theme. Traders are also
promoting the stock as an Aids-related issue, due to increasing sales of its
condom production facilities.
In Osaka, the OSE average gained a slight 0.73 at 21,348.15 in volume of
20.5m shares.
Roundup
THE Pacific Rim was generally firmer as international funds were switched
out of Thailand into neighbouring markets.
HONG KONG rose sharply on speculation that interest rates would be cut by
the weekend. The Hang Seng index advanced 111.52 to 5,753.76 in turnover of
HKDollars 3.91bn.
HSBC Holdings led the rally, rising 75 cents to HKDollars 44 on news that
the Bank of England would not object to the group's proposed bid for Midland
Bank.
BANGKOK rallied on bargain hunting following Tuesday's 8.9 per cent drop.
The SET index gained 9.53 to 677.37.
SEOUL lost ground, with sentiment depressed by rumours that the tax affairs
of some individual investors were to be investigated. The composite index
fell 8.06 to 579.91 in turnover of Won400bn.
MANILA was stronger on selective buying of commercial and industrial stocks.
The composite index appreciated 19.25 to 1,358.20 in turnover of 182m pesos.
Philippine Long Distance Telephone gained 25 pesos to 1,090 pesos.
TAIWAN extended Tuesday's advance and the weighted index put on 59.18 to
4,560.00 in turnover of TDollars 30bn.
KUALA LUMPUR's composite index climbed 3.18 to 594.09 in turnover of
MDollars 138m. Telekom moved ahead 20 cents to MDollars 12.70, with some
549,000 shares traded.
AUSTRALIA advanced in strong trade. The All Ordinaries index gained 15.7 to
1,682.0 in turnover of ADollars 205m.
Westpac shed 5 cents to ADollars 3.89 before reporting a loss of ADollars
1.67bn for its fiscal first half. The bank also announced an ADollars 1.2bn
rights issue.
Elsewhere, BHP moved forward 14 cents to ADollars 14.28 and News Corp put on
48 cents to ADollars 22.10.
SINGAPORE's Straits Times Industrial index rose 3.07 to 1,472.87 in dull
trade, with most institutional interest focused on Hong Kong.
NEW ZEALAND declined as investors took profits. The NZSE-40 index retreated
5.26 to 1,547.43 in NZDollars 19.4m turnover.
