FT  21 MAY 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALUMINIUM closed ahead on the LME after three-month metal hit stiff
resistance around Dollars 1,360 a tonne. The overall steadier trend was
prompted by a constructive close on Tuesday and by speculative interest. TIN
came under profit-taking and technical selling in the afternoon, prompted by
the failure of three-month metal to test Dollars 6,300 a tonne after hitting
a new 18-month high of Dollars 6,290 in the morning. But the selling was
well absorbed, with underlying interest evident below Dollars 6,250.
PLATINUM held at Dollars 361 an ounce on the London bullion market after
earlier falling on reported Middle East sales and a technical correction to
Tuesday's rally. Analysts said the market had been overbought on its rise to
Dollars 364, but sentiment was bullish on Nymex, where platinum futures were
higher at midday, again outperforming Comex gold and silver. Optimism that
economies worldwide are recovering sparked buying. Analysts also cited
continued concerns over the availability of supply in the physical markets.
Comex GOLD futures were weaker at midday on selling by players disappointed
at the failure to surmount resistance levels on Tuesday.
Compiled from Reuters
