<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Newmont's gesture fails to
convince gold market - Why the producer's symbolic purchase has so far not
succeeded in lifting prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS meant to be a big, symbolic gesture by Newmont Mining, North
America's biggest gold producer. Newmont wanted to send, with a flourish and
fanfare, a clear message to the market and other producers that it was sure
the gold price was at or very near its lowest point.
Newmont bought 375,000 troy ounces (or 11.7 tonnes) of gold at a cost of
nearly Dollars 126m on April 29 - the day the gold price was fixed in London
at its lowest point for six years. But the impact of the news was dampened
because it became fouled up by US stock market disclosure regulations. These
forced the group to include details of the gold deal in its report on
financial results for the first quarter.
The gold deal was completed on the day those results were due to be revealed
and Newmont was obliged to tell its shareholders immediately. After all, it
was locking in a net profit of more than Dollars 40m.
However, even allowing for the lack of razzmatazz accompanying Newmont's
announcement, some gold bulls have been disappointed by the market's
reaction. Newmont bought its gold at Dollars 335.95 a troy ounce, and two
weeks later the gold price still languishes at Dollars 337.30, near its
lowest for 16 years in real terms, when inflation is taken into account.
Some bullion dealers were also perturbed by the comparative lack of impact
Newmont's buying spree had on the market at the time. Sellers, particularly
from Europe, swamped Newmont's attempt to give the gold price a push in an
upward direction. However, as the price had drifted to a low of Dollars 333
an ounce on April 29, Newmont managed to lift it by a dollar or two.
Some observers contrast this with the market's reaction in February 1988
when Newmont announced it had completed the biggest gold loan ever  - of 1m
ounces or 31 tonnes. Perhaps unfairly, this move was blamed for starting the
steady fall in the gold price which continued through the following four
years.
In a gold loan operation a mining company borrows metal from a commercial
bank or syndicate which has, in turn, borrowed some from a central bank. The
mining company then effectively sells the gold in the market for cash which
is then used for a designated purpose. In the opinion of some analysts,
Newmont signalled in the most dramatic way in 1988 that the gold price had
reached its peak and, once the news was out, the price took a tumble.
Mining companies pay back gold loans, both principal and interest, usually
in gold but occasionally in cash.
Gold loans are mainly used to finance new gold mining projects, but
Newmont's was arranged to take advantage of the low interest rates offered,
roughly 3 per cent at that time, compared with the money markets. The group
was under tremendous pressure to reduce the burden of its Dollars 1.6bn
debt, most of it taken on to ward off the unwelcome overtures of marauders
led by Mr T. Boone Pickens, the well-known corporate raider.
Newmont bought gold at Dollars 449 an ounce for its five-year loan and was
repaying at the rate of 62,500 ounces a quarter. By the end of last year
about half the loan had been repaid.
Mr Jim Hill, Newmont's vice president, corporate relations, says the company
'is neither disappointed nor surprised' by the reaction so far to its
announcement about the early repayment of the rest of its gold loan. 'Gold
analysts reacted very positively,' he says.
'We felt that, whereas the gold price might go down a few more dollars, the
trend from now on would be up. So we decided to pay off our gold loan and
lock in a net profit of about Dollars 100 an ounce.'
Newmont is not the only producer to repay a gold loan before the due date.
And an analysis by Ms Jessica Jacks, analyst with the RTZ Corporation, the
world's biggest mining company, shows that at the end of 1991 total gold
loans outstanding involved 330 tonnes compared with 391 tonnes in December
the previous year. Therefore a net 60 tonnes of gold (1.9m ounces) was
repaid last year.
Yet a large number of professionals operating in the gold market seem to
believe that the price has not yet touched bottom. Most of the commodity
funds, for example, are selling the metal short - they have contracted to
sell gold they do not yet own in the expectation that they will be able to
buy it at a lower price when they need it.
Sceptics also point out Newmont's move seems to bear the mark of Sir James
Goldsmith, the Anglo-French financier, who is one of the greatest bulls of
gold. Much of his fortune is wrapped up in Newmont. His General Oriental
Investments, where he has a two-thirds stake, owns 42 per cent of Newmont.
Sir James is also chairman of the group's new strategy committee.
Yet it is clear Newmont did not just play a hunch. Mr Paul Maroni, Newmont's
chief financial officer, lists some of the factors pointing to a gold price
rise soon: production is tailing off; new gold is expensive to find and to
produce; demand from the jewellery industry (which has been buying more gold
than is newly-mined each year) remains buoyant.
Mr Maroni suggests those producers who continue to sell when the price rises
 -and effectively 'cap' any substantial increase - are mainly high-cost
producers who could not survive without this form of insurance. The time
will come when their ability to survive will be called into question, he
suggests.
Also, the extraordinarily high level of gold sales from the former Soviet
Union which helped to drive down the price in the past two years cannot
continue because its stocks have almost run out and production is now
relatively modest.
Mr Maroni says there is also a potential 'wild card' which might benefit
gold - a 'meltdown' of the world's financial system. Sir James has recently
forecast such an event, which he suggests will see investors returning to
the security offered by gold. Mr Maroni echoes this view: 'We don't think
the world financial system is in very good shape.'
Leaving that 'wild card' aside, many analysts agree with Mr Maroni's
analysis. Ms Rhona O'Connell, analyst at Williams de Broe, part of the
Banque Bruxelles Lambert group, says: 'We agree with the view that this is
the bottom of the gold market.' But she warns: 'Recovery will be a slow and
painful process.'
Mr Andy Smith, analyst at Union Bank of Switzerland, also says the gold
price is likely to be higher at the end of the year than it is today -
perhaps by Dollars 30 or Dollars 40 an ounce. 'But it won't move for a month
or so and it might not stay there when it gets there.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 38
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6926</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBACIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Basis of a deal on radical CAP
reform in sight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE fifth attempt this year to synthesize the vested interests of the EC
farm sector around a genuinely radical reform of the creaking Common
Agricultural Policy was finalised early yesterday morning, giving the basis
for a deal.
Although it festoons most member states with sweeteners to help them digest
severe cuts in subsidised prices, the structure of the European Commission's
bold attempt to overhaul the CAP is still intact.
Mr Ray MacSharry, the EC agriculture commissioner who has cajoled,
bludgeoned, and horse-traded with the 12 farm ministers for 18 months to
bring them this far, said yesterday: 'What we're involved in here is a
totally different philosophy to what has existed for 30 years.'
Agreement is now in view - and as ministers settled into their second
consecutive night of negotiations, there was hope for a deal either today or
tomorrow.
Yet despite general conviction that the fifth compromise paper presented by
the Portuguese presidency constituted the basis for settlement, a major
North-South row over plans to concede more milk quotas to Spain, Italy and
Greece gathered pace through the day and could delay the denouement.
The central element in the overnight compromise was the cereals price. Mr
MacSharry persuaded the Portuguese presidency to retrace its steps and
deepen the planned cut in subsidised grain prices to 29 per cent.
The Commission had wanted to drop the cereals price by 35 per cent, from
Ecu155 per tonne now to Ecu100, though it drew its public line at Ecu105,
with the tacit understanding that Ecu108 a tonne was its limit. Mr Arlindo
Cunha, the Portuguese farm minister, had tried to break the logjam by moving
towards Germany, which insisted on settling as near as possible to the 20
per cent cut in domestic subsidies demanded by the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) to conclude the stalled Uruguay Round.
Mr Cunha last month proposed Ecu112 per tonne, and received an unprecedented
and public rebuff from Mr MacSharry. On Tuesday they split the difference
and settled at Ecu110 - a 29 per cent cut close to the 30 per cent the
Commission had always set out to achieve, with a 1 per cent psychological
sweetener to enable Germany to feel it was in the '20s'.
The compromise on cereals looked set to harden into a deal acceptable to the
Twelve last night, opening the way to agreement on the rest of the reform
structure for which it is the foundation.
It will enable a market with a production overhang of around 20m tonnes (as
well as similar amounts in intervention stockpiles) to come back into
balance. It will make EC grains competitive, without the need to dump
abroad, and should all but eliminate cereal export subsidies - the real rock
on which the Uruguay Round is foundering.
Within the CAP reform structure itself, it will enable significant price
cuts in the livestock and dairy sectors, which will be part compensated by
lower cereal feedstock prices.
The Commission also won back its own compromise position on how the scheme
is to operate.
In essence, the reform moves away from price support towards direct payments
to farmers. All farmers will get a full refund of the price cuts paid
directly to them, contingent for all but small farmers to their taking 15
per cent of their land out of production. All farmers will also get
compensation for this 'set-aside', whereas the Commission had wanted to bite
further into overproduction by excluding the biggest farms.
Ministers had also rejected the Commission's plan to monitor set-aside by
individual farms, which Mr MacSharry and his colleagues insist is the only
way of making farmers take responsibility for their production. The
presidency opted instead for county-size regional units  - but on Tuesday
the Commission got the individual farm unit reinstated. Senior officials say
farmers will eventually bridle if they are penalised as a region because
some farmers within it flout the land in production limits. These officials
believe they have established a transitional regime to the effective
controls they were seeking.
Against this, scattered over the compromise are concessions for dried fodder
and cereals grown for silage; for France's maize growers and the South's
hard wheat growers; for tobacco producers and hill sheep farmers.
Germany, which is likely to be allowed to pay a one-off national subsidy to
its farmers this year, has also been granted special treatment for the
eastern Laender. Some formula of future yield will be the yardstick for
compensation for price cuts there, against fixed, past production reference
periods for the rest of the EC - another critical weapon in the fight
against oversupply.
Ireland has scored a signal victory with an easing of what was to have been
a very severe contraction of the intervention regime, which currently
absorbs about four fifths of its beef produce. The compromise recognises the
fact that Irish (and French) farmers slaughter their herds later in the
year, and ensures they do not lose out in case those who slaughter earlier
get into what will be finite stockpiles first.
The UK, which at times over the last 18 months has suggested MacSharry was
trying to refashion EC agriculture on a backward Irish model, was said by
Irish farm minister Joe Walsh to be seeking the same regime for Northern
Ireland.
A British special case - providing half-subsidy for sheep farmers in
disadvantaged areas over the 1,000 per flock limit - was also in the
compromise, although British ministers were fighting for more.
But the extra milk quota for Italy, Spain and Greece remained a big
stumbling block, opposed by the UK, Netherlands, Denmark, Belgium and
Luxembourg. This was enough to block the concession, but as the evening wore
on, it seemed likely that all but the three recipients would come out
against it.
'It's going to be very hard to get round that one,' predicted Mr David
Curry, the UK deputy agriculture minister.
The three countries have applied the milk quota regime only loosely, and are
looking for extra quotas to soak up some of their existing excess
production. The Commission reasons that this is a worthwhile price if these
countries are now obliged to implement and monitor quotas. There were few
signs last night that such reasoning was percolating through the rest of the
Council.
</TEXT>
