FT  21 MAY 92 / International Capital Markets: EBRD plans to set up finance
advisory brokerages in E Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) plans to set up
two corporate finance advisory boutiques in Eastern Europe which may
eventually be launched as financial institutions in the private sector.
Mr David Hexter, head of the EBRD's Financial Institutions Group, said the
bank is keen to establish the new corporate finance advisory brokerages, as
these would help to select and identify new projects in Eastern Europe for
the EBRD and others.
The two projects still need the EBRD board's approval. The projects would
require only a small amount of capital at first.
Once they were established as fully fledged financial institutions, however,
the EBRD said it would probably reduce its involvement by selling, or by
reducing its participation.
Mr Hexter said: 'In both cases we have identified locally committed people
who are prepared to run with the idea'. The EBRD plans to provide help such
as credit analysis, training, and computer systems. He added that ideally
the EBRD should play the role of a 'catalyst', encouraging foreign banks to
participate in banking joint ventures.
Mr Hexter, who previously helped to set up banking ventures in Poland,
Czechoslovakia and Hungary while he was working at Citibank, said that he
was impressed by the willingness of Eastern European bankers to learn and to
adapt to market conditions.
The EBRD is working to develop banking systems in many Eastern and Central
European economies. An estimated 90 to 95 per cent of the banks in the
region are state-owned. The EBRD wants to promote the development of private
sector banks.
