<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / International Company News: Yamaha blames sluggish demand
for 29% decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL WEINBERG
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
YAMAHA, the world's leading musical instrument maker, logged a 37.6 per cent
drop in non-consolidated pre-tax profits, to Y6.8bn (Dollars 52.6m). Net
profits fell 29.4 per cent to Y2.8bn in the year ended March. Both figures
were down for the second consecutive year.
The Shizuoka-based company blamed sluggish demand for pianos and other
musical instruments for the declines.
Overall, sales for the year edged up 0.1 per cent to Y383.7bn after a slight
decline the previous year.
Domestic sales, however, gained 1.3 per cent to Y272bn, despite weak demand
for synthesizers and other electrical instruments.
The negative effect of the yen's rise contributed to a 2.8 per cent drop in
exports, to Y111.5bn, despite the start of piano shipments to Steinway of
the US during the second half of the year.
Piano sales fell Y7.4bn to Y60bn, electronic instruments Y3.2bn to Y68bn and
audio equipment Y3bn to Y29bn. Sales of other instruments gained Y1.4bn to
Y50bn.
Yamaha's current assets slipped Y12.6bn to Y150.6bn, including a drop of
Y518m in its securities holdings, to Y890m.
For the year to next March, Yamaha expects sales and profits to decline
further, largely because of a planned shift of household equipment
operations to a subsidiary.
Pre-tax profits are expected to fall 48 per cent to Y3.5bn and net profits
47 per cent to Y1.5bn, on a sales drop of 10 per cent in sales to Y345bn.
</TEXT>
