<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / International Company News: Honda hit by fall in domestic
sales - Changes planned to give local management more autonomy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HONDA Motor, the Japanese car maker, yesterday reported a 1 per cent fall in
consolidated pre-tax profit to Y130.76bn (Dollars 1.01bn), and announced
changes to its management structure to give executives in the US and Europe
more autonomy.
In common with other Japanese car makers, Honda has suffered from the
downturn in the domestic market, where new registrations were 5.1 per cent
down January to April, compared with the same period last year. But the
company is still planning to expand its share of foreign markets.
It said net profit for the current year is likely to fall by about Y5bn from
last year's Y64.9bn, itself down 14.9 per cent, partly because of costs
related to the commencement of UK production, scheduled for this October.
A series of management promotions and title changes have created four clear
divisions of Honda's car business, covering Japan, the US, Europe and
'others,' with each of the regions apparently given more control over local
design, research and marketing.
'We felt that we had to make our management more flexible in these regions.
Basically, the international car market is very stable, with no area
promising rapid growth, and we have to adjust to this stable growth era,'
Honda said.
The company's consolidated sales rose 2.1 per cent to Y4,391bn, with a 3.9
per cent increase in car sales and a 2 per cent fall in revenue from
motorcycles, even though there was a 6.4 per cent increase in sales by
volume.
The company said motorcycle sales were helped by strong demand from other
Asian countries, although revenue was hurt by an appreciation of the yen.
Parent company pre-tax profits, more exposed to the weak domestic car
market, fell by 21.3 per cent to Y66.9bn on a 4 per cent increase in sales
to Y2,911bn. For the current year, the parent is expecting slight sales
growth at Y2,920bn and profits flat at Y67bn.
'We are not very optimistic in our estimations for the domestic market this
year. Total sales in the market will probably be at the same level as last
year's 7.43m units. Sales will be at that level or a little lower,' the
company said.
The company sold about 669,000 cars in Japan last year, unchanged from the
previous period, 953,000 in the US, up from 952,000, and 196,000 in Europe,
up from 173,000, while the 'others' accounted for 143,000, an increase of
22,000 units.
As with many leading Japanese companies, Honda is planning to reduce capital
spending, with the target this year Y200bn, down from Y237.8bn last year.
</TEXT>
