FT  21 MAY 92 / International Company News: Maple Leaf Foods advances 31%
despite weak markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MAPLE Leaf Foods, the Canadian food-processing subsidiary of the UK's
Hillsdown Holdings, has again overcome weak markets to post a 31 per cent
rise in first-quarter earnings.
Net earnings from continuing operations climbed to CDollars 12m (USDollars
10), or 15 cents a share, from CDollars 9.2m, or 14 cents a share, a year
earlier.
Sales dropped to CDollars 638m from CDollars 747m, due largely to the
surgery which has transformed Maple Leaf, formerly Canada Packers, over the
past 18 months into a more tightly focused and aggressive company.
Mr Charles Bowen, recently appointed chief executive, ascribed the improved
earnings to continued cost-cutting, lower interest expense and wider margins
as a result of a greater emphasis on value-added products.
The company earned net interest of CDollars 1.9m this year, compared with
debt-service charges of CDollars 3.7m in 1991.
Maple Leaf, which has virtually no long-term debt and net cash reserves of
over CDollars 200m, has recently switched its focus from reorganisation to
expansion.
It has signed a flour-milling joint venture with ConAgra, the big US
agri-business group. The company reported sharply higher first-quarter
earnings from its milling opera-tions.
Maple Leaf has also proposed buying out the minorities in Corporate Foods,
its baking subsidiary, as a first step towards North American expansion.
