</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SWISSAIR and Austrian Airlines are to operate jointly customer service
offices in their two home countries from November 1 as part of a programme
to intensify co-operation and reduce costs.
The remaining offices, including agencies of the two airlines in border
towns of neighbouring countries, will be operated by the home airline.
Passenger and cargo handling at Swiss and Austrian airports will pass to the
home carrier from September 1.
Austrian Airlines and Swissair, together with Scandinavian Airlines System
(SAS), formed the European Quality Alliance in 1989 to share facilities and
improve their competitiveness.
The three recently set up jointly operated stations in some eastern European
cities.
Further links among the three were possible, said Mr Otto Loepfe, chief
executive of Swissair, but he ruled out mergers.
'Generally we have said that, short of merger, all possibilities are open,'
he said at a Zurich press conference.
