FT  21 MAY 92 / International Company News: Polygram, Universal in film
venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POLYGRAM, the London- based music and entertainment company which is 80 per
cent owned by Philips of the Netherlands, has formed a joint venture with
Universal Pictures of the US for the distribution of films in North America.
The North American distribution venture marks a further step in the
company's efforts to increase its presence in the film industry.
The joint venture, to be called Gramercy Pictures, will be based in Los
Angeles.
It is aimed at marketing medium-budget films supplied by both Polygram and
Universal.
The company intends to handle the release of an initial eight films a year,
with more expected as the joint venture grows.
PolyGram and Universal, which is part of MCA, the US film subsidiary of
Matsushita of Japan, will continue to handle their own distribution in
markets outside North America.
The new company was formed because the partners believe the marketing of
medium-budget films requires a different approach than the saturation
advertising often available for big-budget, blockbuster films.
'Many good movies, with enormous box office potential, require a more
nurturing marketing and distribution process. This new company was
especially created to do just that,' said Mr Tom Pollock, chairman of the
MCA Motion Picture Group.
PolyGram said the joint venture was part of the company's Dollars 200m
programme of investment in the film business.
The investment programme was announced in September, when Polygram took
majority control of two film production companies, Propaganda Films and
Working Title.
At the time, Polygram said that its plans for distributing medium-budget
films in the US might involve setting up such a joint venture company.
</TEXT>
