<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Shares fall on Pounds 2.2m loss at Henry
Barrett
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Henry Barrett Group fell 6p to 26p yesterday, close to an all-time
low, after the the steel and industrial fasteners company announced an
interim loss and expressed caution about the immediate outlook.
Barrett, which has been forced to rein back after rapid expansion in the
1980s, reported a pre-tax loss of Pounds 2.19m in the six months to February
29, compared with a profit of Pounds 272,000.
Turnover fell to Pounds 49.4m, against Pounds 57.4m, which included Pounds
11m relating to discontinued activities or businesses for sale.
Mr James Barrett, group chief executive, said stockholding and industrial
fasteners were profitable. But the construction division, mainly involved in
structural steelwork, lost money because of pressure on margins.
'We're looking for margin not volume recovery,' he said.
Losses per share were 3.47p (earnings 0.37p) and no interim dividend is
being paid. However, the company said it would pay a nominal final dividend
because several shareholders are trusts which have to sell shares if no
dividend is paid.
Barrett has continued to sell loss-making businesses, leading to an
extraordinary charge of Pounds 2.7m. Last month Park Pallet, which is
involved in materials handling, was sold for Pounds 168,000.
Exceptional charges of Pounds 295,000 covered redundancies in ongoing
businesses. Once Barrett's disposals and cuts are complete, the workforce
will fall to 800, compared to 1,350 a year ago.
Net borrowings remained high at Pounds 19.9m at the end of the period,
equivalent to 87 per cent of shareholders funds (74 per cent). Mr Barrett
said gearing should fall towards 50 per cent by the year end as cash flow
was expected to turn mildly positive and some property sales were pending.
Interest costs were unchanged at Pounds 1.18m.
</TEXT>
