<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Currie has 65% of Pacific
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MARTIN Currie Pacific Trust said that it has received more than 65 per cent
acceptances for its offer for Pacific Horizon Investment Trust, which is
managed by Jupiter Tyndall.
Valid acceptances have been received for 65.79 per cent of the ordinary
shares and 44.55 per cent of the warrants.
A further 4.92 per cent of ordinary shareholders and 6.46 per cent of
warrant holders have sent in acceptances, which are in the process of being
validated. The offer has been extended until June 2.
Jupiter Tyndall has been battling to block the takeover and has assembled a
25.1 per cent stake in the trust's warrants. Last week, it voted down a
resolution which required a 75 per cent majority of warrant holders. As a
result, Martin Currie dropped an improved offer for the ordinary shares of
Pacific Horizon.
Jupiter has said that it will put forward its own propo-sals to enhance
shareholder value and enable share and warrant holders to receive cash for
all or part of their holdings.
Jupiter has a 15.4 per cent stake in the ordinary shares and has said that
it will not accept the offer, thus preventing Martin Currie from passing the
90 per cent mark at which it could compulsorily acquire the outstanding
shares.
In these circumstances Jupiter says that the rights of the warrant holders
will have to be substantially enhanced; Martin Currie Pacific says it has
received legal advice that this is not the case.
</TEXT>
