FT  21 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Miller hit by write-down of Pounds 6.5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pre-tax profits of Miller Group, one of the UK's biggest privately-owned
construction companies, tumbled from Pounds 10.75m to just Pounds 537,000 in
1991 as the recession continued to hit property values.
The figures were struck after an exceptional provision of Pounds 6.45m
arising from land and property write-downs and the closure of a specialist
subsidiary. This followed an exceptional provision of Pounds 3.5m in 1990.
The group has interests in civil engineering, general construction, mining
property development and housebuilding.
It recently appointed Mr David Cawthra as chief executive to assist with its
expansion plans. Mr Cawthra was previously chief executive of Balfour
Beatty, the construction arm of BICC the large engineering group.
Turnover of Miller last year was virtually static at Pounds 238.03m against
Pounds 235.38m. After tax of Pounds 210,000 (Pounds 4.16m) and dividends the
group suffered an overall loss of Pounds 314,000 (Pounds 5.91m profit).
Mr James Miller, chairman, stressed the strength of the company's balance
sheet.
