<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / UK Company News: A future based on a dual-track strategy for
growth - Vital changes that have transformed Courtaulds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN HIS new headquarters in London's west end Mr Sipko Huismans was in
ebullient mood as he announced an 8 per cent improvement in Courtaulds' full
year profits.
The move to the smart new offices symbolises the changes at Courtaulds since
it demerged its textiles operations two-years ago, according to Mr Huismans.
'We've moved the group from a tired, beaten up textile company in dingy
surroundings into a modern up-to-date entity which has taken a grip of its
destiny,' he says. 'We were described as a rat-bag of industries ripe only
for takeover. Now we have demonstrated we have critical mass.'
Courtaulds' ability to shrug off the recession has been dependent upon tight
financial controls and its ability to manage high-margin businesses, Mr
Huismans says.
The company has cut its workforce from 23,550 last year to 22,700 and
further cost savings are inevitable. Any company executive who reckons his
company is efficiently run is a fool, argues Mr Huismans. Courtaulds has
managers who cannot manage and there is lots more room for profits
improvements, he adds.
For the future, Mr Huismans has developed a dual-track strategy for growth
through the exploitation of a new material called Tencel and through the
replication of businesses on a global scale. Geographical expansion will
mainly be in the Far East.
He says he is not looking at diversification in any circumstances and that
any acquisitions would be add-ons. Mr Huismans says that during his tenure,
he would like to more than double turnover in the Far East. At present the
region generates about 6 per cent of sales and he would like it to reach 15
per cent.
Mr Huismans, who has been chief executive for nearly two years, reckons
managers can achieve about four or five things over about half a dozen years
before running out of steam.
Meanwhile, Tencel, a man-made fibre aimed at the high-quality cotton market,
remains one of Courtaulds' chief hopes. Its main advantage is that it does
not need dry cleaning, can be laundered like cotton, but unlike cotton it
can be produced when needed.
A first Tencel plant, costing about Dollars 85m, is on-stream and should
make every existing plant for cellulose fibres obsolete, according to Mr
Huismans. The process also has a minimal environmental impact, he adds. He
wants Courtaulds to reap the full benefits from Tencel, rather than
setting-up co-marketing agreements.
As for threats, the main one - according to analysts - is a Taiwanese
investment for additional viscose production in the US which threatens to
flood the market there, potentially undermining margins of between 20 and 25
per cent. But Mr Huismans reckons any investment would not come on stream
for five years and the permits for the necessary pulp plant have not even
been given yet.
'We've made mistakes,' admits Mr Huismans. 'I can name half a dozen without
even thinking.' When pressed for examples he says it would be invidious to
give details, but adds that all of them were because the group failed to
understand the market or underestimated the reaction of the competition. 'In
the end, you have to be an optimist, otherwise you end up as a gilts
investor,' he concludes.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
</PAGE>
