<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Sun Alliance in closer ties with top Swiss
insurer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUN ALLIANCE, the UK's largest insurance company, will today sign an
agreement with Helvetia, one of Switzerland's top five insurers, to jointly
develop international commercial lines business.
The deal, which the managing director designate of Sun Alliance
International, Mr Peter Foreman, expects to sign in St Gallen, Switzerland,
today, formalises a co-operation agreement which has been in existence for
ten years.
It should boost the profile of both companies in the highly competitive
market for providing multinational companies with worldwide insurance
programmes.
Increasingly companies with strong international networks - such as American
International Group, Zurich, Union des Assurances de Paris and Allianz -
have been able to dominate the market.
British companies, which lack comparable international networks and do not
have the available available to make acquisitions, have been increasingly
forced to join forces with international rivals.
Sun Alliance itself has forged links with Taisho of Japan and Lucky
Insurance Company of South Korea, while both Royal Insurance and Commercial
Union have also formed long-term links with Japanese companies.
Sun Alliance also has less formalised accords with Vesta Group in Norway and
Atlantica in Sweden. More recently Royal agreed to merge its European
operations outside the UK with Aachener and Munchener of Germany and
Fondiaria of Italy.
According to Mr Paul Cusition, manager international insurances at Sun
Alliance International, says that by acting more closely together the
companies have already been able to win the custom of one Swiss
multinational.
Mr Cusition says that the arrangement is seen as long-term and strategic.
Contracts signed by the two companies allow for a six month notice period if
either party opts to terminate the deal.
Mr Cusition says it will strengthen Sun Alliance's ability to service
multinational clients in both Switzerland and Germany, where the Swiss
company is well represented.
</TEXT>
