<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Resilient Argyll advances by 25%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE continued resilience of food retailers to recession was yesterday
underlined by Argyll Group, which runs the Safeway, Lo-Cost and Presto
chains, as it posted a 25 per cent gain in annual pre-tax profits to Pounds
364.5m.
These followed similar substantial profits increases in recent weeks from
two other big food retailers, Tesco and J. Sainsbury.
However, the market was worried that cost increases were currently
outstripping same-store sales gains and Argyll's shares fell 10p to 357p.
Sir Alistair Grant, chairman, said as a result of the low-inflation
environment in the 1990s, far more attention had to be paid to increasing
productivity. 'We will have to industrialise the way we run our stores,' he
said.
Efficiencies would come from better management of its supply chain. The
company is testing sales-based re-ordering systems. This year saw the
extension of sales scanning equipment to all Safeway stores.
In the year to March 28, Argyll's sales breached the Pounds 5bn mark for the
first time climbing 6 per cent to Pounds 5.04bn. Operating profits climbed
16 per cent to Pounds 331m as a result of the widening of operating margin
from 6.3 per cent to 7 per cent.
Capital expenditure was Pounds 442m as Argyll opened 17 Safeway stores. This
year 25 stores are due to open with spending projected to increase to Pounds
550m.
Interest income - including Pounds 2.5m in dividends from its shareholdings
in two mainland European retailers, Ahold and Casino - was Pounds 33.5m.
This was considerably higher than the previous year's Pounds 5.5m income
because of the cash inflow from last June's Pounds 387m rights issue.
The company received Pounds 78.3m in extraordinary income from the
settlement of its legal claim against Guinness over the Distillers bid. The
taxman took Pounds 19.8m of the Pounds 100m settlement while Pounds 1.9m
disappeared in legal costs.
Earnings per share grew 12 per cent to 24.2p. A final dividend of 6.55p will
lift the annual payout by 15 per cent to 9.75p.
This set of results marked the fifth year since Argyll acquired the Safeway
supermarket chain. Under its ownership, Safeway's sales have increased
threefold and profits sixfold.
'We are quite proud of what we have achieved,' said Mr David Webster, deputy
chairman.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
