<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Westpac announces record loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WESTPAC Banking Corporation, Australian's biggest trading bank, has declared
the largest loss in the country's banking history following a massive
increase in property loan writedowns. The dividend has been cut and the
capital base strengthened through a ADollars 1.2bn rights issue.
It yesterday disclosed a ADollars 2.6bn (USDollars 1.96bn) turnround for the
half year to March, sending it to a pre-tax loss of ADollars 2.32bn against
a ADollars 313.4m profit last time. The bank's bottom-line loss was ADollars
1.67bn after a ADollars 713m tax credit and adjustment for minorities,
compared with a ADollars 218m profit previously.
The three-for-10 renounceable rights issue is at ADollars 3 a share. The
issue will not be underwritten, and the price compares with Westpac's close
of Dollars 3.89 in Sydney yesterday, down 5 cents.
Mr Frank Conroy, managing director, said the bank anticipated a 'sound'
profit in the current half and would pay a 12 cents a share interim
dividend, against 15 cents last time. This rate was expected to be
maintained for the full year.
He said the Reserve Bank supported the company's conservative approach and
had confirmed that, even after provisions, Westpac would satisfy official
capital adequacy requirements.
The Westpac loss follows bad and doubtful debt write-offs of ADollars
2.65bn, an increase from ADollars 579m last time. More than ADollars 2.1bn
of write-downs reflect revaluations of the ADollars 6.3bn property
portfolio.
Mr Conroy said average revaluations were 34 per cent below book value.
Westpac has also taken a much more pessimistic view of its 'problem' loans,
increasing provisioning from 28 to 47 per cent, raising their value from
ADollars 6.4bn to ADollars 8.2bn, or more than 10.6 per cent of the
company's total risk-adjusted assets.
Mr Conroy said shareholders would benefit in two ways. 'First, with the
values recognised as current market value, the bank can implement a strategy
of orderly disposal. But I stress the word orderly. There will be no fire
sales or dumping of property on the market.
'Second, as the size of our property problem reduces, the burden on future
profits from these non-performing assets will reduce.'
Lex, Page 22; Background, Page 31
