<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / The Lex Column: Commercial Union
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's placing of Pounds 100m of irredeemable preference shares is the
clearest sign yet that CU is moving off the back foot. The company was
forced to become risk averse in the mid 1980s after disastrous losses in the
US, a policy which, as it happens, enabled it to avoid most of the mortgage
guarantee problems now haunting its competitors. Emboldened by a more
encouraging first quarter, CU is now in a position to take a more aggressive
stance on new premium growth.
Shareholders might not have been easily persuaded to put up the money
themselves, and would certainly have demanded a heavy price. But they are
still entitled to ask whether the chosen instrument best suits their
interests. The advantage is that the shares will count as capital for
solvency margin purposes - taking this ratio from 41 per cent at the end of
the first quarter to 44 per cent - while the gross rate of 11.55 per cent is
almost a half-point cheaper than that recently paid by Halifax building
society on a similar issue. The claim that ordinary shareholders' returns
are being attractively geared up will depend on whether the UK general
insurance cycle really is on the turn.
Certainly the tentative conclusion from the composite insurance results of
the last week or so is that better premium rates are at last sticking in
most classes of business. The recovery, though, looks set to be long and
slow and the risk for CU is in picking up dud accounts. Its UK general
insurance premiums increased by no less than 26 per cent in the first
quarter, against a 2 per cent fall at General Accident and a single-figure
increase at Royal.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 22
</PAGE>
