FT  21 MAY 92 / Letter: Pointers to an economic upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From M WHITWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I refer to Peter Marsh's article 'How To Figure Out The End of
Recession' (Management, May 18).
If one accepts the thesis that it is small business which generates
underlying growth in the economy and creates employment, then statistics on
new business start-ups and liquidations/insolvencies will provide a valuable
indicator. There are many sources of this information and I would like to
highlight one set of figures which may be of interest, new company
formations.
Limited companies are predominantly private rather than public and small
rather than large. New company formations may therefore provide a useful
indicator of start-up activity.
Year on year growth in new company formations was the norm until the year
ended March 1989. Over the most recent three years numbers have
progressively fallen and we are yet to see an upturn. When and if an upturn
occurs, maybe this will be an important indicator that the UK is moving out
of recession.
M Whitwell,
chief executive,
Jordan and Sons,
21 St Thomas Street,
Bristol BS1 6JS
