<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Leading Article: RPI RIP
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH pride themselves on scoring own goals; and nowhere is this more
true than in economic statistics. The Retail Prices Index has probably been
responsible for more own goals than most.
The particular fatuousness of the RPI lies in the fact that when the
government increases interest rates to combat inflation, the immediate
impact is to make inflation even worse. This arises because mortgage
interest rates feature in the RPI. There is an equally adverse effect when
interest rates are reduced. The net result is to produce violent swings
around the trend.
Governments would have to grin and bear it if the RPI represented some kind
of final truth. But to present the RPI as an accurate measure is simply
laughable. Most countries do not count mortgage interest payments. Instead,
house prices or rents enter one way or another. With the gradual revival of
the rented market in the UK, this method might be used for the British RPI.
It is therefore good, if belated, news that the chancellor is to refer the
treatment of owner occupiers' housing costs to the Retail Prices Index
Advisory Committee. But loud cheering is not the order of the day, for there
are fundamental fallacies behind the RPI and the Advisory Committee. The
first is that there is a single method of measuring the price level of goods
and services which is equally suitable for economic policy, uprating
benefits, updating taxes, indexing gilts and using in pay negotiations.
It is for instance often argued that the RPI has an inflationary bias
because prices would appear to rise by about 2 per cent a year simply as a
result of quality improvements in products included in the index. But if 2
per cent were docked off social security benefits for this reason, hardship
would soon result, as the majority of hidden quality improvements probably
take place in products such as hi-fi systems beyond the reach of
beneficiaries.
But the biggest anachronism of all is the Advisory Committee itself, which
is a survival of the 1960s and 1970s, and represents many vested interests
who are determined to get as much out of cost-of-living compensation as
possible. Better to leave the job to the Central Statistical Office, subject
to ministerial supervision and parliamentary scrutiny.
If anyone fears that the government would then tamper with the index for
political reasons, he or she need only glance at the immense powers of the
cabinet secretary to make sure that the rules of the game are obeyed. And if
anyone believes that the cabinet secretary's disapproval would remain
discreetly hidden, he has a lot to learn about how government works in the
world's oldest semi-democracy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6986</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAATFT</PROFILE>
