<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Leading Article: Soccer it and see
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WHILE the British parliament yesterday debated the pros and cons of European
integration, the streets of London assumed a continental air. Baking sun,
waving flags and the sing-song accents of Spanish and Italian football fans
added to the cosmopolitan feel. The European cup final was in town.
But the British were only spectators, a fitting finale to the dismal
standard of football in this year's English football league. Last Sunday
against Brazil, England's national team was made to look leaden, prompting
from the manager an uncharacteristic footballing understatement, that his
squad 'lacks individual flair'.
Yet while Europe's politicians ponder and prevaricate, the people's sport is
pushing out to new borders. Yesterday the European Football Union (UEFA)
decided that clubs from Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia can enter European
competitions; the republics of Slovenia, Croatia, Ukraine and Georgia are
knocking on the door.
European integration is the key to English football's salvation. The trend
towards big clubs and European competition is commercially unstoppable. That
the contract to televise English football has apparently been awarded to a
European-based satellite company is a sign of things to come.
Europe may not have a single currency by the end of the decade, but it
certainly should have a European soccer league. The top few English clubs
will then have to emulate the skills of continental Europeans, or get beaten
by them every week.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
