<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAASFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Europe's new muddle army: Plans for military co-operation
will have to disentangle overlapping forces and command structures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It did not look such a great idea. Putting together a Franco-German brigade
of 4,200 soldiers took three years' preparation. When it was inaugurated
near Stuttgart in 1990, senior French officers admitted it would take
somewhat longer before anyone would consider sending the brigade into
combat.
Two French regiments, two German battalions; one kind of beret but different
codes of discipline, pay structures, radio systems, ammunition. Headquarters
staff spoke French to each other one day, German the next, occasionally
resorting to English. Le Monde dubbed it the unite-gadget, the gimmick unit.
The French army seemed happy to keep it small.
Yet the apparently fanciful experiment has become the embryo of a grand
project. At their summit starting today in La Rochelle, President Francois
Mitterrand and Chancellor Helmut Kohl are set to agree the blueprint for a
joint corps, starting at about 35,000 men, ready in three years and intended
as the nucleus of a future European army.
For now, it is the nucleus of a disorderly tangle involving Europeans and
Americans in intense diplomatic exchanges on the nature of European defence
initiatives and their impact on Nato. The arguments are not about the
principle of joint forces, but how they should be organised and who they
should take orders from. They are not yet about what these forces might
actually do in crises like Yugoslavia's.
Ideas for new military combinations have been taking shape for about two and
a half years. They arise from two distinct perspectives - Nato restructuring
and development of the European Community.
For Nato, multinational groupings were the best way it could keep a cohesive
military structure after losing the enemy that for 40 years provided its
reason for being. Almost all its members were cutting defences. Combined
formations could rationalise these forces and make the continued presence of
foreign troops in Germany more acceptable to the Germans. At the same time,
the US was contemplating progressively bigger reductions in its troop levels
in Europe - currently being halved to 150,000, with further withdrawals
widely expected. By common accord, Europe had to take more responsibility
for its own defence. Since relatively small forces were now required to be
ready at short notice, it was logical that these should essentially come
from the Europeans.
Other notions of joint European defence - maybe, one day - on a more
grandiose scale, were meanwhile appearing on the EC's horizon in the
build-up to last December's Maastricht summit, coinciding with Nato's
strategy review.
Convergence was always going to be difficult, however. The EC had always
left defence to Nato. There was a defence body straddling the two, the
Western European Union (WEU), consisting of nine members of both the EC and
the alliance, but it enjoyed no public profile, had been dormant for much of
its existence, and had no troops. Nato, always busy trying to patch over its
internal strains, was meanwhile searching for a new purpose, and Washington
was going to be edgy about any attempt to rock the boat.
And then, as always, there was the complicating factor of France. It is
where Nato used to have its headquarters, has five other Nato allies on its
borders, but for 25 years has had no part in the allied military hierarchy
or in its joint military planning. It is now the nation most eager to carry
the flag for Euro-defence.
Nato got in first. A year ago, Britain leapt at the suggestion by General
John Galvin, Supreme Allied Commander Europe (Saceur), that it should head a
new rapid reaction corps of at least four divisions: 70,000 men. It would be
a Nato force, but could also provide units for a European reaction force;
commanders would just swap their Nato hat for a WEU hat. Under the WEU's
wing, the forces could be sent outside the Nato area - something on which
Nato has never reached a consensus.
France saw the plan as a crude bid to pre-empt its own efforts to create a
European defence structure that would be something more than a by-product of
Nato. The Germans participated in the plan, but thought they had been
stampeded by the British.
When France and Germany came out with their own plan for a joint corps in
October, the reaction from Washington and London was even sourer. Some other
European allies shared their concern that it could undermine the alliance,
in particular loosening the cement which since the 1950s had kept Germany at
the heart of Nato.
The UK, anxious not to alienate the US, contests the logic that Nato's role
should decline proportionately as Europe's defence role increases. Some
other EC partners are also cautious about the Franco-German plan, including
the Dutch and Portuguese. But, one senior British diplomat says, for most
European countries 'it is very difficult to tell the French to get lost'.
Behind the careful compromises worked out at Nato's Rome summit in November
('the development of a European security and defence role . . . the
enhancement of the role and responsibility of the European members') and the
tantalisingly hedged ambitions endorsed by EC leaders at Maastricht in
December ('the eventual framing of a common defence policy, which might in
time lead to common defence') lie two fundamentally different approaches.
For the French, it is prudent for Europe to make preparations independently
of the US. From a British viewpoint, that is the kind of attitude that will
make the US leave.
Nato has constantly reiterated the need for a continued 'North American
presence' in Europe. Canada, which up to now has shared this transatlantic
function with the US, dealt allies a nasty surprise in February by saying it
would pull its small remaining force out altogether. Keeping US forces, even
at much reduced levels, is seen as providing the crucial linkage to Nato's
ultimate defence guarantee, the US nuclear 'umbrella'. US involvement in
Nato also stands as a more general emblem of transatlantic co-operation. Gen
Galvin describes his post as 'America's seat at the table in Europe'.
Sensitivity to this US view has led Nato allies to shelve the idea of
appointing a European Saceur for the first time. Instead, Gen Galvin will
hand over next month to another US army officer, Gen John Shalikashvili. As
part of the military overhaul, the number of Nato commands is being been
reduced, but Americans hold on to the two top posts - the supreme commands
for Europe and the Atlantic - and to the southern Europe command in Naples.
The paradoxical result is that, while Nato is being redesigned to take on a
more European complexion, the US has a bigger share of the top military
jobs.
Britain opposes setting up any parallel European command structure -
confusing, it says, and a waste of money. The WEU is, however, to have a
contingency planning staff of 40.
The WEU is being brought into service because it is there. The body once had
an incipient military organisation but handed it over when Nato was formed.
It embodies a firmer commitment than Nato's for allies to come to each
other's aid. But its own military involvement has not gone beyond
co-ordinating some Gulf naval operations.
Britain wants it to be balanced halfway between Nato and the EC. But the
language of Maastricht ties it more closely to the Community, as 'an
integral part of the development of the European Union' and the executor of
EC decisions that have defence implications. The WEU is set to co-ordinate
closely with the Community, moving its secretariat from London to Brussels
and opening its membership to other EC states. European Nato allies outside
the Community may only join as associates.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the UK defence secretary, last week spelt out initial
proposals for forces that might be made available to the WEU. How big they
were would be up the WEU, but there would be no standing forces and the
organisation would draw on existing headquarters. He accepted that the
Franco-German corps could be well suited for the task but only as one of a
number of available units.
France is lobbying hard to persuade other WEU members to give the corps more
substance by joining. But there are few immediate candidates. Belgium is the
most likely - the reason for a lightning visit there by Mr Rifkind on
Tuesday - but appears still to be hesitating. Britain says clearly it will
not join, but would contribute other forces for the WEU. These could include
the existing UK-Netherlands amphibious force and the air-mobile division
which Britain, Germany, Holland and Belgium are jointly forming as part of
Nato's rapid reaction corps.
But Nato would have first call on the troops. Mr Rifkind allowed that the
WEU might be called on to act within Europe, but only when Nato chose not be
engaged. It was 'hard to conceive of significant combat operations in Europe
where Nato would not be involved'.
The Germans, alert to the worries of the US and other allies, have given
firm assurances that their own troops will remain assigned to Nato. The
French foresee arrangements under which the whole corps could be placed
under Saceur's wartime operational control. This is clearly distinct from
assigning French troops automatically to Nato. But the Germans say the corps
promises to associate France more closely with Nato's military partners, to
Nato's benefit.
The Bonn authorities meanwhile appear to see the corps as a possible way of
easing the constraints on German military involvement abroad, something that
the constitution is usually read as precluding.
Still unclear are the corps' relationship to the WEU - the US fears it may
create yet a third layer of military control - and its geographical scope.
'It seems odd,' admits Mr Willem van Eekelen, the WEU secretary-general, 'to
argue to the French and Germans to make these forces available for
everything except defence of their territory'.
WEU foreign and defence ministers are expected to approve outline plans for
putting troops at the organisation's disposal when they meet in Bonn on June
19. But it will all take time to clarify, and even then it will be an
agreement on means rather than ultimate aims.
Through the conceptual wrangling, the diplomatic niceties and the recondite
arguments can be glimpsed a familiar spectacle of the old European military
powers jockeying for influence.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6988</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAARFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Leading Article: Forward from Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Major claimed yesterday, in opening the House of Commons debate on
the Treaty of Maastricht, that the treaty 'marks for the Community an
important and vital change of direction', in that it had 'for the first time
begun to reverse the centralising trend', and to move decision-making power
back towards the member states.
He was elegant enough not to dot the i, but this was in fact a neat and
telling response to the criticisms of his predecessor, who signed the Single
European Act in 1987. 'You allowed the centralising Euro-steamroller to
continue on its way,' he was saying to her in substance, 'whereas I have not
merely stopped in its tracks but obliged it to change direction'.
Thus he made much of the fact that the provisions of the treaty relating to
foreign and security policy, justice and home affairs do not figure in the
bill now before the House, because they are not modifications of the Treaty
of Rome, do not affect the law or institutions of the EC as such, and
therefore do not impinge directly on the law of the United Kingdom. Instead
they are separate 'pillars' of the European Union, in the form of
international agreements among the member states to co-operate in certain
specific matters. Disputes arising from them, Mr Major said, could if
necessary be brought before the International Court of Justice (which can
only arbitrate in disputes between states), but not before the European
Court (whose judgments, which may involve private firms or individuals, take
precedence over those of domestic courts).
Subsidiarity enshrined
Mr Major also stressed the treaty's enshrinement of the principle of
subsidiarity in EC law, in what he believes are legally binding terms -
although these terms are in fact much too abstract for anyone to predict
with confidence how the court will interpret them when they are put to the
test. His basic message was clear: the dragon of centralising federalism has
been slain, and the way is now clear for Britain, during its presidency in
the second half of this year, to take the lead in a chastened and more
pragmatic Community, which will at last give due priority to the interests
of a wider Europe, opening negotiations with the EFTA countries and
preparing the way for the admission of those further east.
Yet Mr Major's own speech contained some clues which show that things will
not in practice be that simple. He drew the House's attention to the fact
that there could be no increase in the EC's resources without British
agreement, and he served notice that he had 'no intention of agreeing' to
any reduction in the rebate on Britain's contribution.
Cohesion fund
The fact is that the Community's southern members regard an increase in
resources as a priority. Only this week a Spanish minister served notice
that Spain will block the process of admitting new members unless it gets
agreement on the early introduction of the 'cohesion fund' agreed at
Maastricht to help the poorer member states prepare for economic and
monetary union. This entails an increase in resources, as proposed by Mr
Jacques Delors in February.
The full Delors package may not go through, but any increase will sharpen
the determination of other member states who are net contributors, notably
Germany, to insist on a reduction, if not outright abolition, of Britain's
rebate. Argument on these homely questions, not to mention predictable
hand-wringing and recrimination over the corpse of Yugoslavia, will take the
edge off any grand British design to give the Community a new lead.
It is true that in many other member states the ratification process has
produced a lively debate, which outside Britain had been notable for its
absence in the period before Maastricht; and it is true that in the process
some of Britain's anxieties about the erosion of national sovereignty have
found an echo elsewhere in the EC. But the next stage of the institutional
argument will not, as Mr Major seems to think, be about the transfer of
powers to or from Brussels. It will be about the best method of taking
decisions on matters already admitted to be of common concern, in the
context of an expanding EC membership; and the more members there are, the
harder it will be to leave any important issue at the mercy of a veto by any
one of them.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
