<PROFILE>_AN-CEUBBAAPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920521
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Arts: Bach cantatas - Music
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL DRIVER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
On so exquisite a summer's evening as Monday's it was all the odder to enter
the Queen Elizabeth Hall and submit oneself to a selection of Bach cantatas,
music that is manifestly intended for liturgical use. Yet there was nothing
gloomy and fusty about these period-style performances by the Orchestra and
Choir of the Age of Enlightenment, under Ivan Fischer. To the contrary,
everything was light and air and colour - colourful drama, indeed, to quote
the title of the six-concert series devised by Sir William Glock, of which
this was the first (the second was last night).
Each programme affords two or three of the vastly numerous (nearly 300) and
varied cantatas along with a selection from the motets, concerti and
orchestral suites (there are two other conductors involved, Rene Jacobs for
the second pair of concerts, Barthold Kuijken for the third). Monday's
programme attracted a virtually full house, as 'authentic' baroque
performance usually does these days, whatever the weather. The first of our
three cantatas, No. 110, 'Unser Mund sei voll Lachens', written for
Christmas Day 1725, was an apt and festive opening chorus, despatched with
bright irresistible crispness and panache.
Cantata No. 104, 'Du Hirte Israel, Hore' (1724) followed, bringing the
mellow oboes d'amore to the fore as well as tenor and bass vocal soloists.
The latter, Michael George, gave an affecting account of his lilting
pastoral aria, whose instrumental bass parts Fischer brought out with a
discreet complementary pungency. The double 12-part choir (with the merest
continuo accompaniment) produced a poised, compact but dramatically
expressive polyphony in the short motet, 'Komm, Jesu, Komm]' (BWV 229). The
fourth Brandenburg Concerto was done without conductor and with sprightly
soloists: recorder players Catherine Latham and Anthony Robson, violinist
Elizabeth Wallfisch (leader of the OAE), who executed the fast decorative
scales of the first movement in a fine spray of virtuosity.
After the interval we were treated to the plaintive sombre funerary colours
of the motet 'O Jesu Christ, Mein's Lebens Licht' (BWV 118) and the graphic
St. Michael's Day cantata No. 130, 'Herr Gott, dich loben alle wir' (1724).
The opening choral-instrumental movement was rendered with keen, brilliant
pointing of rhythm; tenor Christoph Pregardien's gigue-like duet with Lisa
Beznosiuk's flute was charming. Bach cantatas are wonderful things: full of
the bracing inventiveness of his Passions, without their longueurs, and
never two the same. My appetite is whetted for the rest of these splendidly
conceived concerts.
</TEXT>
