<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / People: Spending a bit of money on pubs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ross Cope, formerly with specialist mortgage provider First Mortgage
Securities, is the new treasurer of Inntrepreneur Estates (IEL), the pub
investment company set up last year by GrandMet and Foster's.
He is an expert in securitisation, or repackaging debt as saleable
securities, and is looking forward to bringing 'a novel financing technique
into the pub market'. At First Mortgage Securities he had been treasury
director, funding and securitising UK mortgages; hence Cope, 44, claims to
be one of a small clutch of people 'who have actually done it rather than
simply talk about it'.
But while the funding side may have been a success, the specialist mortgage
providers that sprang into life during the boom years of the 1980s, have
been particularly badly hit by repossessions, and are narrowly eyeing their
future commitment to the market.
As a technique suitable for thinly capitalised companies, securitisation
should work for IEL, which owns pubs and leases them out on 20-year
contracts. One of Cope's tasks will be to refinance the Pounds 1.32bn loan
taken out at IEL's inception.
An accountant who had a spell as treasurer of Girobank, he is a fan of
GrandMet's concept of managing pubs as properties in their own right. 'After
a month in the new job, I have worked out how you spot Inntrepreneur pubs.
They are the ones that look up-market, with a bit of money spent on them -
basically they don't look like pubs.'
</TEXT>
