<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: NRA criticised over expenditure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs HAVE strongly condemned the National Rivers Authority for weaknesses in
financial management that led to wasted expenditure of Pounds 1m and the
resignation of its first chief executive.
A report from the Public Accounts Committee published yesterday criticises
the Environment Department, Lord Crickhowell, chairman of the NRA, and his
board for failing to keep a sufficiently close eye on the water pollution
organisation's expenditure.
The primary reason for the criticism, which is extremely outspoken for a
parliamentary committee, was evidence that rules for spending large sums of
money had been ignored in fitting out the NRA's new head office in Bristol.
The project resulted in the wasting of about Pounds 1m out of a total cost
of Pounds 2.65m, and the resignation last June of Mr John Bowman, chief
executive, with a pay-off of Pounds 125,000. Two other senior executives
received written warnings for ignoring the financial procedures laid down
for the NRA.
In July, 1990, the NRA engaged Corporate Design Interiors (CDI) to advise on
relocating and to help choose contractors. It was also one of three firms
asked to tender for the Pounds 12,000 contract to design the layout of the
new offices.
The NRA then decided to combine the design contract with a much bigger one
for fitting out the building. Instead of asking several firms to tender, it
considered only two that had bid for the much smaller design job. The Pounds
2.65m contract went to CDC, a sister company of CDI, without Lord
Crickhowell, Mr Bowman or the NRA board being told.
An internal inquiry found that had the job been properly managed it would
have cost only Pounds 1.6m. It also said that the NRA's own board needed to
be more vigilant on spending.
The NRA said last night there had been 'serious shortcomings' in the
management of fitting out the Bristol head office, which resulted in poor
value for money.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
