FT  21 MAY 92 / Democrats seek probe over Iraq support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of influential Democratic members of the US Congress is seeking the
appointment of a special prosecutor to investigate possible wrongdoing by
the Bush administration in its support of President Saddam Hussein of Iraq,
before his August 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
The House of Representatives judiciary committee said yesterday it planned
to hold a hearing on whether to name an independent counsel.
This follows allegations by Mr Henry Gonzalez, chairman of the House banking
committee, and others in Congress, that the administration is trying to
cover up its misuse of government loan guarantees that Iraq had obtained for
agricultural purchases, but then used to acquire military goods and
technology.
At the core of the matter is an alleged abuse of loan guarantees for
supposed agricultural exports to Iraq that were financed by the branch in
Atlanta of Italy's Banca Nazionale del Lavoro (BNL).
The BNL affair is beginning to attract widespread attention in the US media,
with the approach of the trial of Mr Christopher Drogoul, former BNL Atlanta
manager accused of making more than Dollars 4bn of improper loans to Iraq
from his branch. The trial, due to begin on June 2, was yesterday postponed
to June 22.
Documents obtained by the Financial Times show that a substantial part of
these loans helped Iraq's nuclear, chemical and missile projects.
