<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / Drop in US housing starts may lead to interest rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BIGGEST monthly drop in US housing starts for more than eight years
prompted renewed speculation yesterday that the Federal Reserve might soon
signal another cut in interest rates.
Housing starts fell by 17 per cent in April, a far bigger decline than most
analysts had expected.
The figures were released by the Commerce Department as governors and
regional presidents of the Federal Reserve, the central bank, met in
Washington to review monetary policy.
On Wall Street, the benchmark long bond closed more than half a point up on
the news, on hopes of an interest rate cut, and the Dow Jones Industrial
Average closed at a record 3,397.99, up 21.96.
The drop in starts affected all regions and categories of residential
property, including single-family homes, down 11 per cent.
Following other warning signals, including a decline in new house sales, the
drop seems to indicate a loss of momentum in residential housing, one of the
few sectors of the economy to rebound strongly from recession.
The consensus is that the economy is growing sluggishly, at an annual rate
of 2-3 per cent. However, the setback in housing is likely to fuel doubts
about the pace and sustainability of recovery. Car sales - another critical
barometer - remain subdued, while unemployment claims are still abnormally
high.
Wall Street analysts have been predicting an easing of monetary policy. If
the Fed acts, the likeliest move is a  1/4 -point cut in the federal funds
rate to 3.5 per cent, the floor set by the current level of the discount
rate at which the Fed lends to banks. This would trigger a 1/2 -point cut in
banks' prime lending rates to 6 per cent.
The Fed is under political pressure to ease monetary policy because monetary
growth is barely above the lower limit of its 2.5-6.5 per cent target range.
However, it may decide that lower rates would only increase fears of higher
inflation.
Housing starts in April were running at an annual rate of 1.1m, the lowest
level since November but 14 per cent higher than last April.
Mr Maury Harris, chief economist at New York broker Paine Webber, said
starts were likely to rebound in coming months, reflecting a slight fall in
mortgage rates since April.
Observer, Page 19
Treasuries advance, Page 31
Dollar drops, Page 33
World stocks, Page 39
</TEXT>
