<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / Observer: Own goal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
What on earth is happening to Professor Sir Roland Smith? Ever since he lost
his job as chairman of British Aerospace last autumn, he has been shedding
his outside directorships. But he is now said to be contemplating stepping
down as chairman of his beloved Manchester United.
The Prof, who not so long ago sat on the boards of more public companies
than anyone, told an American Chamber of Commerce lunch yesterday that he is
'unlikely to remain chairman of Manchester United'. However, before he can
quit the United directors' bench he has to get the nod of approval from the
court of directors of the Bank of England on which he sits.
He says that it's the first time such a 'mundane point' has ever been
considered by the court. Perhaps it is. But Sir Roland would have gone up in
Observer's estimation considerably if he had announced that he was handing
in his notice at the Bank of England and devoting more time to United. He
would have to attend far fewer board meetings, Old Trafford is much closer
to his home, and its financial affairs would benefit from his continued
attention.
