<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Prescott wins Oscarin battle over
lunch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF AN ability to raise the spirits of party activists is the chief goal for
Labour's leadership candidates, Mr John Prescott should abandon his campaign
to be deputy leader and run for the top job.
Yesterday, the Manufacturing Science and Finance union welcomed all four
leadership contenders to address its annual conference in Bournemouth and,
to the surprise of some, it was the shadow transport secretary who went home
with the Oscar.
Yet the day was also replete with ironies. This, after all, was the judgment
of the largely leftwing delegates of a union representing thousands of
Tory-voting white-collar workers, while the affluent south coast resort town
appeared wholly oblivious of the passionate debate on the future of
socialism taking part in its midst.
Each candidate played his or her part in character. Mrs Margaret Beckett
used her 15-minute address to play the gender card, making the case for a
fresh appeal to women voters. Mr Bryan Gould, an MSF member, sold himself as
the 'ideas candidate' but was in danger of losing his audience in a
sophisticated argument about devaluation, referring to the gold standard and
sterling M3.
Battling against the effects of lunch on the 300-odd delegates, Mr John
Smith's 18-page speech was respectfully if unspectacularly received. And
before Mr Prescott appeared, it was widely held that Mr Gould was the narrow
points victor.
However, that was not to reckon with the pugnacious MP for Hull. Squinting,
ad-libbing and at times tripping over his text, he none the less injected
the right note of indignant exasperation that prompted repeated bursts of
applause.
Mr Prescott's basic thesis remained unchanged. What the party needed, he
said, was someone to grab it by the scruff of the neck and shake up its
organisation.
With characteristic plain speaking, he went on to bash the Tories and the
press, with a sideswipe at the party leadership for good measure.
'There is much talk of the need for new radicalism and new vision in the
Labour party - not that I resist new ideas - but I'm firmly convinced that,
adequately presented, our historic values remain as true today as ever.'
Where the other candidates won barely 30 seconds of respectful sedentary
applause, Mr Prescott ended with a full minute of standing ovation.
It was a triumph of a kind. But as a long-time champion of electoral reform
reflected, in the Pavilion Theatre's upper circle: 'Under proportional
representation, he could be leader of that sort of party and bring a lot of
union influence to bear . . . in opposition.'
