<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM rules out protest in 'friendly
fire' deaths
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT signalled yesterday that it would take no action against the
US pilots involved in the deaths of nine UK soldiers killed by 'friendly
fire' in the Gulf war.
Mr John Major indicated to MPs that he did not believe the incident
justified a protest to Washington over its role in protecting of the pilots.
While lessons had to be learnt, he said, 'I hope we won't lose sight of the
fact that those were American pilots risking their lives alongside our
troops in a battle against a common enemy and to liberate Kuwait.'
Speaking after an Oxford inquest ruled on Monday that the nine were
'unlawfully killed', the prime minister faced pressure by Mr Neil Kinnock,
the Labour leader, to use his authority to ensure the victims' families had
the full truth. Mr Major replied: 'I'm not in a position to provide any more
information.'
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, later admitted that in the immediate
aftermath of the Gulf war, 'there was some confusion and uncertainty about
what exactly happened'. While the war had ended in February, the US Marine
Corps had not answered points raised in the Ministry of Defence inquiry
until July 10, he said.
However, Ministry of Defence officials said that all available information
was now in the hands of the victims' families.
Mr Rifkind said the UK was working closely with its allies to ensure that in
future, 'the risk of troops firing on their comrades is minimised'.
Meanwhile, Mrs Barbara Mills QC, director of public prosecutions, has asked
to see all the relevant documents held by the Oxford coroner and the MoD on
the incident.
The DPP's office said yesterday that Mrs Mills would consider the papers in
detail to see whether there was sufficient evidence to bring criminal
charges against the two US pilots allegedly responsible.
Her office repeated though, that there was no power to prosecute a foreign
national in England and Wales for any offence of murder or manslaughter
allegedly committed abroad.
</TEXT>
