<DATE>920520
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / Flat-rate pension rebates 'too costly'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TAX REBATES to encourage young people to opt out of the state
earnings-related pensions scheme (Serps) should be reduced and larger
rebates offered to older people, according to the Institute for Fiscal
Studies.
The institute concludes in a study of financial arrangements for personal
pensions that the present system of flat-rate tax rebates costs the
government more in forgone revenue than it can ever save on social security
payments.
'There is no particular reason to favour younger workers over older,' the
institute concludes.
By the time an individual has reached the late 40s, it is no longer
advantageous to hold a personal pension and policyholders would be well
advised to opt back into Serps, says the institute. The age at which the
advantage disappears depends on whether the personal-pension holder is male
or female and on the assumptions of investment returns earned on
contributions.
The government has ruled out age-related rebates, arguing that they would
not provide enough incentives for young people to opt out of the system and
that they would be too confusing. Much of the life assurance industry, which
markets personal-pension plans, opposes any move to age-related rebates.
The government has said it will offer additional incentive payments only to
personal-pension holders over 30 from April next year. The rebate will still
be insufficient to discourage older people from rejoining the state scheme,
the study says.
Pension scheme sponsors need to increase contributions as members of schemes
grow older, the institute says. Thus lower contributions are needed for
younger members and higher ones for older members. The government's present
flat-rate rebates allow young people to buy a more generous personal pension
plan than they could achieve by remaining in Serps, but the contribution is
too small for older people to maintain personal pensions.
The institute also notes that transaction costs on personal pensions can
significantly reduce returns to policyholders. The institute concludes that
between a third and a fifth of contributions to a scheme can be eaten up in
charges.
The Personal Pensions Stampede. Institute for Fiscal Studies, 7 Ridgmount
Street, London WC1E. Pounds 20.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
