<DOCNO>FT922-7063</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CETCHAFDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920520
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / 'The prime minister must be the final judge': Code of
conduct for members of the government Warning on conflicts between private
investments and public duties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yester-day issued the guidelines on conduct that are given to
each minister on taking office. On investments, the document urges ministers
to 'order their affairs so that no conflict arises or is thought to arise
between their private interests and their public duties'. Where there is
doubt about an interest, 'it will almost always be better to relinquish or
dispose of the interest, but in such cases the prime minister must be the
final judge'.
The document shows that Westminster and the City are miles apart in their
approach to handling the many potential conflicts of interest that arise
between private investments and public duties.
City institutions generally take a permissive attitude: directors and other
senior staff are allowed to own shares in companies they advise, for
instance. Yet any dealings have to be disclosed internally - and many houses
operate a policy of allowing staff to trade only with prior approval from a
central compliance officer.
Ministers are subjected to one general rule - that they avoid all conflicts
of interest. Investments that could give rise to conflicts, or perception of
conflicts, should be disposed of. Such guidance looks idealistic. 'It would
be nice if you could see all conflicts in advance,' says Mr Colin Condron,
compliance officer at Barclays de Zoete Wedd, the investment bank.
He suggested that one route for ministers might be to ban investments in
equities, or restrict them to investment trusts. Alternatively, ministers
could be required to put their shares into 'blind' trusts, under which they
are not given any information about their investments - one of the
suggestions in the document for ministers who have a wide range of
investments.
Even that may not save ministers from embarrassment: 2 1/2 years ago, Mr
Cecil Parkinson, then transport secretary, was forced to issue a denial that
he had been involved in insider dealing after share trans-actions undertaken
by brokers WI Carr in the name of his nominee account.
The official guidelines to ministers say they should declare to colleagues
any private interest if they have to discuss public business in any way
affecting it. They should also 'remain entirely detached from consideration
of that business'.
There is no formal restriction - other than the normal rules on MPs'
interests, on former ministers taking up posts or other private-sector
interests - 'although they should naturally avoid any course which would
reflect adversely on their or the government's reputation for integrity or
the confidentiality of its proceedings'. On taking up office, the document
says, ministers should give up any other public appointment.
Directorships: Ministers must resign all directorships when they take up
office, the document says. The exceptions are directorships in private
companies established in connection with private family estates  - and
charitable organisations, unless there is a possible conflict of interest.
Partners in professional firms should cease any role in day-to-day
management of the firm's affairs, but need not dissolve their partnership or
allow their annual practising certificate to lapse. 'It is not possible to
lay down precise rules applicable to every case,' the document says.
'Ministers in doubt about their personal position should consult the prime
minister.'
Investments: Ministers cannot be expected to dispose of all investments. But
if a minister holds a controlling interest in any company, the
considerations are similar to those governing the holding of directorships.
The document points out that an investment in concerns closely associated
with a minister's department may create the danger of an actual or apparent
conflict of interest arising from exercise of powers or other influence in a
way that affects the value of the investment or from dealings where there
may be reasonable suspicion that the minister has special knowledge.
Ministers called upon to exercise any power or discretion or other influence
that could give rise to an actual or apparent conflict of interest should
delegate to another minister, and should take no part in the preparation or
reaching of any relevant decisions.
Ministers are bound by the provisions of the Companies Securities (Insider
Dealing) Act 1985 in relation to the use or transmission of unpublished
price-sensitive information obtained by virtue of their ministerial office.
Ministers are also urged to avoid speculative investments about which they
have, or may be thought to have, early or confidential information likely to
affect the price.
Ministers 'will wish to consider whether or not investments of their (minor)
children and their spouse should be treated similarly to their own'. The
document stresses that it is for ministers to judge what action they need to
take in respect of investments, but they should record any action in a
minute to the permanent secretary of the department.
Membership of Lloyd's: The prime minister, the chancellor of the exchequer,
the trade and industry secretary - and DTI and Treasury ministers
responsible for matters relating to Lloyd's - should not be underwriting
members of Lloyd's.
Any such minister who has been an underwriting member should not exercise
statutory powers affecting Lloyd's - or any syndicates, brokers or agents
with which he or she is connected - until all syndicate years for which he
or she was an underwriting member have been closed or until he or she has
reinsured all liabilities in such a way that he or she has no further
interest in their performance.
A law officer who is an underwriting member of Lloyd's, or who still has
open syndicate commitments in respect of past membership, should not tender
advice on the formulation, application or enforcement of legislation
relating to Lloyd's.
It is 'inappropriate' for other ministers who are members of Lloyd's to take
an active part in the management of the affairs of syndicates of which they
are members.
Ministers who are Lloyd's Names may be required to suspend underwriting
risks in any area in which their departments have responsibility.
Every minister is required on appointment to a first or subsequent
ministerial office to obtain the prime minister's permission before
continuing a connection with Lloyd's, however nominal. Any minister wishing
to establish any such connection during his term of appointment should
likewise obtain the prime minister's permission to do so. The secretary of
the cabinet is required to keep a list of ministers who are members of
Lloyd's.
Cabinet business: Cabinet and ministerial-committee business is defined as
consisting mainly of matters 'which significantly engage the collective
responsibility of the government because they raise major issues of policy
or because they are of critical importance to the public' and questions on
which there is an unresolved argument between departments.
Chairmen of ministerial committees are urged to limit references to the
cabinet. The only automatic right of appeal is if Treasury ministers are
unwilling to accept expenditure as a charge on the reserve. The document
says the internal process through which a decision has been made should not
be disclosed. Decisions reached by the cabinet or ministerial committees are
binding on all members of the government. Ministers and the law officers: It
will 'normally be appropriate to consult the law officers' in cases where:
The legal consequences of action by the government might have important
repercussions in the foreign, European Community or domestic field.
A departmental legal adviser is in doubt concerning the legality,
constitutional propriety or vires of proposed legislation or administrative
action.
There is a particular legal difficulty that may raise political aspects of
policy.
Two or more departments disagree on legal questions.
By convention, written opinions of the law officers, unlike other
ministerial papers, are generally made available to succeeding
administrations. Opinions of or advice from the law officers must not be
disclosed outside government without their authority.
Accountability: Each minister is responsible to parliament for the conduct
of his or her department.
Public appointments: In considering candidates for public appointments,
ministers should pay particular attention to securing, on merit, proper
representation of women and members of ethnic minorities on public bodies.
Acceptance of gifts and services: It is 'a well established and recognised
rule' that no minister should accept gifts or services from anyone that
would, or might appear to, place him or her under an obligation. The same
principle applies if gifts etc are offered to a member of their family.
</TEXT>
