<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / RPI housing factor review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has ordered a review of the way housing costs are treated in
the retail prices index, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, announced
yesterday.
In a parliamentary written answer, he disclosed that the government was
referring the treatment of owner occupiers' housing costs to the retail
prices index advisory committee, the body that advises the chancellor on the
method of construction and compilation of the RPI, the UK's main index of
inflation.
The move follows widespread criticism inside and outside parliament of the
method of measuring the cost of housing, which is based on mortgage interest
payments.
A particular complaint has been the way the method makes the RPI rise in
response to higher interest rates when those are introduced to control
inflation.
That has knock-on consequences for wage negotiations and other costs.
The inclusion of mortgage interest payments in the RPI has also been
criticised because they involve a large element of investment and because
they can be seen as measuring the cost of credit, while no other type of
credit charge is included in the index.
Only Britain and the Republic of Ireland among European Community member
states include mortgage interest payments in their main inflation measures.
Six EC countries make no allowance for owner occupier costs.
The chancellor's advisory committee is already investigating how the council
tax, holiday spending and new cars should be treated in the RPI.
</TEXT>
