<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / Rivera landscape sells for Dollars 1.21m: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LANDSCAPE painting by the Mexican artist Diego Rivera, 'Paisaje de
Toledo', giving a Cubist impression of the countryside around Toledo in
Spain, sold for Dollars 1.21m (Pounds 661,202) at Christie's in New York on
Monday night. It was bought by a Mexican dealer and reflects the strong
current demand for Mexican art.
The auction totalled Dollars 7.75m and was 24 per cent unsold. 'The
Temptation of St Anthony', a Surrealist work by Leonora Carrington, made
Dollars 440,000, an auction record for the artist.
Christie's sales of modern illustrated books and 20th-century decorative
arts in Geneva on Monday were less successful, with both nearly 50 per cent
unsold. The top price was the Pounds 37,218 paid for an autographed
manuscript by Jean Cocteau, Cherchez Apollon, illustrated with three
sketches.
Sotheby's also had difficulties, this time with tribal art in New York. The
most important lot, a rare Benin bronze head of a leopard, dating from the
17th century and estimated as worth as much as Dollars 500,000, was unsold.
There was little demand for medium-quality works, but an object from New
Guinea, a Middle Sepik River suspension hook, sold for Dollars 159,000, at
the top of its target. The auction brought in Dollars 1m, with 52 per cent
unsold.
Silver remains a healthy market and in Geneva an auction of European silver
totalled Pounds 2.5m and was more than 87 per cent sold. A French silver
gilt toilet service made by Francois-Daniel Imlin in Strasbourg in 1825 for
Stephanie, Grand Duchess of Baden, a protegee of Napoleon, sold for Pounds
228,461. A French silver soup tureen and cover, made by Jean-Baptiste de
Lens in Paris in 1736, far exceeded its forecast at Pounds 191,744.
</TEXT>
