<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / Bank notes optimism over recovery: The Quarterly Bulletin
cautions that the revival is likely to be slow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAUTIOUS optimism is back in fashion in Threadneedle Street.
The Bank of England in its latest quarterly bulletin says: 'The prospects
for recovery now appear better than for some time.' It warns, though, that
prospects are 'by no means uniform throughout the economy, and the pace of
recovery is likely to be slow, depending on the course of the world economy
and the impact of domestic and international financial fragility'.
Although the Bank believes output in Britain fell slightly in the first
quarter, it has taken heart from a recent recovery of business and consumer
confidence and the better mood of financial markets since the election.
Together with the May 5 cut in bank base rates to 10 per cent from 10.5 per
cent, 'these developments are encouraging and herald the prospect of an end
to recession,' it says. But the report also makes clear that much remains to
be done if the UK is to have as successful an economy as many of its rivals
abroad.
For that reason, the Bank lays great emphasis on Britain's fulfilling the
convergence criteria of the Maastricht Treaty on economic and monetary union
by 1996, when the European Community is due to discuss the possible move to
the third and final stage of Emu.
The Bank expects the present counter-inflationary stance will enable the UK
to meet the Maastricht terms on inflation and interest rates, but it has
doubts about the government's capacity to bring the ratio of the general
government deficit to the GDP from about 5 per cent at present to the
Maastricht level of below 3 per cent by the 1995-96 fiscal year.
The ratio of government debt to national income is likely to rise until
1995-96, which the Bank says would be the longest such rise for about 40
years. Achieving the 3 per cent ratio 'will require firm control of public
expenditure'. The government should therefore set 'a credible medium-term
target for public spending and borrowing'.
The Bank also urges greater efforts to lower inflation. It warns that direct
comparisons of consumer price trends between the UK and its EC partners can
be too flattering.
It says that there is 'no room for complacency' over earnings trends, even
though average earnings growth has moved more into convergence with that in
the UK's partners in the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary
System.
'Continued downward pressure on costs will be essential', especially if
Britain is to make the most of export opportunities. Here, too, there is
some additional cause for worry. Strong exports helped to support output
through much of the recession, but weakness in overseas markets is 'now
contributing to the uncertainty surrounding the strength and timing of
recovery' in Britain.
The pace of recovery will depend far more on progress in easing personal and
corporate debt burdens and developments in the property market.
The Bank notes that the fall in interest rates from 15 per cent in October
1990 'has not yet significantly strengthened confidence.' The personal
sector continued to increase its savings in the first quarter while its
gross income gearing ratio - the measure of households' gross interest
payments as a percentage of disposable income - was still high at 13 per
cent at the end of 1991 compared with its 1990 peak of 14 per cent.
The Bank suggests that falling house prices were one factor explaining the
public's muted response to lower interest rates. House repossessions were
another concern.
The commercial property market is also likely to remain depressed as
premises are completed and add to existing excess supply. The Bank notes
that office rents fell by more than a fifth up to the end of 1991, while one
estimate puts the drop in rental values for all properties in the City of
London at 38.9 per cent last year.
Corporate defaults have caused the banks greatly to increase their
provisions against bad debts. But the Bank says risk asset ratios remain
well above internationally agreed standards and there is no sign that bad
debts are causing banks to curb their lending.
Bank of England Quarterly Bulletin, May 1992. Vol. 32, No 2. Subscription
details from Bulletin Group, Economics Division, Bank of England, London
EC2R 8AH.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
