<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / IT sector warns of skills shortage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK faces a shortage of information technology skills which might lead to
an exodus of computer software and service companies, according to leading
IT companies.
Mr Paul Aspin, southern region industrial business manager for International
Business Machines, said: 'Companies can now base themselves wherever in the
world the relevant IT skills are, and use international networks to transmit
data from there.'
Mr Aspin, who is also a board director of West London Training and
Enterprise Council, warned that unless the relevant skills were developed,
the IT industry would move to continental Europe and elsewhere.
Investment in IT training per person in the UK is half that in Japan,
according to Mr Peter Bonfield, chairman and chief executive of ICL, the
computer group.
Lack of training by companies has meant that people who have the skills are
poached by companies at increasingly higher pay levels.
Dr Phil Blackburn, chief executive of the West London Tec, said: 'Short-term
recruitment ends up eating up funds that would be more effectively allocated
to long-term training.'
The Tec yesterday launched the IT Skills Forum, for which it has targeted
Pounds 1m to be spent on joint projects with members of the forum, such as
IBM, ICL and British Airways, to ensure that skills are developed.
As part of its programme, it is conducting a skills survey to track the
emerging skills needed by users.
The first phase of the survey has disclosed that 90 per cent of IT users
have no data processing or IT department responsible for transmitting
skills. The survey also reveals that most people who learn to use computers
do so by sitting next to someone with experience.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
