<DATE>920520
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / Jaguar reveals 2-stroke project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAGUAR, the UK luxury carmaker, has developed a prototype two-stroke engine
which might enter production in the next decade.
The surprise disclosure of the project represents a pioneering step among
European luxury carmakers. Several of the leading volume carmakers are
developing two-stroke engines for small cars.
Jaguar, a subsidiary of Ford of the US, said yesterday that development of
the compact and lightweight V6 engine was the result of a 4 1/2 -year
research programme. Its engineers have worked with Orbital Engine of
Australia, the company that leads the development of two-stroke technology,
and with Queen's University, Belfast.
Mr Ron Lee, Jaguar manager of engine development, said the prototype
3.2-litre V6 was 40 per cent lighter than a comparable 12-cylinder engine
but could give the same output.
The company's present engine ranges comprise a 5.3-litre V12 and 4.0-litre
and 3.2-litre six-cylinder engines.
It is developing a V8 engine range, codenamed AJ26, which is planned for
launch in 1996. Jaguar is expected to decide this summer whether the new
engine will be made at one of its existing Midlands sites or at a Ford
engine plant.
Jaguar said that the next stage in the two-stroke engine project would be a
full-scale development programme in Australia with Orbital.
The company said it aimed to produce a 350 brake horsepower demonstrator
engine in the next two years. Jaguar's work has included the performance
testing of a three-cylinder development engine.
According to the company, two-stroke engines might offer significant
benefits to luxury carmakers because they would be substantially lighter and
much more fuel-efficient than the present generation of large car engines.
</TEXT>
