FT  20 MAY 92 / BBC offers rise below inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC HAS angered unions by offering more than 25,000 staff an annual pay
rise below the current rate of inflation.
The corporation's offer for the year from the beginning of August is 3.7 per
cent, with a guarantee that nobody will receive a rise worth less than
Pounds 300. There is also a Pounds 75 increase in the London allowance,
bringing it to Pounds 2,190. The deal would cost Pounds 21.5m a year on the
BBC's pay bill of Pounds 590m.
The pay offer, which applies to members of the Bectu broadcasting union, the
NUJ journalists' union and the AEEU electricians' union, comes on the eve of
a BBC governors and top management conference to consider the corporation's
future role.
Bectu, which represents about 14,000 BBC staff, asked for 3 percentage
points more than inflation - at present 4.3 per cent - and a minimum salary
of Pounds 7,500. Mr Neil Fraser, head of BBC Radio Scotland, is leaving the
corporation after 24 years 'to pursue other programme interests', it was
announced yesterday.
