<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 92 / Channel 5 bidding row returns to High Court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEGAL battle between Five TV and TV-am over their planned bids for the
Channel 5 franchise returns to the High Court today amid considerable
bitterness.
Mr Bruce Gyngell, chairman of TV-am, believes the integrity of the breakfast
television company has been tarnished and is determined to pursue the issue
for as long as it takes to clear the company's name.
On May 5, Five TV issued a writ against TV-am, which is leading a consortium
called The Entertainment Channel, for alleged breach of contract. Five TV,
whose shareholders include Mr Moses Znaimer, founder of City TV in Toronto,
said TV-am had signed a confidentiality and exclusivity deal preventing it
from bidding for Channel 5 with anyone else.
Five TV was horrified when TV-am signed an agreement to bid for the
franchise in a consortium including Time Warner, the international media
company, and Mr Conrad Black's Daily Telegraph group. It meant that a rival
was in possession of most of Five TV's confidential plans.
Mr Gyngell emphasised that Mr Stratis Zographos, his finance director, had
signed what he took to be a normal confidentiality agreement and had not
noticed a line blocking any investment in a rival Channel 5 bidder.
Mr Gyngell has denounced the clause as a 'restraint on trade', although on
May 8 in the High Court TV-am gave an undertaking that it would give Five TV
notice before it concluded any agreement to bid for Channel 5.
The legal action is delaying any serious attempts at bringing together the
rivals to form a single consortium, which would almost certainly be in a
position to bid the minimum Pounds 1,000 a year for the franchise.
In the Five TV camp are Thames Television, Sony Entertainment, the parent of
Columbia and Tristar Pictures, and CanWest, an international broadcaster.
Several leading shareholders in the two consortia believe the start-up costs
are so high that Channel 5 will be viable only if any bid is uncontested.
Apart from the legal action, there is a gulf between the programme plans of
the two groups, with Five TV placing greater emphasis on local news and The
Entertainment Channel thinking more in terms of a single national channel.
As soon as the two sides leave the High Court, the talking may start in
earnest before the deadline of July 5.
</TEXT>
